<FIRST>r a AM-AbortionBombing     10-04 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Bombing,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Bomber Released from Prison, Second Set for November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two men who bombed three abortion
facilities here on Christmas Day 1984 is free and the other is
scheduled to be paroled next month, federal officials said
Wednesday.
   James Simmons and Matthew Goldsby, both 26 and from the
Cantonment community north of Pensacola, have served about half of
the 10-year prison sentences they received for the Christmas Day
bombings.
   The bombings in this Florida Panhandle city, followed by three
more in the Washington, D.C., area the next week, refocused
national attention on the abortion issue.
   Simmons was transferred from the Tallahassee Federal
Correctional Institution to a work-release program in Pensacola a
couple months ago.
   He was released from there 59 days early on Sept. 25 under the
federal curfew parole program, said Tom Kowalski, regional
administrator for the U.S. Parole Commission in Atlanta.
   Although free, he must observe a curfew until his regular parole
date of Nov. 28, Kowalski said.
   Goldsby is scheduled for release Nov. 21. His initial release
date was May 21, 1990, but George Rast, the regional parole
commissioner, moved it up two years ago because Goldsby was
credited with superior program achievement, which could include
good conduct, work performance and educational advancement.
   Simmons, a glass company employee, and Goldsby, a construction
worker, were convicted of planting homemade pipe bombs at a clinic
and two doctors' offices where abortions were performed. The
building in which one office was located was demolished by the
explosion and ensuing fire and the other office was seriously
damaged.
   Damage at the clinic, The Ladies Center, was less severe and it
soon reopened, becoming the target of numerous anti-abortion
demonstrations.
   One doctor at the bombed-out clinic retired and the other
discontinued abortions because insurance companies refused to cover
his new office, fearing it also might be attacked as long as he
continued that part of his practice.
   Simmons' wife, Kathren, and Goldsby's former fiance, Kay
Wiggins, were convicted on conspiracy charges and placed on
probation.
   All four had attended the First Assembly of God Church in
Pensacola and said the two men were driven by religious conviction.
   Feminist leaders criticized the sentences are being too lenient
to begin with. The terms were the shortest given to people
convicted of bombing or torching abortion clinics up to that time.
   The case drew wide public attention when it went to trial in
April 1985 with defense lawyers portraying their clients as
idealistic ``knights in shining armor'' or ``Tom Sawyer and Huck
Finn.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
