<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2356EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CrippledBomber 3rdLd-Writethru a0820 10-04 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crippled Bomber, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0820,0819</SECOND>
<HEAD>B-1B Lands Safely After Jammed Nose Gear Forces Transcontinental
Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, `The crippled ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
crew IDs, CORRECT that Edwards AFB is 1,200, sted 2,000, miles from Dyess.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ABI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A B-1B bomber with
crippled landing gear flew halfway across the continent Wednesday
and made a successful touchdown on the Mojave Desert lake bed where
the space shuttle lands.
   The $280 million aircraft, with its four-member crew unable to
unlock its nose landing gear, refueled in the air and landed at
6:15 p.m. after 11{ hours in the air that began as a training
flight in Texas.
   The big bomber trailed a plume of dust as it rolled down the
12-mile-long runway after touchdown, slowly lowering onto its nose.
   ``There were no injuries,'' said Tech. Sgt. Donn Clarius, a
spokesman at Edwards Air Force Base. ``The flight crew came out
just fine.
   ``There was no fire or explosion or anything.''
   He said the bomber suffered some damage, which was being
assessed by ground crews as darkness fell.
   Dale Punter, an aerospace buff who monitors military frequencies
from his home in Lancaster, listened to radio traffic between the
pilots and controllers.
   Just before touching down the pilot said, ``It's been a great
day for flying, except for a few glitches,'' Punter reported.
   Just after the landing, Punter said he heard the pilot say, ``It
was real nice. Structure looking good.''
   During the landing, the massive bomber skidded on its nose for
more than half a minute, yet it did not break up. No flames were
seen.
   ``It's one of the safest areas to land,'' said base spokeswoman
Dottie Spiegelberg, adding that the hard clay surface means there
are no sparks and minimizes the chance of explosion or fire.
   The aircraft, flying out of Dyess Air Force Base in Texas,
wasn't carrying bombs. ``There are no nuclear weapons,'' said Lt.
Anu Sjaardema, an Edwards public affairs spokeswoman.
   An 18-unit disaster preparedness team was mobilized at Edwards,
including explosives experts, a mortuary services officer, an
environmental officer and fire department personnel, the lieutenant
said.
   ``They route a lot of emergencies to our lake bed, both military
and civilian. We have a team to respond to that all the time,''
said Sjaardema.
   The flight crew was Capt. Jeffrey K. Beene, 30, aircraft
commander, of the 337th Bombardment Squadron at Dyess; Capt. Vernon
B. Benton, 30, co-pilot; Capt. Robert H. Hendricks, 31, offensive
systems officer and Lt. Col. Joseph G. Day, 38, an instructor and
offensive systems officer with the 338th Combat Crew Training
Squadron.
   The crippled plane was refueled by a tanker plane before flying
to Edwards, about 1,200 miles away.
   The B-1B, with a maximum speed of 1,000 mph and range of more
than 7,000 miles, is 147 feet long and 137 feet wide when its
swing-wings are extended. It weighs 477,000 pounds when fully
fueled and armed.
   Maj. Mary Beth Kilgore at Dyess said the plane started circling
Dyess at about 9:30 a.m. PDT. It left for California five hours
later.
   Mechanics from Dyess and the plane's manufacturer, Rockwell
International, worked with the plane's crew to try get the nose
gear down. The plane's rear wheels were down while it circled
Dyess, located at the western edge of Abilene, a city of 100,000 in
west Texas.
   The plane took off from Dyess at 6:38 a.m. PDT on a training
mission.
   The plane was originally tested at Edwards AFB and Ms. Kilgore
said Dyess officials believed someone there could figure out the
problem.
   Dyess is one of four bases in the United States where B-1
bombers are stationed.
   In March 1986, the variable-sweep wings became stuck on the
second production model of the B-1B during a training flight out of
Dyess AFB. The pilots successfully made a high-speed landing at
Edwards when the wings were swept back. The plane stopped after
using 13,000 feet of runway.
   There have been three B-1B crashes and the crash of a B-1
prototype. The most recent crash was in November 1988 at Ellsworth
Air Force Base in South Dakota. All four crew members ejected
safely.
   The three crashes left the Air Force with 97 of the B1-B planes,
the first bomber added to Strategic Air Command in about 25 years.
Production has been completed, for $20.5 billion. The plane was
killed by President Carter in 1977 and resurrected by President
Reagan in 1981.
   In February, the GAO said problems persist in performance of the
plane _ range and payload _ and fuel leaks probably could not be
corrected. Fixes could cost $400 million per aircraft if the Air
Force decided to do them all, the GAO said.
</TEXT>
