<FIRST>u w AM-BogotaNewspaper     10-04 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bogota Newspaper,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombed El Espectador Now Losing Money, Newspaper President Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bogota newspaper that was bombed bcause of
its coverage of Colombia's drug trade is now losing money and may
have to close, its president is quoted as saying.
   A car bomb that exploded near the offices of El Espectador on
Sept. 2 did $2.5 million worth of damage, according to the
president, Luis Cano, in remarks at a luncheon with editors and
reporters of The Washington Post on Wednesday.
   A report on the luncheon appeared in Thursday editions of the
Post.
   Advertisers have been threatened, and some smaller ones have
left the newspaper, Cano said. But among employees, ``no one
abandoned the paper,'' he said.
   ``If we don't receive some support, we cannot continue,'' Cano
was quoted as saying.
   Cano said his company, which employs about 1,000 people and
publishes the second-largest daily in Colombia with a circulation
of 200,000, is seeking a long-term, low-interest loan from
Colombia's central bank.
   He is touring the United States, in part to seek support from
news organizations.
</TEXT>
