<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Moslems     10-04 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Moslems,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Difficulties, Pope Strives for Better Relations with Moslems</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his travels to Africa and Asia, his
peace initiatives and calls to forget the painful past, Pope John
Paul II has made unprecedented openings to the Moslem world.
   But the road to dialogue is dotted with obstacles, and the
Vatican is keeping a wary eye on challenges to the church in
Islamic countries.
   Over the past two decades, and especially during John Paul's
11-year pontificate, the Roman Catholic Church has sought to erase
the image of medieval crusades fought in the name of faith.
   ``Moslems and Christians have generally understood each other
badly and sometimes, in the past, have exhausted each other in
polemics and wars,'' he said in Morocco four years ago as the first
pontiff to set foot on Arab soil as an official state guest.
   He said dialogue was essential between the Catholic church and
Islam, the two largest religious groups in the world.
   But the spread of Moslem fundamentalism has raised alarm,
especially for isolated minority communities of Christians. The
danger of Moslem-Christian rivalries has been dramatized by the
bloodshed in Lebanon.
   The pope's concern over the Lebanon fighting recently led him to
make the first direct appeal by a pontiff to the Islamic world,
saying there can be no winners in such a struggle.
   He also repeated his desire to visit the country torn by 14
years of civil war, despite threats against him from Moslem
extremists.
   On Oct. 9, John Paul begins a visit to Indonesia, the world's
largest Moslem country with an estimated 140 million Moslems and a
tiny Roman Catholic minority of 5 million. He will be there until
Oct. 14.
   The pope has previously stopped in such predominantly Islamic
countries as Turkey and Bangladesh as well as several African
countries with large Moslem populations.
   The era of dialogue was spurred by the Second Vatican Council,
which also opened the way to improved relations between Catholics
and Jews.
   ``Upon the Moslems, too, the church looks with esteem,'' said
the 1965 declaration Nostra Aetate. ``They adore one God, living
and enduring, merciful, and all powerful, maker of heaven and earth
and speaker to men.''
   Vatican officials are pleased that its efforts have led to
stepped-up exchanges of visits between church representatives and
Moslem theologians.
   The Vatican also maintains diplomatic relations with a number of
predominantly Islamic countries, including Egypt, Iraq, Syria,
Iran, Turkey and Indonesia.
   John Paul's calls for a homeland for the Palestinians have won
him appreciation in the Moslem world while his meetings with PLO
leader Yasser Arafat drew protests from Israel, a country with
which the Vatican has refused to establish formal diplomatic
relations.
   The church has generally been cautious to avoid offending Moslem
sensibilities. Officials note that on Islamic issues, it often has
to deal with governments, not religious leaders.
   ``It's something like the church in Eastern Europe, where
diplomacy is the best method. We like to do things quietly,'' said
a Vatican official speaking on the usual rule of anonymity.
   During the height of the fury earlier this year over Salman
Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' the Vatican's newspaper
said millions of Moslems had found the novel offensive. It
condemned ``whatever is irreverent and blasphemous'' in the book
but said the author should not be killed, as the late Iranian
leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, demanded.
   According to church surveys, the amount of religious liberty and
pluralism varies considerably in the Moslem world.
   In some cases, the Catholic minorities ``live in a state of
tension and of concern at the possibility of new restrictions,''
said Fides, a press service at the Vatican's missionary office.
   The Vatican is worried about the spread of Moslem fundamentalism
in countries such as Sudan ad in Nigeria, where rivalries between
Christians and Moslems led to the burning of churches and mosques
in the northern part of the country in 1987.
   In an unusual public criticism, the Vatican in a major document
on racism issued in February condemned the imposition of the
Sharia, or Islamic law, on non-Moslems.
   Catholicism's fastest growing church is in Africa, but it is
subject to special pressures.
   During a visit to Rwanda in 1982, Libyan leader Col. Moammar
Gadhafi declared ``Africa is not Christian'' and called for a holy
war to help spread Islam on the continent.
   Vatican officials consider Indonesia a generally tolerant
country, but Indonesian Catholics say they are worried about a
government bill presented to Parliament that would give legal
recognition to several hundred Islamic courts.
   Religion and politics are also intertwined on East Timor, a
former Portuguese colony with a large Catholic population forcibly
annexed by Indonesia in 1976. Church officials report that a number
of Moslems have been converting to Catholicism as a political
statement of their opposition to Indonesian rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
