<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Alexander     10-04 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Alexander,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>H.G. Alexander, Intermediary for British-Indian Talks, Dies at 100</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horace G. Alexander, a Quaker who served as
an intermediary between Mahatma Gandhi and the British government
during India's struggle for freedom, has died. He was 100.
   Alexander died of natural causes Saturday at Crosslands
Retirement Community in Kennett Square, a suburb of Philadelphia,
said his stepdaughter, Cecilia Bradbeer Sibinga.
   Gandhi once described Alexander as ``British in nationality but
Indian in heart.'' Alexander was with Gandhi in Calcutta Aug. 15,
1947, when India gained its freedom from the United Kingdom.
   In 1984, India honored Alexander for his contribution by
awarding him one of the country's highest decorations, the Padma
Bhushan Award, roughly translated as ``outstanding human being.''
   Two years after his first wife, Olive Garaham, died in 1943,
Alexander made his first visit to the United States. He moved to
Swarthmore with his second wife, Rebecca Biddle Bradbeer, in 1969.
   In a 1984 interview, Alexander said he continued to believe in
the non-violent principles of Gandhi.
   ``I try to be hopeful about the future, but it is rather
difficult, isn't it? But there are a lot of people in the world who
are trying to take non-violence seriously, so maybe in the course
of time, it will begin to affect national policy,'' he said.
   ``People have a great capacity for good things as well as evil
things, and I suppose each of us has to go on doing the little bit
he can.''
   In addition to his stepdaughter and second wife, Alexander is
survived by a son, James Biddle Bradbeer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
