<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     10-04 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Different Cast, But `Different World' Premieres in Top 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television viewers were indifferent to cast
changes in ``A Different World'' as the NBC comedy series without
Cosby kid Lisa Bonet placed fourth in the latest A.C. Nielsen Co.
ratings.
   ABC's ``Roseanne,'' elbowed aside the previous week by the
season premiere of ``The Cosby Show,'' regained first place and
``Cosby,'' with Miss Bonet back in the family fold, went to No. 2.
   ``Cheers'' was rated third, followed by the season premiere of
``A Different World'' and ``The Golden Girls,'' all on NBC. CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote''' was in sixth place, followed by the season
premiere of NBC's ``Empty Nest.''
   A preview showing of ABC's ``Living Dolls'' on Tuesday night
earned eighth place in the ratings.
   ``Dear John'' on NBC was No. 9, and the season premiere of CBS'
``60 Minutes'' was in 10th place.
   NBC remained the top network for the 67th week in a row. Its
average prime-time rating last week was 14.6 with a 25 average
share. ABC's averages were a 13.4 rating and 23 share and CBS 12.9
and 22.
   The ratings are the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million
homes with television sets in the United States. The share is the
percentage of the sets in use.
   The share for all three networks last week was 69.4, down from
the previous week's 72.
   In Sunday night movie competition, ``The CBS Sunday Movie''
narrowly beat ``Night Walk,'' a mystery starring Robert Urich and
Lesley-Anne Down. The show had a 16.3 rating and 27 share for 21st
place.
   In 22nd place was ``The ABC Sunday Night Movie,'' ``Indiana
Jones and the Temple of Doom.'' Long available on videocassette,
the broadcast of the film nonetheless drew a 16.1 rating and a 27
share.
   But ``Sweet Bird of Youth,'' a broadcast version of the
Tennessee Williams play starring Elizabeth Taylor and Mark Harmon
came in at No. 40 for the ``NBC Sunday Night Movie.'' The
television movie had a 13 rating and a 21 share.
   Comic Jackie Mason's ``Chicken Soup'' on ABC went from No. 14 to
11th place in the ratings, while another ABC show, ``Doogie Howser,
M.D.,'' went up six notches from 33rd to 27th place in its regular
time slot.
   The highest rated Fox Broadcasting Co. show was ``Married...With
Children,' in 50th place.
   In the news category, ``The CBS Evening News'' took first place
with a weekly average rating of 9.7, followed by ``ABC World News
Tonight'' with 9.6 and ``NBC Nightly News'' with 9.3.
</TEXT>
