<FIRST>r i PM-Refugees-Embassy     10-04 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees-Embassy,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defying Police, Hundreds Make Desperate Sprint For Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fearing they might miss the last
train to the West, hundreds of East Germans scuffled with
Czechoslovak police to get to the West German Embassy. Many
refugees were injured.
   The desperate struggle came hours before East Germany sought to
curb the exodus of refugees on Tuesday, banning its citizens from
traveling to Czechoslovakia without a visa.
   However, East Germany also decided Tuesday to permit the about
10,000 East Germans around the embassy compound to emigrate to the
West.
   Hundreds of East Germans overturned a police barricade and
scaled facades, rooftops or a 6-foot spiked fence in an effort to
reach the crowded embassy compound, which had been closed earlier
Tuesday.
   Police swung their nightsticks and ``clubbed like mad,'' one
Czechoslovak witness reported. Many refugees were left
blood-spattered.
   More people from the waiting crowd surged toward where the
beatings took place. Refugees quickly built ``a human ladder'' to
help many clear the fence, witnesses said.
   Some became caught on the fence's sharp spikes, while others
jumped or fell head-first to the ground. Some were later seen lying
unconscious inside the compound, the witnesses said.
   Outside the embassy, families with small children were unable to
get inside.
   ``This is pandemonium,'' said a Red Cross assistant handling
injured refugees on the embassy grounds.
   Thousands of other East Germans had packed into the embassy
grounds earlier, and Red Cross officials feared sanitation problems.
   Later Tuesday, young men were seen climbing the embassy facade
from a truck. Refugees inside the compound pulled them in through
windows.
   The crowd of East Germans flocking to the embassy continued to
swell during the day. More newcomers joined them after dark,
shivering in freezing weather as their promised departure by East
German trains was delayed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
