<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of Grace Jones on charges of
possessing less than $18 worth of cocaine was postponed for the
fifth time since her April arrest, and the singer-actress said the
delays are hurting her career.
   ``I had to go on television in Europe to refute newspaper
reports which say I was a fugitive from Jamaica,'' she said, adding
that Revlon commercials in which she appears have been taken off
the air pending the outcome of the trial.
   Ms. Jones, who traveled from Los Angeles to her homeland only to
find the prosecutor failed to show up Tuesday, complained
vehemently of the cost of returning to the Caribbean island for
each new trial date. She traveled from Paris, Madrid and Rome for
previous trial dates that were postponed because prosecutors were
not familiar with the case, judges failed to show up or witnesses
were missing.
   Ms. Jones is charged with possessing 0.007 ounce of cocaine
while vacationing in Kingston. A new trial was set for Oct. 26.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moving on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former baseball star Steve Garvey's ex-wife,
Cynthia, was released from jail a day after refusing him
court-ordered visits with their two daughters.
   A sobbing Ms. Garvey refused to speak to reporters as she left
the Sybil Brand Institute on Tuesday with her lawyer. The state's
2nd Court of Appeals said the Superior Court ``abused its
discretion'' by not granting bail and ordering her to jail for
contempt of court.
   ``It remains her position that she is not guilty of contempt and
she intends to continue defending herself,'' said attorney Gerald
Margolis.
   Superior Court Judge Frances Rothschild convicted Ms. Garvey of
43 counts of contempt for violating a December 1988 order requiring
daughters Whitney, 13, and Krisha, 14, to spend every Tuesday
afternoon and two weekends a month with their father. Rothschild
ordered her to spend five days in jail and set a Nov. 3 hearing on
a sentence of up to 126 days in jail and two years' probation.
   The Garveys were divorced in 1981 and Garvey recently remarried.
Earlier this year, he admitted fathering the children of two other
women, one of whom is suing him.
   Garvey's attorney, Dennis Wasser, said Garvey was ``somewhere in
Southern California'' with the daughters and would stay with them
through the week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAKE OSWEGO, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh has adopted a
new name _ Osho _ and given his followers a change of habit.
   Osho is a Japanese word that means ``the whole man, the fully
awakened one and respectfully symbolizes a man of peace, grace and
love upon whom Existence is showering all its blessings from every
direction,'' according to a statement from the sect's Oregon press
service dated Sept. 15 and received in the mail Tuesday.
   Disciples also have begun wearing maroon robes during the day
and white robes during evening meditations at the commune in Pune,
India, the release said. In the years when the commune was based in
Oregon, Rajneeshees wore various shades of red, but the 58-year-old
guru later advised them to drop the practice to avoid harassment
and discrimination.
   The self-described ``rich man's guru,'' who teaches meditation
as a means to enlightenment, returned to India four years ago after
pleading guilty to U.S. immigration charges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GAITHERSBURG, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles says playing polo renews
his mental and physical strength and is good for his image, but he
won't force his sons to play the game.
   ``I do believe it's very important to be seen not to be a
chicken, to be leading from the front, showing you're prepared to
do perhaps some of the more dangerous things,'' the heir to the
British throne said in an interview in Polo Life magazine, a
semiannual publication of Fleet Street Publishing Corp. of
Gaithersburg.
   He says he almost never loses his temper in a match but admits
to some violations of the Queen's English: ``I swear occasionally,
not too loud. On the whole, I remain reasonable.''
   Charles says he hopes his two young sons take up the sport,
although he won't force them to play the game.
   ``What I've really got to do is find an old pony that they can
ride around and try and hit the ball. They've got little sticks and
occasionally we potter about. Yes, it would be lovely if they could
do it because it's lots of fun playing with your own children.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mick Jagger mixed a little politics into his rock
'n' roll schedule by visiting the Statehouse for a chat with Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis.
   ``He asked me what I thought of his stuff, and I told him it's
only rock 'n' roll and I like it,'' the governor said Tuesday.
   Clad in a turquoise green suitcoat and clutching a folder, the
46-year-old lead singer of the Rolling Stones looked surprised to
find about 160 people crowding the hall outside the governor's
office to catch a glimpse of him.
   Asked what he and Dukakis talked about, Jagger replied, ``A
little about gun control.''
   The state House on Monday gave overwhelming initial approval to
a home-rule petition that would ban assault weapons from the city
of Boston. ``I think it's a start,'' Jagger said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Pat Cooper says his caustic
remarks may have cost him jobs, friendships and family, but he says
he is happy.
   Cooper's act, which angrily criticizes the world, has gained
popularity with a new generation. At 50, he is playing comedy
clubs, the venues of the younger comedians. He is a regular guest
on radio's ``The Howard Stern Show.'' He headlines at Trump Castle
this weekend.
   For the past 10 years, Cooper has hustled jobs for himself in a
business he got into out of necessity, not choice, he said.
   ``I did two weeks of high school and went to work because, in my
family, you had to bring the money,'' the Brooklyn-born Cooper
said. ``They didn't say, `I love you,' or `hug and kiss you.' They
only kissed the veal cutlet because that cost a lot of money.''
</TEXT>
