<FIRST>r w PM-HispanicHealth     10-04 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hispanic Health,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Groups Dispute Report on Hispanic Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Hispanic group and the alcohol and
tobacco industries are dismissing claims that beer, cigarette and
fast-food ads are jeopardizing Latinos' health.
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest said in a
publication called ``Marketing Disease to Hispanics'' that Latinos
suffer from an increasing number of health problems related to
drinking, smoking and high-fat fast foods.
   The Beer Institute, a trade association, said Tuesday's report
had no scientific basis and rejected suggestions that the beer
industry is promoting alcoholism among Hispanics.
   Institute president James Sanders said money contributed by the
industry to the Hispanic community benefits public health, literacy
and cultural programs as well as economic development.
   ``Problems of nutrition and substance abuse in the Hispanic
community are real, and they deserve real action and real
solutions,'' Sanders said. ``Taking down billboards and shuttering
hamburger stands won't help these very real problems.''
   Anheuser-Busch spokesman Jesse Aguirre said his company's
advertising promotes responsible beer drinking and discourages
alcohol abuse. He called the report ``irresponsible, patronizing.''
   It ``assumes that Hispanic American citizens cannot make sound,
educated consumer decisions just like other segments of the
American public,'' Aguirre said.
   Walker Merryman, vice president of the Tobacco Institute, a
trade association for the cigarette industry, agreed: ``Anybody who
sees an advertisement for a product is capable of making a decision
about whether to use it.''
   Dr. Carlos Molina, a member of the center's board and president
of the Latino Caucus of the American Public Health Association,
said Hispanic groups have been silent on the issue largely because
they receive about $1 million a year from alcohol, tobacco and
``junk-food'' companies.
   ``That support ... muzzles our national leaders on vital health
issues,'' he said.
   However, the National Council of La Raza, a leading non-profit
Hispanic service organization with affiliates in 26 states,
rejected that conclusion. Susan Herrera, vice president of the
council, estimated the group gets 2 percent of its funding from
beer or tobacco companies.
   ``We don't feel compromised,'' she said. ``If we can't take
people's money and do what we need to do then we shouldn't have any
business taking that money.''
   The council has ``been in the business of drug and alcohol abuse
programs, and we're still operating them,'' she said.
   The report cites studies showing:
   _Men of Mexican heritage have a 40 percent higher risk of death
due to cirrhosis of the liver than white men.
   _In Colorado, lung cancer rates among Hispanic men increased 132
percent between 1970 and 1980, compared with a 12 percent increase
among white men. In New Mexico, lung cancer deaths nearly tripled
for Hispanic men from 1958 to 1982, while doubling for white men.
   _Obesity, linked to adult-onset diabetes, among Hispanic women
over age 18 was about 25 percent more prevalent than among white
women.
   The report calls for higher excise taxes on alcoholic beverages
and cigarettes, a ban on cigarette vending machines and a ban on
all alcoholic beverages and cigarette advertising that links those
products with health and youthfulness.
   The Center for Science in the Public Interest is a non-profit
organization that focuses on health and nutrition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-APME     10-04 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-APME,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers Urged to Develop ``Customer Obsession''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newspaper industry, faced with a
decline in readership, must develop ``customer obsession'' to
reverse the slide, the president of the Associated Press Managing
Editors told the APME convention.
   ``Readership surveys can be useful, but they aren't enough,''
said Paul Janensch, editor and general manager of The Rockland
Journal-News in New York City's suburban Rockland County, N.Y.
``Surveys can't halt sliding readership unless the editor and the
editor's staff are fanatical about getting close to the community.''
   Opening the annual APME convention on Tuesday, Janensch said
steadily declining readership ``confronts us with the most serious
problem facing newspapers today'' and that it even hits markets
where the economy is booming.
   ``If you are lucky enough to be in a growing market and your
circulation is going up, you may think you don't have a problem,''
he said.
   ``Wrong. Even where circulation is going up, net newspaper
penetration is going down. There are no exceptions.''
   ``In 1967, about 73 percent of U.S. adults said they read a
newspaper every day,'' he said. ``Last year, the number was down to
51 percent.''
   ``Call it what you will _ customer obsession, putting the reader
first, serving the constituents _ we must do it better,'' Janensch
said. ``I firmly believe that if we build a strong rapport with our
communities, we will prosper. If we don't, we will fade away.''
   While many are captivated by national news and big-name events,
most of America's newspapers survive by providing residents of the
community with information they need in their daily lives, he said.
   ``Is your newspaper first and foremost a local newspaper?''
asked Janensch. ``Do you care as much about the expansion of a
local business as you do about the national trade deficit?''
   In addition to building community ties, Janensch said, a
newspaper's staff must reflect the paper's market.
   ``Does your staff at all levels reflect the racial and ethnic
diversity of your target readership?'' he asked the editors. ``Are
about half of your staffers women? Do your staffers have roots in
the community?''
   Also as the convention opened, a military historian dismissed
suggestions that negative reporting of the Vietnam War damaged the
war effort. Accounts of the Vietnam War often served as a warning
flag for top commanders, who often weren't aware of problems in the
field, said William Hammond, a historian at the Army Center of
Military History in Washington.
   ``Sometimes the commander high up the chain of command is the
last one to find out anything,'' Hammond said.
   ``In this case, media coverage actually extended the vision of
the commander, and he was able to make a response that was very
important to the overall goal of the American military in
Vietnam,'' he added.
   Major stories that would have bruised the Army's image went
largely unreported, including the persistent problems of the M-16,
the primary infantry weapon used in the war, he said.
   Far from aiding the war effort, he said, the lack of reporting
left officials with little incentive to improve.
   ``The press in Vietnam did not pick up the story with any
consistency,'' Hammond said. ``What happened? The military never
had any kind of a prod to do much about repairing the weapon.''
   His book ``The Military and the Media'' stirred controversy when
he said that, overall, news accounts of the Vietnam War gave a
better picture of that conflict than official reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
