<FIRST>r w PM-Marines-RapeSlogan     10-04 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marines-Rape Slogan,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marines Investigating Use of Rape Slogan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps says a drill instructor is
responsible for the slogan ``kill, rape, pillage, burn'' used by a
group of recruits during basic training at Parris Island, S.C.
   ``This is not a normal occurrence and I would consider this an
isolated incident,'' Capt. J.R. Mill, public affairs officer at
Parris Island, said Tuesday.
   The investigation began after Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
received a photograph of a recently graduated platoon that showed
recruits holding a sign with the slogan and a skull and crossbones.
   Another sign in the picture showed a naked woman.
   Mill said the signs ``were done in bad taste, which represents
neither the policy nor the philosophy of this command or the United
States Marine Corps and we are taking corrective action concerning
this situation.''
   He said the signs ``were made under the supervision and approval
of a drill instructor.''
   The photograph identifies the drill instructor in charge as
Staff Sgt. Kirkpatrick.
   The public affairs office said there was a Staff Sgt. Brian
Kirkpatrick on the base. There was no answer at Kirkpatrick's
office phone Tuesday.
   ``It's outrageous. The Marines ought to be ashamed,'' said
McCain, a highly decorated retired Navy captain who spent 5{ years
as a prisoner of war in North Vietnam.
   The 8x10 color, formal photograph showed the men standing at
attention on risers with the officers who trained them in the
foreground. The parents of one of the recruits sent McCain the
photo Monday.
   As part of training, recruits often make signs or pennants with
designs and slogans, but Mill said the ``kill, rape, pillage,
burn'' slogan should not have been condoned.
   Recruits, he said, are schooled in a code of conduct that has
strict rules about humane treatment of civilians, the enemy and
property.
   ``I was in the service 22 years and never saw anything like
this,'' said McCain, blaming the officers in charge. ``It shows a
lack of supervision. We are paying those officers with taxpayers
dollars. We want them to be honorable fighting men.''
   After receiving the photograph, McCain wrote to Marine
Commandant Gen. Alfred Gray.
   ``It is my feeling that ... the signs that the recruits are
holding are inappropriate and do violate the values which Americans
expect their Marines to carry with them in defense of the nation,''
McCain wrote.
   ``While platoon mottoes are important to motivation and morale
in the boot camp environment, the high standards of the Marine
Corps demands a philosophy, a set of values, a dedication and a
resolve with which the enclosed photograph is simply incompatible.''
   McCain asked Gray to ensure that the commanders of the platoon
in the photograph ``understand and embrace proper Marine Corps
values.''
   McCain also asked Gray to make sure the recruits in the
photograph were contacted and ``that they understand why this type
of conduct is inconsistent with the Marine Corps values and
tradition.''
</TEXT>
