<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ObsceneArt     10-04 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obscene Art,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Final Congressional Passage Imminent on Obscene Art Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Uncertain whether Senate will vote today on legislation, top
prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil libertarians and members of the arts
community seem to be accepting House-passed limitations on federal
aid to ``obscene'' art as restrictions they can accept.
   The House voted 381-41 Tuesday to send the Senate a spending
bill containing the guidelines after adopting them on a voice vote.
Senate approval is expected this week, and President Bush is
expected to sign the measure.
   The restrictions are a retreat from a stricter ban that Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and other conservatives fought for over the
last three months.
   The language the House sent the Senate, worked out last week by
House-Senate negotiators, bars the National Endowment for the Arts
and the National Endowment for the Humanities from issuing grants
for exhibitions they consider ``obscene.''
   Included are works depicting sadomasochism, homoeroticism,
sexual exploitation of children or individuals engaged in sex acts.
   To deny financing, endowment officials must also find a work
lacks ``serious literary, artistic, political or scientific value.''
   Helms had sought to prohibit federal aid for obscene or indecent
art, and for works offensive to a religion, ethnic group, race, age
group or the disabled.
   ``Given the uproar and general mood these days, probably the
outcome is something we could live with,'' Geoffrey Platt Jr.,
lobbyist for the American Association of Museums, said Tuesday.
   ``When one melds together principle and politics here, the
ultimate result was gratifying,'' said James F. Fitzpatrick,
president of the Washington Project for the Arts.
   Fitzpatrick's organization is among those that have exhibited
one of the shows that sparked the conservative attempts to impose
restrictions on federal arts assistance. It included photographs,
by the late Robert Mapplethorpe, of homosexual acts and of children
in erotic poses.
   The other show contained a photograph by Andres Serrano of a
Christ figure in a jar of urine.
   First Amendment lawyer Floyd Abrams and American Civil Liberties
Union attorney Barry Lynn said they believed the language is the
first time government aid to art would be limited based on a work's
content.
   ``But it's a compromise, and it's a vast improvement over the
initial language,'' Lynn said.
   ``We reached an agreement that if I had my druthers I'd rather
not have seen,'' conceded Rep. Sidney Yates, D-Ill., who led the
bargaining for the opponents of Helms' proposal. ``But concessions
had to be made.''
   The restrictions would last one year while a newly created
commission studies endowment procedures and considers if permanent
standards should be imposed for federally supported art.
   ``The NEA and the institutions it supports should have higher
standards than the local porno store,'' said Rep. Dana Rohrabacher,
R-Calif., who lost a fight in July to eliminate the NEA's $170
million budget.
   The legislation also requires the NEA to notify Congress 30 days
before issuing grants to the Southeastern Center for Contemporary
Art in Winston-Salem, N.C., which showed the Serrano picture, and
the Institute for Contemporary Art at the University of
Pennsylvania, which exhibited the Mapplethorpe photographs.
   Jack Duncan, counsel to the American Council for the Arts,
called that provision ``a method of intimidation.'' The NEA spent
$45,000 for the two exhibits.
   Many lawmakers had privately expressed a desire to adopt some
restrictions, fearing failure to do so would leave them vulnerable
to election opponents accusing them of favoring pornography.
   After the July fight on Rohrabacher's proposal, the Republican
National Committee sent press releases to the districts of 21
Democrats, accusing them of supporting ``sexually explicit and
anti-religious works of art.''
   The NEA is required by law to support materials that ``in the
experts' view foster excellence, are reflective of exceptional
talent, and have significant literary, scholarly, cultural or
artistic merit.''
   The $11.2 billion measure for the Interior Department, cultural
and other programs is for fiscal 1990, which began Sunday.
   The legislation also extends for another year a ban on the
leasing of offshore tracts for oil and gas drilling; imposes new
restrictions on lobbyists who seek federal money for clients; and
allows lumber companies to cut timber on federally owned land in
the Northwest while protecting areas inhabited by the rare spotted
owl.
</TEXT>
