<FIRST>r a PM-HassleIndex     10-04 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hassle Index,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Travelers Traffic Woes Growing, Some Will Stay Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine of 10 Americans think the country's
traffic problems aren't getting any better, leading many people to
alter their travel plans, a survey said.
   ``Motorists' freedom of mobility is being restricted by
congested roads in all sections of this country and the problem is
not just limited to major urban areas,'' said Kay Aldous, vice
president for public and government affairs for the American
Automobile Association.
   ``Many suburban roads also are being affected,''
   The second annual ``hassle index,'' released Tuesday, was based
on a nationwide survey of 1,743 adults by the U.S. Travel Data
Center in Washington. The results were discussed at a conference in
Hollywood of the Travel Association of America.
   The study showed that 92 percent of drivers believe traffic is
worse or hasn't improved since last year, compared with 86 percent
who felt that way in 1988.
   Nine percent said they wouldn't travel because of congestion,
the same as last year.
   ``This has serious implications for the whole travel industry,''
said Jerry Cheske, a AAA spokesman.
   Forty-eight percent of motorists surveyed said local roads are
more congested than a year ago and 44 percent said it was unchanged.
   Five percent said congestion has eased and the rest were
undecided.
   The biggest concerns about traffic were in the West and
Northeast, where more than 95 percent of respondents said roads are
as bad or worse than last year. The figure for the Southeast was
only 86 percent.
   The survey, which gave no margin of error, found that 83 percent
of respondents who took a vacation trip 100 miles or more by car or
planned to take one this year felt auto travel was worse or at
least as bad, up from 80 percent in 1988.
   Sixty-seven percent said they left earlier to avoid traffic, up
from 59 percent. Twenty-nine percent drove at least 10 miles out of
their way, the same as last year.
   To ease traffic problems, the AAA recommended the federal
government release $10 billion in the Highway Trust Fund to
construct and improve roads, particularly interstate bypasses
around congested metropolitan areas.
   The ``hassle index'' is compiled from AAA's travel attitude
monitor, a report on auto and air transportation that will be
released later this year.
</TEXT>
