<FIRST>r w PM-AbortionOpponents     10-04 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Opponents,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Group Targets State Legislatures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the National Right to Life
Committee say they are stepping up efforts to persuade state
legislatures to restrict abortions.
   David O'Steen, executive director of the group, on Tuesday
rejected claims by pro-choice groups that their political strength
has increased since the Supreme Court ruling last spring allowed
greater leeway for state regulation of abortion.
   O'Steen, at a news conference concluding a two-day strategy
conference, said anti-abortion candidates have won seven of 10
special elections for state legislative seats since that ruling in
a Missouri case.
   Although some polls suggest majority support for abortions,
O'Steen argued that support is only for abortions under narrow
circumstances.
   ``Most Americans think ... abortion is wrong,'' he said.
   The group has prepared model bills that can be introduced by
state lawmakers. However, it declined to release copies of the
proposed state legislation.
   Leaders said the legislation would restrict abortions in a
number of ways, including ``as a form of birth control.'' It also
would call for parental consent in cases of minors seeking
abortions, detail a father's rights in an abortion decision, ban
the use of public funds and ban abortion used for gender selection.
   The broadest prohibition would involve abortions used for birth
control, a term that O'Steen contended describes the purpose behind
93 percent of all abortions.
   Burke Balch, state legislative director of the organization,
said the group would focus on a handful of states where abortion
could become an issue in legislatures during the remainder of 1989.
He said those states were Pennsylvania, Michigan, Florida,
Illinois. Texas and Ohio might also be targeted he said.
   Most state legislatures have already adjourned for the year.
</TEXT>
