<DOCNO> AP891004-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugLawyers Bjt   10-04 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Lawyers, Bjt,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Decisions, Crackdown Make Criminal Lawyers Rethink</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drug crackdown and a U.S. Supreme Court
decision allowing prosecutors to seize money and property earmarked
for attorneys' fees may chase some of the nation's top defense
lawyers out of criminal law.
   Racketeering laws, they complain, give the government so much
power to confiscate assets that the Sixth Amendment right to choose
one's own attorney may effectively vanish because suspects are left
penniless before trial.
   In June, the high court approved that power, ruling 5-4 that
prosecutors may even seize assets set aside to pay an attorney.
   The power applies to all racketeering suspects, not just accused
drug traffickers, said Neal Sonnett, president of the 15,000-member
National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers.
   ``In this hysteria of getting tough on crime, there seems to be
a feeling that it's OK for the war on crime to become a war on the
Constitution,'' he said.
   The association has made it a policy to help attorneys who are
targeted by aggressive prosecutors, Sonnett said, but many defense
lawyers are discouraged.
   ``I have received communications from attorneys who are
articulating severe gloom, several of whom are saying they may
leave the practice,'' he said.
   One who abandoned criminal law was Miami attorney Joel
Hirschorn, who left private practice after 22 years and joined a
firm to try civil law.
   ``What's going on here is that government, every time I tweak
its nose, can go after my fees,'' Hirschorn said. ``Prosecutors
have the right to shut off the cash flow _ and I have mortgages to
pay.''
   But Miami U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said seizure destroys
the profit motive and can break up a drug ring more effectively
than jail sentences. He said lawyers have no right to argue they
are somehow exempt from the law.
   ``It was very important that the Supreme Court ruled that
defense lawyers are not under a different standard,'' he said.
   Lehtinen said that in his district no lawyer need fear
prosecutors going after fees unless the attorney has taken an
active part in laundering drug money.
   But some attorneys said the threat of seizure is abused in other
districts.
   ``They may start with the drug dealers, but they are going to go
all the way down,'' said Jose Quinon, who defended Medellin Cartel
boss Carlos Lehder Rivas last year.
   ``The final result is that the adversarial system as we have
known it is gone _ the government will choose your lawyer,'' said
Quinon, president of the Florida Association of Criminal Defense
Lawyers.
   Defense attorneys already face the difficult determination of
whether prosecutors will freeze their client's assets. In many
cases, the line between legally and illegally obtained assets is
impossible to draw, they say.
   Edward Shohat, who also worked on the Lehder case, said trying
to figure out prosecutors' intentions is almost impossible.
   ``There is no pattern to it,'' Shohat said. ``I've had cases
where you would have thought they would act, but there was no
seizure, while in other cases, you wonder why they did.''
   That means that a defense lawyer must first spend his time and
his client's money just defending his fee, instead of preparing a
criminal defense.
   Joseph Beeler, who participated in the Supreme Court case that
led to the ruling, said prosecutors use of seizure to scare off
lawyers, a use of the Racketeer Influenced, Corrupt Organizations
Act that Congress never intended.
   On a personal level, Beeler said, ``I've certainly turned down
business _ and I hate to do it _ because the government has made it
impossible for them to defend themselves.''
   One result of private attorneys balking at taking criminal cases
will be an increasing load on already overworked public defenders,
said Robyn Blumner, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union of Florida.
   Sonnett said attorneys have been sounding out Congress about an
exemption for attorneys' fees, but he acknowledges the political
climate makes it difficult for Congress to appear as if somehow
supporting drug dealers.
   For now, many lawyers say they will continue their criminal
practice, but the days of an elite group of top criminal attorneys
may be numbered.
   `In the next couple of years, you will see some of the best and
the brightest leaving criminal practice,'' Quinon said. ``People
are already beginning to handle civil cases. That was unthinkable a
short while ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
