<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Converging On Washington For Housing March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of people are arriving in
the nation's capital to urge Congress and the Bush administration
to lift the homeless from the streets and make housing more
affordable for all Americans.
   Organizers wouldn't say Tuesday what turnout they expect for
three days of activities culminating in a ``Housing Now!'' march
Saturday on the national Mall.
   But the breadth of their sponsorship, coupled with a massive
planning effort dating to early in the year, could produce one of
the largest demonstrations Washington has seen in years.
   ``We're saying enough is enough,'' said Washington homeless
activist Mitch Snyder. ``Today the streets in Boston, New York and
Washington look like those in Calcutta. This demonstration is to
provide some will and some backbone to the administration and
Congress.''
   Activists complain the Reagan-Bush administrations cut the
budget authority for federal housing assistance programs by 77
percent _ from $32 billion to less than $8 billion a year _ and
cite that as the principal reason for the growing numbers of people
who are without homes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Volunteers Offer Help to Defense Worker, But Terminal Patient</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Can't Fly
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health of a terminally ill Defense
Department employee may have deteriorated too much to allow him to
take advantage of offers from volunteers to fly him for free back
to his Massachusetts home.
   The offers were made after the Defense Department refused a
request from the wife of Avram Brody, to fly him on an Air Force
air-ambulance flight from Palmdale, Calif.
   Amy Brody said her husband, a three-year Defense Department
computer operator, wanted to return to Massachusetts where he was
born and raised so he could be among relatives and friends for the
last weeks of his life.
   Brody, 25, was diagnosed last year with terminal brain cancer.
It would have cost roughly $29,000 to hire a private air ambulance.
   Air Force officials refused a transcontinental flight, even when
congressmen and a White House aide were enlisted to help Brody.
   Mrs. Brody said Tuesday she did not know if her husband's
condition might improve enough to make a flight offered by private
citizens possible. Brody has already outlasted the life expectation
given by doctors by several months.
