<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-NoriegaProfile     10-04 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Noriega Profile,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama's Wily, Ruthless Defense Forces Chief Savors a Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, who once
called his opponent's bullets ``kisses,'' is a shrewd and ruthless
survivor who revels in power and in thumbing his nose at what he
calls ``the colossus of the North.''
   On Tuesday, elements of the 15,000-man Defense Forces he
commands claimed they had deposed him. But once again, he dodged
the bullet and showed up Tuesday afternoon to accept the rebels'
surrender.
   It is known that ``Tony'' Noriega enjoys a crisis, and events of
the last 18 months would have driven a less determined man into
retirement.
   Many Panamanians want him out. The United States, which indicted
him on drug-trafficking charges in February 1988, has tried
everything short of military force to remove him. The international
community has condemned him.
   But Noriega, who comes from El Chorrillo, the Panama City
district where Defense Forces headquarters is located, has survived
and created a mystique.
   It is said he thrives on pressure and would prefer death to
losing power. That is part of machismo that won him the nickname
``The Man,'' the English word his initials spell.
   Noriega has wrapped himself in nationalism, saying it is part of
the historic mission of his generation to take control of the
Panama Canal. Under an accord with the United States, Panama is to
take over the canal by the year 2000.
   During his last crisis in May after the opposition swamped his
candidate in presidential elections that were annulled by the
government, Noriega was seen standing alone before the tomb of his
patron, Gen. Omar Torrijos.
   The epitaph on the tomb is: ``I don't want to enter heaven. I
just want to enter the Canal Zone.''
   Torrijos, who seized power in a 1968, signed the 1977 accord
with former President Carter to turn over the canal. Torrijos was
killed in a plane crash in 1981, and Noriega became commander of
the Defense Forces in 1983. The position has allowed him to control
the government.
   Noriega says his enemies are fomenting a plot to abrogate the
canal pact.
   The general was raised by foster parents and joined the Defense
Forces in 1962. His ascent began when he caught the attention of
Torrijos, then an ambitious young officer.
   In his climb to the top, he dealt with everyone from the CIA to
Colombian cocaine cartels.
   Less than a year after Torrijos gained power in 1968 coup, he
made Noriega, then an obscure major, chief of intelligence with the
rank of lieutenant colonel.
   It was like having the keys to the city. Noriega immediately
began assembling dossiers on everyone who counted in Panama.
   Noriega's job also put him in close contact with U.S.
intelligence agencies, and he formed powerful alliances.
   One U.S. official who dealt with Noriega at the time, on drug
enforcement efforts, said Noriega was polite but when it came to
something he wanted, he was ``the coldest man I ever met.''
   After Noriega became the Defense Forces commander, he acquired a
fleet of expensive cars and a home in an exclusive neighborhood.
   He reportedly is involved in a vast array of businesses
including hotels, casinos, a television station, radio stations,
maritime services, duty-free liquor stores and prostitution.
   Rumors about his personal life are plentiful, but there are few
facts. Even his age is in dispute. The general says he is 51, but
the date in his high school yearbook would make him 54. He is
married and has a daughter who lives in the Dominican Republic.
   Although his private life is that of a rich man, he worked hard
to develop a populist image modeled on the revered Torrijos,
spending weekends meeting with residents of towns and villages in
this nation of 2.2 million.
   Noriega often speaks of his humble origins and characterizes his
domestic opponents as rich and white.
   ``The humble, the poor and the blacks, they are the utmost
authority of the people,'' he once said.
   As the standoff with the United States dragged on in past
months, Noriega enjoyed underlining Washington's helplessness,
despite the 12,000 troops it has stationed in Panama.
   Noriega exercises his power with ruthless assurance. He has
closed newspapers for months at a time, and presidents served at
his pleasure.
   Rumors of opposition inside the Defense Forces _ such as the
March 16, 1988 coup attempt _ were met with purges and
reorganizations.
   ``Kisses,'' was how he described the bullets fired in that
attempted coup.
   The United States, long his ally, began to distance itself after
the headless body of one of his opponents, Hugo Spadadora, was
found in a U.S. mailbag in Costa Rica in 1985.
   A full break came in February 1988, when two federal grand
juries in Florida indicted Noriega on drug-trafficking and
money-laundering charges.
   The domestic opposition began to intensify its campaign against
Noriega and Washington imposed crippling economic sanctions.
   Noriega didn't budge.
   Shortly after the indictments in Floria, Noriega delivered a
speech. He brandished a machete above his head, then brought it
crashing down on the podium.
   ``Not one step back!'' he shouted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
