<FIRST>r a PM-OilSpill     10-04 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Spill,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard: Overworked Captain Still Should Have Avoided Grounding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker captain was sleepless,
distracted and had no lookout when his ship hit a reef and spilled
289,000 gallons of oil, but he still should have avoided the
accident, a Coast Guard investigator says.
   ``I think he knew where he was,'' Capt. David H. Whitten said
after listening to 2{ hours of testimony Tuesday from Iakovos
Georgoudis, captain of the World Prodigy.
   The ship hit a reef off Newport on June 23, spilling the heating
oil.
   The captain's workload contributed to the accident, Whitten
said, but ``you can't regulate that. He's expected to handle
distractions.''
   Georgoudis told Coast Guard and National Transportation Safety
Board investigators he had been in control of the ship for 36
hours, catching at most two hours of sleep the morning before the
accident. Georgoudis said he stayed on the bridge that long because
of poor visibility, which did not clear until that morning.
   Georgudis said he sent his chief officer below to do
calculations for unloading the cargo at Providence after the
shipping agent messaged the Greek tanker that there might be a
second, previously unscheduled stop.
   Georgoudis said that when the chief officer took longer than
expected, he called for a second officer to help him, but the
message apparently never was relayed.
   He also said he had sent his lookout to help a harbor pilot
board and was alone with a helmsman when the ship hit Brenton Reef.
   ``I was everything'' at that point, trying to handle radio
traffic, navigation and various calculations, Georgoudis said.
   Georgoudis said he saw a buoy warning of the reef about 30
minutes before the accident, but he could not explain the grounding.
   ``That's my big question,'' Georgoudis said. He said he noticed
he was on the wrong side of the buoy only ``when the buoy was very
near my bow.''
   The captain said he discovered only moments before the accident
that he was northeast of where he was to have met the harbor pilot.
He said he heard no radio warnings from the pilot boat until the
World Prodigy hit the rocks at about 10 knots.
   The captain acknowledged that Ballard Shipping Co., the tanker's
owner, and Greek regulations required a lookout when entering a
harbor. Georgoudis said he had been in Providence harbor once
before, in 1987, on a different ship.
   Defense lawyer Peter DiBiase refused to let Georgoudis, 43,
answer questions after the hearing and said the captain would
return immediately to Greece.
   Georgoudis agreed to testify after pleading guilty Friday to one
misdemeanor count of violating the federal Clean Water Act and no
contest to a state pollution charge. He was fined $30,500.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
