<DOCNO> AP891004-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0435EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-04 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen in Tokyo, Stocks Rise Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar declined against the Japanese yen today
amid apparent massive dollar-selling by central banks, while the
key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose slightly.
   The dollar closed at 140.60, down 0.05 yen from Tuesday's close.
It had opened at 141.05 and climbed as high as 141.85 yen at one
point. The day's low was 140.50 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average rose 16.43 points, or 0.05 percent, to
35,382.80, reversing its fall in the morning. Volume was 850
million shares.
   The dollar's early gains in Tokyo followed an upswing on
overseas markets overnight, traders said.
   In the morning, banks from Singapore bought West German marks
for yen, sending the dollar upward, while traders virtually ignored
Bank of Japan intervention aimed at keeping the dollar down, said
Minori Takeuchi, a trader at Chemical Bank.
   ``But in the afternoon, the Bank of Japan again intervened and
there were rumors of intervention by the Bank of England and the
(German) Bundesbank, causing the dollar to decline gradually,'' she
said.
   ``We think the central banks sold huge amounts of dollars,'' she
said.
   Japan's central bank does not comment on its exchange market
activities.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei average lost 13.41
points, falling to 35,352.96 within the first 15 minutes of morning
trading. It had lost 256.60 points the previous day.
   The index rose gradually in the afternoon, but dealers said
there was no clear direction.
   Takahide Furuhashi, head of analysis at DB Capital Markets, said
that across the board, companies with large capitalization were
sold in favor of smaller companies.
   He said buyers were ``looking for low price-earnings multiples.''
   Companies holding land in Osaka and Nagoya, where land prices
have been rising, were popular issues, he said.
   ``The market is still watching interest rates. Yesterday, the
market was worried about an interest rate hike in West Germany, and
I think it is still concerned today,'' said Takeshi Yamamoto, head
of research at Barclays de Zoete Wedd Securities.
   He said shares of companies thought to have hidden assets, such
as warehousing firms and private railways, were doing well, while
retailers were still slumping following Tuesday's announcement by
Shuwa Corp. that it was selling its shares in the Life store chain.
   ``Supermarkets had been bought heavily on merger and acquisition
stories, led by Shuwa,'' which earlier this year made highly
publicized bids for smaller chains, Yamamoto said.
</TEXT>
