<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Aid     10-04 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Aid,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Foreign Ministers Back Aid for Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European foreign ministers have backed a $650
million package of aid for the struggling economies of Poland and
Hungary.
   ``The process of political and economic reform in Poland and
Hungary has progressed considerably,'' said the ministers of the
12-nation European Community.
   ``However, the process remains fragile and could be weakened by
economic difficulties,'' they said in a statement issued Tuesday at
the end of daylong talks on foreign policy issues.
   The aid package was unveiled last week as part of Western
efforts to help the Eastern European countries reform their
economies.
   British Foreign Secretary John Major said it was ``very
desirable'' to help the two countries, but said they must make
economic reforms to sustain their societies.
   The West wants to encourage the push in both countries for
broader economic and political reforms.
   In July, President Bush and heads of other leading democracies
asked the European Community to coordinate economic aid for Poland
and Hungary. They also urged emergency food shipments for Poland.
   At Tuesday's meeting, the foreign ministers endorsed a plan by
the European Commission, the trading bloc's executive body, to add
about $220 million to next year's budget to help the two countries.
   They also supported other elements of the plan, which included
agricultural aid, reducing trade restrictions, direct investment,
professional training and pollution control.
   Half of the $650 million cost of the plan would be paid for by
the community nations, and half would come from the other 12
nations including that United States that are taking part in the
drive.
   The foreign ministers also urged that higher-level officials of
the 24 nations meet soon ``to ensure that sufficient momentum is
maintained'' in the Poland-Hungary push.
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski of Poland sent a letter in July to
community officials asking for 685,000 tons of beef, pork, powdered
milk, butter, oils, wheat, corn, rice and sugar in the coming
months.
   He also said Poland would need at least 3.7 million tons of food
next year and again in 1991.
</TEXT>
