<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Hangings     10-04 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Hangings,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Convicted Murderers Hanged At Pretoria Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three black men convicted in
separate murder cases were hanged today at Pretoria Central Prison,
raising to 42 the number of executions in South Africa so far this
year.
   None of the killings had been depicted as having political
overtones, although anti-apartheid activists and human rights
lawyers have been campaigning for a moratorium on all executions.
   Two mixed-race men were hanged on Friday, the first executions
since mid-July and the first approved by President F.W. de Klerk
during his seven weeks in power. One of them, Mangena Jeffrey
Boesman, was a member of the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement, and was hanged despite a clemency appeal from
the United Nations.
   Two of the prisoners hanged this year were white, the rest black
or mixed-race. The number of executions is far lower than in
previous years, such as 1987, when a record 164 people were
executed.
   The government says 54 condemned prisoners have received
reprieves this year. More than 200 prisoners, nearly all of them
black men, remain on Death Row.
</TEXT>
