<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Soviet     10-04 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Soviet,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze In Nicaragua For `Strictly Political' Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze is in Nicaragua for talks, but an official report said
he and President Daniel Ortega would not discuss Soviet aid to the
leftist government.
   Shevardnadze arrived Tuesday for the 24-hour visit, saying he
brought a message for Ortega from President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
and the Soviet leadership. He did not immediately disclose its
contents.
   ``We attribute great importance to these conversations ... in
Managua, at such a transcendental stage when a new era, a peaceful
era for the Nicaraguan revolution is to begin,'' Shevardnadze said.
   ``We support it, and the Soviet Union would like to contribute
to this historic cause.''
   Shevardnadze, the highest-ranking Soviet official to visit
Nicaragua, was scheduled to meet today with Ortega and the
leadership of the Sandinista National Liberation Front, which
seized power in a 1979 revolution from rightist President Anastasio
Somoza.
   Barricada, the Sandinista newspaper, quoted a government
official as saying Shevardnadze's visit would be ``strictly
political.''
   ``The topics of bilateral cooperation will be broached in
November,'' when a Nicaraguan-Soviet economic meeting is scheduled,
Barricada said.
   The newspaper listed Soviet aid to Nicaragua at $11.2 billion
from 1980 to 1988. According to U.S. government figures, the Soviet
Union has been giving Nicaragua $1 billion a year, half of it in
military aid.
   The Soviet Union also provides about 40 percent of Nicaragua's
annual consumption of 760,000 tons of petroleum and Soviet bloc
countries provide the rest. Mexico and Venezuela quit supplying the
leftist Sandinista government with oil in 1981 because of
non-payment.
   Shevardnadze is expected to discuss Nicaragua's general
elections set for Feb. 25.
   In August, Ortega moved up the date of the 1991 elections and
promised a free press and open and honest balloting.
   In return, he and other Central American presidents agreed to
disband the U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, by December and
to quit allowing them to operate from neighboring countries.
   Observers from the United Nations, the Organization of American
States, the European Parliament and a delegation led by former
President Carter will monitor the elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
