<FIRST>r a PM-DogSpared     10-04 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dog Spared,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Sets `Condemned' Dog Free</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small dog facing a ``death penalty'' for
biting a man has been released after a judge ruled that even
canines have constitutional rights.
   Marion County Circuit Judge Richard D. Barber ruled Tuesday that
the dachshund terrier named Blue Two should go free after spending
75 days at the Humane Society of Willamette Valley.
   Barber said the county has a right to confiscate a dog in the
interest of public safety but that right ``cannot be exercised with
total disregard of what we consider to be due process of law.''
   Bob Cannon, the county's legal counsel, predicted the ruling
will prevent the county from enforcing state law in all future
dog-bite cases.
   But the defense attorney for the dog's owners said the decision
shows that county animal control ordinances need to be changed.
   ``Blue Two obviously was not one of those dangerous dogs,'' said
attorney Walter Todd, who represents Vic and Karen Parkison.
   Karen Parkison greeted her pet with tears in her eyes. She said
the dog had turned gray and lost weight.
   ``I'm just happy and relieved to have him,'' she said, adding it
was ``75 long, long days of waiting.''
   The dog had bitten a man July 13. The victim said he did not
want the dog put to death, but the county proceeded with a hearing.
</TEXT>
