<FIRST>r a PM-RockefellerUniversity     10-04 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rockefeller University,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidate for University President Linked to Allegedly Fraudulent
Paper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. David Baltimore, a Nobel Prize winner who
helped write a research paper that has been challenged as
fraudulent, has been offered the presidency of Rockefeller
University.
   Some ``very strong members of the faculty'' criticized the
choice, said Richard M. Furlaud, a co-chairman of a committee of
Rockefeller University trustees that searched for a new president.
   Baltimore, a 51-year-old molecular biologist who shared the 1975
Nobel Prize in medicine for cancer research, has not been accused
of wrongdoing in the paper.
   He would succeed Dr. Joshua Lederberg as head of the graduate
university, which specializes in biomedical research and training.
Lederberg will turn 65 years old, the mandatory retirement age, in
May.
   The National Institutes of Health and the House Subcommittee on
Oversight and Investigations were investigating charges that a
paper signed by Baltimore and five other authors was not supported
by the data.
   The research was done in a Massachusetts Institute of Technology
laboratory and not by Baltimore.
   Since 1982, Baltimore has directed the Whitehead Institute for
Biomedical Research, a private group in Cambridge, Mass.,
affiliated with MIT.
   ``We have looked very carefully into the whole NIH investigation
and the report of error in the paper, and we are absolutely
convinced that as far as he is concerned, there is not a scintilla
of evidence of fraud, misconduct or anything else,'' Furlaud said.
   Baltimore said he planned to meet today with faculty members and
planned several more visits in coming weeks. However, he said
topics of discussion probably would not include the paper but
rather ``where Rockefeller is going to go, what the needs of the
university for science are for the next decade and whether they
feel I can lead the institution in the right directions.''
   He said he had not decided whether to accept the position.
</TEXT>
