<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower in Europe this morning,
pressured by renewed rumors of central bank intervention in East
Asian markets. Gold prices rose.
   Traders said there were rumors that the Bank of Japan, Bank of
England and Deutsche Bundesbank sold dollars in several regional
East Asian markets.
   The rumored central bank intervention was the only thing that
was preventing the U.S. currency from going higher, dealers said.
   Traders said investors were prepared to sit out today and part
of the Thursday trading session waiting for the outcome of the West
German central bank's Thursday policy-setting meeting.
   Many traders were expecting the central bank to increase
interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.05 yen to a closing 140.60 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 140.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8735 West German marks, down from 1.8865
   _1.6245 Swiss francs, down from 1.6350
   _6.3580 French francs, down from 6.4005
   _2.1201 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1195
   _1,371.75 Italian lire, down from 1,380.50
   _1.1750 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1763
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6100 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6055 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $365.95 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $365.50. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.05.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $366.10 compared with $365.25 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed unchanged at $366.50.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.23 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.22.
</TEXT>
