<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0615EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SpermBanks     10-04 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sperm Banks,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Worries Means Gays Can No Longer Donate Sperm in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New state rules requiring donors to sperm
banks to undergo two AIDS tests and barring homsexual men and
intravenous drug users from donating were welcomed by the director
of one bank.
   ``In order to minimize the risks of transmission and increase
the safety to recipients, we have to get some controls over who the
sperm donors are,'' said Dr. Grace Centola, who runs a sperm bank
at the University of Rochester Medical Center.
   The first question asked by patients seeking sperm from an
anonymous donor is invariably about the danger of contracting
acquired immune deficiency syndrom, she said Tuesday.
   The regulations that took effect Monday also require for the
first time that sperm banks be licensed by the state.
   Donors are required to undergo two separate AIDS tests, the
second one six months after the sperm has been donated and frozen,
said Mary Anne Gardineer, Health Department associate director for
regulatory affairs.
   The regulations exclude a person from donating if he's had any
homosexual activity, intravenous drug use or sex with a person
thought to be at high risk for AIDS since 1977.
   The same people already are barred from donating blood,
Gardineer said.
   The U.S. Centers for Disease Control have documented no cases of
transmission of the AIDS virus through donated sperm in the United
States, a spokesman said.
   Gardineer said there's been one case of an Australian man who
tested positive for the AIDS virus after donating sperm to eight
women. Four of the women later tested positive for the virus, but
three of their babies born through artificial insemination were
healthy, Gardineer said. The fourth pregnancy never came to term.
   AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread
most often through sex, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers,
infected blood and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   New York state's 25,000 confirmed AIDS cases is about
one-quarter of the nation's total.
   Geoffrey Knox, a spokesman for the Gay Men's Health Crisis, said
he had no problem with the prohibition against homosexual men.
   In 1987, about 30,000 women in the United States were
impregnated through the use of anonymous donor sperm, Centola said.
   Gardineer couldn't be sure of just how many sperm banks there
are in the state because they haven't been licensed in the past.
   The new rules don't apply in cases where a person is donating
sperm for a specific person, such as his wife.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0071 </DOCNO>
