<SECOND>PM-Council Proposal,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposal `Appeals' to Council Clerk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Clerk Pam Ferris got the surprise
of her life when the man at the microphone at the City Council
meeting asked for her hand in marriage.
   Lou Droesch, a mortgage broker, walked to the microphone as
Tuesday night's meeting neared its end.
   ``I'm crazy about your city clerk,'' Droesch told the council.
``And I ask that the city fathers approve my asking for her hand in
marriage.''
   Mayor Herm Fauson knew about the proposal and rescheduled an
executive session so the proposal could be made.
   Before giving his approval, Fauson said, ``One of the conditions
that we might ask that you include in the proposal is that you
don't try to take her away from the city.''
   Droesch agreed and promptly got down on one knee and asked
Ferris to marry him. She accepted.
   Droesch, who lives just outside town, said he will leave the
time and place to Ferris.
   ``First I thought he was going to ask to be annexed to
Louisville,'' Ferris said, who had no prior knowledge of the
proposal.
   The couple and the council celebrated with champagne after the
meeting was adjourned.
