<FIRST>r a PM-Bakker-Falwell     10-04 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bakker-Falwell,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Falwell Says Bakker Wrong to Blame Him for PTL Troubles</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bakker Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rev. Jerry Falwell said evangelist Jim Bakker
shouldn't blame him for the collapse of PTL because the damage to
the bankrupt ministry took place before he assumed control, a
newspaper reported.
   In an interview in today's editions of The Dallas Morning News,
Falwell said he met Bakker for the first time when the PTL founder
called him to Palm Springs, Calif., to turn over the ministry.
Bakker resigned in a sex-and-money scandal in 1987.
   ``I don't know a thing about the gentleman,'' Falwell said. ``I
thought he was a joke.''
   Falwell made the comments in response to Bakker's testimony at
his fraud trial in Charlotte, N.C., on Monday in which he accused
Falwell of cheating PTL followers.
   Bakker also said Falwell and his attorney, Norman Roy Grutman,
``threatened'' board members by telling them they ``might be liable
to a civil suit.''
   Falwell said that after he and his associates arrived at PTL and
realized the situation, Grutman told the PTL's board of directors
``they had best get directly involved because they had personal
civil responsibilities.''
   Falwell said he never met any of the PTL directors. But he said
he called in Arthur Andersen &amp; Co., the accounting and management
consulting firm, brought in attorneys and appointed ``a blue-ribbon
panel'' of directors from across the country.
   ``I told them to conceal nothing, to tell the truth, to release
all financial papers to the press and to immediately expose any
inequities or illegal activity,'' Falwell said. ``And they did it.''
   Bakker is accused of plotting to swindle followers out of $158
million and of using at least $3.7 million to support a lavish
lifestyle. The ministry has filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection from creditors.
   Falwell, an evangelist from Lynchburg, Va., was in Dallas for a
speaking engagement Wednesday.
</TEXT>
