<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0744EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines     10-04 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Discusses Alleged Aquino Assassination Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet today endorsed the ban on
burying Ferdinand Marcos' body in the Philippines after the defense
chief briefed them on an alleged plot to assassinate President
Corazon Aquino, officials said.
   Presidential spokesman Adolfo Azcuna said the ``sensitive
information'' on reputed security threats to the government was
discussed during the Cabinet session, but he refused to elaborate.
   Economic Planning Secretary Jesus Estanislao said, however, that
Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos briefed members on the security risks
facing the government if Mrs. Aquino allowed the body of the former
president to be buried in the Philippines.
   Marcos, 72, died in Honolulu Thursday. He had lived in exile in
Hawaii since he was toppled in a civilian-military uprising that
propelled Mrs. Aquino to power in February 1986.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow the body to be brought back to
the Philippines for burial and also forbade the late president's
widow, Imelda, and their three children to come back.
   ``There are destabilization threats,'' Estanislao told The
Associated Press. ``He (Ramos) presented intelligence reports,
including the possible assassination of the president.''
   Estanislao would not say whether Ramos provided details of any
alleged plot, nor whether the defense chief identified those who
allegedly were behind it.
   ``One thing you must realize is that there are parties abroad
who are very interested in destabilization, including Mrs.
Marcos,'' he said. ``And there are parties here who are interested
in destabilization. These two parties can act together.''
   In a news conference after the Cabinet meeting, Ramos refused to
confirm or deny Estanislao's disclosure, saying what was taken up
during the briefing was ``highly classified.''
   ``We are still trying to measure if this is an empty threat or
not,'' Ramos added. ``We cannot afford this kind of hysteria
because we are trying to attract investments in the country.''
   Marcos' followers have been linked to several of the six armed
attempts to topple Mrs. Aquino. But since Marcos' death,
demonstrations by his followers have been relatively small and
peaceful.
   Agriculture Secretary Carlos Dominguez said the Cabinet was
unanimous in its support for the controversial decision, despite
growing public pressure to allow Marcos' remains to come home.
   ``We have supported the president since the beginning on her
stand,'' Dominguez said. ``There is no question in the Cabinet as
to the position we are taking.''
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court agreed to consider a petition from
Marcos' supporters to overturn the ban and gave the government 10
days to respond.
   Mrs. Aquino says she will abide by the court's decision but
claims Marcos' burial in the Philippines could lead to civil unrest
and discourage foreign investment.
   Mrs. Marcos has been prohibited from leaving the United States,
where she is to be tried in New York in March on charges of
embezzling government money and investing some of it in the United
States. The Marcoses were indicted in October and Mrs. Marcos is
free on $5 million bond.
</TEXT>
