<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     10-04 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippine Consul Raises Possibility of Marcos Viewing at Consulate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippines' consul general here has offered
to allow Ferdinand Marcos' body to lie in state at the consulate if
his widow makes the request in writing and Philippine President
Corazon Aquino consents.
   In an ironic twist, the body would lie in state in a room
dedicated to Mrs. Aquino's husband, whose 1983 assassination led to
Marcos' downfall in a 1986 uprising that lifted Mrs. Aquino to
power.
   Consul General Tomas ``Buddy'' Gomez made the offer Tuesday
after a shouting match on the consulate steps with Marcos
supporters angry because the Philippine flag was not lowered to
half-staff after the former Phillipine president died in exile here
at age 72.
   Gomez said he didn't order the flag lowered because he had no
instructions from Manila to do so.
   The request for a lying-in-state at the consulate was made by
Joe Lazo, president of the Friends of Marcos. He said the Marcos
family would agree to having Marcos' body in the pavilion named for
Marcos rival Benigno Aquino Jr.
   ``Joe, you put that in writing and have that signed by the
widow,'' Gomez responded, adding he would make a personal request
to Mrs. Aquino.
   Gomez also said he would allow Marcos to be buried temporarily
at the consulate if he had Philippine and local government approval.
   This would satisfy the family's wish not to have Marcos buried
in American soil since the consulate legally is an extension of the
Philippines, Gomez said.
   Aquino was gunned down in 1983 at the Manila airport as he
returned to the Philippines from self-imposed exile in the United
States. The slaying, which many Filipinos blamed on Marcos and his
supporters, galvanized the opposition.
   Plans are going ahead to have Marcos' body temporarily entombed
here in hopes the Philippine government eventually will allow him
to be buried in his homeland, a family spokesman said. Mrs. Aquino
has refused to allow Marcos' body to be returned to his homeland,
saying it could provoke unrest.
   The Philippines Supreme Court has agreed to consider a petition
from Marcos supporters to lift the ban.
   Marcos' body has been on display at the family's mansion in
Makiki Heights, overlooking Honolulu. Hundreds have visited to view
the body, which will be taken Friday to a Roman Catholic cathedral
for a funeral Mass.
   ``There's one point I want to make perfectly clear and that is,
the final resting place of my father is going to be Ilocos Norte,''
Marco's home province, said his son, Ferdinand ``Bong Bong'' Marcos
Jr.
   Entombing Marcos above ground would serve a symbolic purpose for
the family in that the former president would not be buried in U.S.
soil, said Gomez.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
