<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0461 10-04 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Lawmakers Say U.S. Should Have Sent Troops to Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: leads with 12 grafs Lugar, Torricelli comments today defending
administration; picks up 6th graf pvs, ``Here you.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers from both parties are criticizing
President Bush for not offering U.S. military aid to an attempted
coup in Panama, but a Senate Republican said today the only
American option is ``to let things take their course.''
   ``Once again we have snatched defeat from the jaws of victory,
and I think it's an outrage,'' Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said
Tuesday.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., said U.S. intervention could
have made a difference in the attempted coup against Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   ``We have the absolute unilateral right to use force,''
DeConcini said.
   But Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said of the complaints: ``It's
very easy to be an armchair general.''
   ``The president finally has to think about our treaty
obligations, our personnel, our relations with other countries in
the Latin American hemisphere and the future of democracy in
Panama, which can flow only from the Panamanian people making
choices,'' he said today on the NBC ``Today'' program.
   Although the U.S. military forces in Panama were on alert,
American officials said they only observed the fighting Tuesday
between members of the Panama Defense forces, standing by to help
any Americans who might be in danger.
   Lugar, a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, urged
continued economic and diplomatic pressure on Panama, saying the
coup attempt indicated growing discontent inside that country with
Noriega.
   ``I have no doubt that there are going to be further attempts,
there is going to be further pressure. This is not over by a long
shot,'' he said. ``We have only that choice _ to let things take
their course.''
   Rep. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., also urged continued economic
pressure without force.
   ``To simply send in troops is not how democracy should be
restored in Panama,'' Torricelli, a member of the House Foreign
Affairs Committee, said on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' program.
``It will happen and will be done the right way without causing a
backlash against the United States.''
   Senate Intelligence Committee Chairman David Boren, D-Okla., was
bitter after emerging from an hour-long classified CIA briefing
Tuesday on the coup attempt.
   ``Here you have brave people in Panama ... trying to rid
themselves of a drug dealer and a thug who's taken over their
country,'' Boren said.
   ``And for the United States, with all of our strength and force
and all of our belief in democracy, to stand by ... and do nothing
and allow these people to fail, personally I think is wrong.''
   Boren said he had been notified early Tuesday that the coup was
in progress and followed its progress throughout the day. He said
200 to 300 rebel troops had seized the Panamanian Defense Forces
headquarters compound with Noriega inside, and had the leader
``trapped and pinned down.''
   But later in the day, about 500 troops loyal to Noriega
surrounded the compound and freed him. The fate of those who led
the revolt was unclear.
   No American troops or citizens were involved, Boren said.
   ``I'm just sorry it didn't succeed. I'm sorry there was not some
way, apparently, for the United States to help make it succeed,''
Boren told reporters.
   He cited failures by the Reagan administration to use force to
help Eric Arturo Delvalle when he sought to remove Noriega from
power, and to help maintain order when Noriega later overrode
national elections to retain power for himself.
   Asked whether military force should have been used Tuesday,
Boren said:
   ``My personal view is that we should have, and we didn't. ... We
certainly knew at that moment where (Noriega) was. He was in a
physical location where perhaps he could have been served with that
warrant for his arrest.''
   Noriega has been indicted in the United States on drug charges.
   ``I think it's one thing for the United States to go into any
other country ... and try to impose its will from the outside,''
Boren said.
   ``It's quite another thing when the people of Panama have very
clearly spoken in their free elections, and overwhelmingly want to
rid themselves of this ... corrupt dictatorship. ... I don't think
it is improper at all for the United States then to offer a helping
hand to the Panamanian people.''
</TEXT>
