<FIRST>r a PM-BerthoudTunnel     10-04 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berthoud Tunnel,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ski Resort Endorse Tunnel Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINTER PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By a 17-vote margin, residents have
lifted a major barrier to plans to cut a $250 million highway
tunnel under the Berthoud Pass to this ski resort.
   The proposed, 4.1-mile tunnel would spare motorists from having
to drive the zigzag road over the breathtaking, 11,315-foot gap and
would cut 20 minutes off the 90-minute, 55-mile trip from Denver to
Winter Park.
   Residents voted 110-93 Tuesday against a measure that would have
prevented the city from extending its borrowing powers to the
tunnel building authority. More than a third of the town's 600
permanent residents are registered to vote.
   The Berthoud Tunnel Building Authority, created by the Town
Council, will now proceed with a $2 million study of the project
and its environmental impact. The authority can issue bonds to be
paid off with tolls.
   Proponents of the tunnel say many tourists are afraid to make
the drive over the pass. Supporters also argue it will spur
development by bringing more skiers to Winter Park, one of the
nation's largest ski resorts.
   Opponents say that the tunnel would disrupt the quiet lifestyle
that attracted many people to the area and that the price tag is
too high.
</TEXT>
