<HEAD>Navy Investigates Disappearance of Money, Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former disbursing officer on the USS
Tuscaloosa has disappeared along with $247,500 of the government's
money, the Navy says.
   Investigators are searching for the officer, Lt. j.g. Bradley
Scott Darr, 31, who has been declared a deserter, Navy spokesman
Cmdr. David Dillon said Tuesday.
   No charges have been filed against Darr, who is from North
Carolina but whose hometown wasn't immediately available, said
Dillon.
   A routine Navy audit last month revealed the discrepancy in the
accounts of the San Diego-based tank-landing ship, which has a crew
of 244, Dilon said. Darr already had been ordered to another post
when the audit was completed.
   Under the orders issued July 30, Darr was supposed to report to
the Naval Air Station in Sigonella, Italy, by Aug. 23, but he never
showed up and was declared a deserter on Sept. 22, the commander
said.
   As disbursing officer, Darr was the ship's banker. ``He's making
deposits, meeting the payroll and handling all the financial
transactions on the ship,'' Dillon said.
