<FIRST>r i PM-US-Soviet-Arms     10-04 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet-Arms,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Could Visit Star Wars Labs This Year, U.S. Envoy Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet arms experts could visit U.S. laboratories
doing research on space-based missile defenses before the end of
the year, an American official said today.
   Henry Cooper, chief U.S. negotiator on defense and space at the
Geneva arms talks, urged Moscow to agree to regular annual
exchanges of visits to such labs as a confidence-building measure.
   He said he believed the Soviets would accept an invitation to
tour two U.S. sites, made by Secretary of State James Baker III
when Baker met with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
last month.
   Arrangements could be set during the current round of superpower
arms talks, Cooper said in an interview with the U.S. mission's
daily bulletin. The round is expected to end by early December.
   The U.S. invitation covers equipment being developed at the Los
Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico and a commercial testing
plant in San Juan Capistrano, Calif. Both are involved in high-tech
research for the U.S. Strategic Defense Invitiative, or Star Wars,
a project launched by former President Reagan to provide space
defenses against incoming ballistic missiles.
   Moscow has complained about the two facilities in the past, and
visits would show ``that we are serious about opening our
laboratories and increasing predictability about ballistic missiles
defense capabilities,'' Cooper said.
   Early research, which can be monitored only on-the-spot,
``provides the greatest insight into where the sides are going,''
he said.
   In the Geneva talks, the Soviets have already agreed to annual
exchanges of data on both sides' research into space-based missiles
defenses, he said.
   The U.S. offer to open SDI to Soviet experts was one of several
arms control moves at the ministerial meeting, where Shevardnadze
announced that Moscow would no longer let its objections to SDI
block the eventual signing of a treaty cutting long-nuclear forces.
</TEXT>
