<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     10-04 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Criticizes Hong Kong for Allowing Swimmer to Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China sharply criticized Hong Kong today for
allowing a top Chinese swimmer who defected to fly to the United
States.
   A spokesman for the local Xinhua News Agency branch, which is
China's de facto embassy in the colony, said Hong Kong had set a
bad precedent in its handling of the case and had harmed
cooperation between the governments.
   Yang Yang, 20, the No. 2 swimmer in China, left Hong Kong for
San Francisco Tuesday after being released from a detention center
under a discretionary section of the immigration code. He was
arrested Sept. 23 for having an expired visa.
   The swimmer earlier had sought political asylum in Hong Kong,
saying he feared Chinese authorities would jail him for
participating in pro-democracy marches in this British colony, but
the asylum request was denied.
   ``This has not only marred cooperation between the two sides in
this respect but will for sure adversely affect the normal contacts
between the residents of the mainland and Hong Kong,'' the
unidentified Xinhua spokesman said in remarks issued by the news
agency.
   Hundreds of thousands of Hong Kong residents visit China each
year, with border crossings particularly heavy during the
traditional Chinese holidays.
   The agency, in paraphrasing the spokesman, said the case ``will
also cast its shadow over the cooperation between the two sides in
other fields. Only the Hong Kong government should be responsible
for all the consequences.''
   A week earlier, Xinhua issued a statement saying Chinese who
participated in pro-democracy activities in Hong Kong would not
face reprisals after returning to China.
   The incident comes at a particularly sensitive time for Hong
Kong, which reverts to Chinese sovereignty in 1997. China has
promised the territory can retain its capitalist system for 50
years and enjoy a ``high degree of autonomy.''
   But confidence in the territory's future suffered a serious
setback when the Chinese army suppressed the pro-democracy movement
in Beijing. Tension between China and the Hong Kong and British
governments tends to exacerbate the problem.
   Local media reported that Yang was granted a non-immigrant visa
giving him permission to stay in the United States for six months.
   He could later travel to Taiwan, where he has been offered
refuge as part of the Nationalist government's plan to grant
residence to Chinese who played important roles in the
pro-democracy movement in China or elsewhere.
   The pro-Beijing New Evening Post today reported that Yang said
after arriving in San Francisco that he would not seek political
asylum in the United States and that he does not know whether he
will go to another country.
</TEXT>
