<FIRST>r i PM-Angola-US     10-04 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola-US,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan President Criticizes United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUANDA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Eduardo dos Santos said
today that his country will not normalize relations with the United
States unless Washington stops aiding Angolan rebels.
   Speaking to reporters at his Futungo de Belas residence outside
Luanda, dos Santos said that despite promising peace initiatives
``war continues in Angola and Mozambique and it is caused by
foreign interference.''
   He indicated Angola would make no more concessions in its quest
for U.S. recognition of Luanda's Marxist government.
   Angola signed a truce with the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola on June 22, but peace talks with the
U.S.-backed guerrilla group broke off after military clashes
continued.
   Western diplomats in Luanda say dos Santos is disappointed by
U.S. officials, who dangled the carrot of recognition to forge
regional peace accords signed in December by Angola, Cuba and South
Africa, and then to get the Luanda government to sit at the
negotiating table with Angolan guerrillas.
   U.S. officials say diplomatic ties will be withheld until Luanda
agrees to free elections.
</TEXT>
