<FIRST>r a PM-NAACPSettlement     10-04 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NAACP Settlement,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement Ends Lawsuit Against Housing Authority</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city has agreed to pay some 1,500 minority
families up to $3,000 each to settle a housing discrimination suit
filed by the NAACP.
   The approximately $3 million agreement was to be signed today in
federal court, settling the lawsuit filed against the Boston
Housing Authority in 1988.
   Under the settlement, the largest group of people eligible for
up to $2,500 each in damages comprises 1,058 families who say they
applied for apartments in predominantly white housing projects in
the Charlestown, South Boston and East Boston neighborhoods over
the last decade but were passed over for white applicants.
   ``We hope this sends a message to the institutions that
discrimination costs,'' said Dianne Wilkerson, chairwoman of the
housing committee of the Boston chapter of the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.
   About 450 other families are eligible for damages of $1,000 to
$3,000 each.
   Under the settlement, the city admitted no wrongdoing.
   The settlement also requires the BHA to create a $500,000 fund
to make grants to encourage integration in the city's public
housing.
</TEXT>
