<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1118EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-HijackSentencing 2ndLd-Writethru s0574-a0467 10-04 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijack Sentencing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, s0574-a0467,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Younis Given 30 Years In Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese hijacker lured into U.S. custody
was sentenced today to 30 years in federal prison for comandeering
a Jordanian airliner in 1985 and holding its crew and passengers
hostage for 30 hours.
   U.S. District Court Judge Aubrey Robinson sentenced Fawaz Younis
to 30 years in prison for taking hostages, 20 years for aircraft
piracy and five years for conspiracy. The sentences are to run
concurrently.
   Robinson could have imposed a term of life imprisonment, but he
noted that no one on the plane had been killed. He said, however,
that a lengthy prison term is required because time ``will never
wipe out what is in the minds'' of the passengers and crew
subjected to the hijacking.
   Younis, who has spent the past two years in custody, could be
eligible for parole in eight years, U.S. Attorney Jay Stephens said
after the sentencing.
   Stephens said the term is ``fair'' and ``substantial'' and that
it sends ``a clear message'' to people ``who would engage in acts
of international terrorism.''
   At his sentencing, the convicted hijacker asked the judge for
leniency, saying he is not a terrorist and that he treated the two
Americans aboard the airliner as ``friends.''
   Younis was convicted March 14 of storming the Jordanian airliner
in Beirut with four other gunmen and holding the 70 passengers and
crew hostage for 30 hours. All aboard, including two Americans,
were freed before the plane was blown up.
   In 1987, Younis was lured aboard a yacht in the Mediterranean on
the pretext of a drug deal and grabbed by undercover FBI agents.
U.S. officials have hailed the case as a strong signal that the
United States will take whatever steps necessary to deal with
terrorists.
   Younis was found innocent of threatening violence against
passengers, destroying a civilian aircraft and carrying explosive
devices aboard the plane.
   ``Why does the American government want to depict me as a
terrorist, and believe that I am a threat to it?'' Younis asked in
a letter to the judge last week.
   He said there is ``a huge difference between me, and those
others'' involved in terrorism.
   Younis, a member of the Amal movement, said he was instructed by
his superiors to hijack an aircraft and fly it to Tunis, Tunisia,
where a meeting of Arab League representatives was in progress.
   During the hijacking, he read a declaration demanding the league
decide that one Arab nation allow all Palestinians to settle in the
country and that Palestinians be removed from Lebanon.
   ``The thorny problem for this court is that Mr. Younis has
previously stated and continues to believe that his actions were
political in nature,'' his lawyer, Francis Carter, said in court
papers.
   In a memo to the judge last week, the U.S. attorney's office
said Younis was one of the members of Amal who held American
hostages in Beirut in connection with the hijacking of TWA Flight
847, days after the hijacking of the Jordanian airliner.
   In the TWA hijacking, Navy diver Robert Stethem was murdered.
   Younis admitted he had been among the first to enter the TWA
airliner when it landed at Beirut Airport, said the government's
sentencing memo.
   Carter said Hezbollah terrorists, not the Amal movement,
hijacked the TWA plane. The Amal, at the request of the U.S.
government, worked to negotiate the release of the hostages, taking
custody of some to prevent all the passengers and crew from falling
into the hands of Hezbollah, Carter said.
   ``No one from the Amal movement was aboard the plane when ...
Stethem was killed,'' Carter said.
</TEXT>
