<FIRST>u w PM-Salinas     10-04 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salinas,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Leader Promises US Congress Action on Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
told a joint meeting of Congress today his country intends ``to
eradicate drug trafficking at its very roots'' but he said the war
against drugs globally is being lost.
   Salinas, who is here on a state visit, also stepped up his
campaign for greater access for Mexican products to U.S. markets,
descibing as an ``inequitable paradox'' the relative openness of
Mexico to foreign imports compared with the United States.
   While pledging a continued all-out effort to curb drug
smuggling, Salinas ruled out joint U.S.-Mexican military operations
to fight the traffickers.
   ``Mexico intends to eradicate drug trafficking at its very roots
in the sphere that falls under its responsibility,'' Salinas said,
speaking in Spanish while his listerners read from copies
translated into English.
   ``This world fight is also our own,'' he said. He added that
mutual finger pointing about who is to blame for continued drug use
wastes time and effort that should be spent attacking the common
enemy.
   Salinas received a warm welcome from the assembled gathering
when he entered the House chamber, a reflection of the marked
improvement in U.S.-Mexican relations since he assumed the
presidency 10 months ago.
   But, consistent with most addresses by foreign leaders before
joint meetings of Congress, only a small percentage of the 535
voting members actually were present. Most of the seats were filled
by congressional pages.
   Salinas, who met on Tuesday with President Bush, said there is a
``mature and responsible understanding'' of the links in the ``drug
chain of terror.'' He added that there is greater acceptance in the
United States regarding the importance of giving greater emphasis
to reducing demand for drugs.
   Previously, the United States put much of its focus on reducing
the supply through interdiction and other efforts.
   While stressing Mexico's willingness to cooperate, Salinas said
the struggle worldwide against drug use has suffered setbacks.
   ``When we see the magnitude of the fight against drugs, we must
honestly ask ourselves: are we winning or losing the war? I think
that, at the world level, we are losing and that is unacceptable.''
He said the solution lies in more cooperation among governments.
   On trade, Salinas said Mexico needs ``greater reciprocity'' to
ensure that it will continue to be one of the most open economies
in the world.
   ``Our country is practically free of (trade) barriers, but we
continue confronting them in the United States,'' Salinas said.
``Let us resolve this inequitable paradox. We seek greater access
to the textile and steel markets and the Generalized System of
Preferences. We want a bilateral agreement that will break down
trade barriers, sector by sector.''
   U.S. officials have expressed irritation with Salinas' portrayal
of the United States as a protectionist nation. They point out that
two-thirds of Mexico's exports come to the United States and that
Mexico had a $2.7 billion surplus in its U.S. trade last year on
total two-way trade of about $44 billion.
</TEXT>
