<HEAD>Appeals Court Endanger's Buffalo Mayoral Candidate's Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wilbur Trammell's bid to become Buffalo's
first black mayor has been set back by a court ruling invalidating
his independent party petitions.
   The former judge said he would appeal the decision reached
Tuesday night.
   The ruling could keep Trammell off the November ballot and allow
James D. Griffin to run with no ballot opposition for an
unprecedented fourth four-year term.
   In its unanimous decision, the appellate division of State
Supreme Court upheld a lower court ruling that petitions to place
Trammell on the ballot as an independent were invalid because he
failed to have a document notarized.
   Trammell said if his appeal fails, he will run as a write-in
candidate.
   ``Let the people of Buffalo, not the court, make a decision
about the mayor of Buffalo,'' he said.
