<HEAD>Police Storm Campus to Quell Riot in Zimbabwe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 50 arrests, government comment.
Pickup 5th pvs, `In a...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police fired tear gas today to
disperse university students protesting the arrest of two student
leaders.
   An estimated 4,000 students boycotted classes and many fought
running battles with baton-wielding riot squads, a student
spokesman said.
   Stones were thrown at police, and the windows of a limousine
used by the Zimbabwe University vice chancellor, Professor Walter
Kamba, were smashed by rioters, said the spokesman who requested
anonymity.
   Sporadic clashes continued throughout the day, and the
semi-official Zimbabwe Inter African News Agency said more than 50
protesters were arrested.
   It was not clear whether students were injured.
   Deputy Police Commissioner Douglas Chingoka was quoted as saying
that the unrest was ``very well under control.''
   The news agency said university officials were scheduled to meet
with President Robert Mugabe to discuss the student protests.
   In a leaflet distributed before the start of classes today,
student leaders called for a meeting on campus to discuss the
arrests today of student council members Arthur Mutambara and Enock
Chikweche.
   The leaflet said police surrounded and stormed a campus
residence and Mutambara was ``profusely bleeding'' after jumping
from a second-floor window in an effort to escape from police who
broke down the door of his bedroom.
   ``The notorious riot police have struck,'' said the leaflet. It
described student action in response as ``a matter of life and
death.''
   Student leaders said they believed Mutambara's arrest was
prompted by a statement he issued Oct. 2 criticizing the government
and university authorities.
   That statement said police banned a student meeting scheduled
for Sept. 29 to mark the first anniversary of a student
demonstration organized in 1988 to protest official corruption.
   In the past year, college students have staged several
demonstrations in which they accused the government of stifling
free expression and curbing academic freedoms.
   Education minister Fay Chung labeled students ``hooligans and
drunkards'' and said they were being manipulated by political
opponents to attack the government.
</TEXT>
