<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     10-04 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calls for Multiparty System in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Ante Markovic called for a
multiparty system as a solution for the country's growing economic
and political problems and charged that conservative Communists are
blocking his reforms.
   ``The logic of pluralistic ownership, which demands a system of
its own, will have to demand and open the society to a multiparty
system,'' he said in a television interview Tuesday night.
   Markovic's statement challenged a Communist Party ruling that
allows existence of multiple parties only under the the Socialist
Alliance, a Communist-dominated umbrella group.
   Despite growing calls for change, the Communist Party has so far
blocked the multiparty systems gradually being embraced by Warsaw
Pact allies Hungary and Poland.
   Markovic, however, said that the ``new socialism'' he has sought
to introduce as part of his market-oriented economic reforms is
meeting with growing resistance of the Communists.
   He said that opponents to his economic reforms expressed concern
that state property would become ``threatened'' by the planned
economic liberalization.
   ``I expect now an intensification of the conflict between
ideology and (reforms),'' Markovic said.
   Yugoslavia's annual inflation rate hit an all-time record of
nearly 1,200 percent, mostly due to sharp increases in the prices
of vital staples and services, such as electricity, meat and bread.
   Officials in the country's largest republic, Serbia, have said
they will demand Markovic's resignation if his program does not
quickly curb the rampant inflation.
   In a speech when he became premier in March, Markovic called an
open-market economy ``an ultimate achievement of mankind for which
no alternative has yet been found.''
   He demanded urgent introduction of stocks and bonds, private
initiative and entrepreneurship in the Yugoslav economy and an end
to state interference in the running of businesses.
   Other segments of the radical market-oriented economic reforms
underlined by Markovic would include the reshaping of the banking
system along Western lines, creation of a capital market, and an
end to state subsidies for loss-making enterprises.
   In addition to Europe's highest inflation rate Yugoslavia is
burdened by a $19 billion foreign debt, a 17 percent unemployment
rate and growing labor and ethnic unrest.
   Yugoslavia consists of six republics and two autonomous
provinces, each with its own government and party structure. Serbia
is dominated by hard-line Communists.
   The decentralized system of government and collective federal
presidency were devised in 1974 Constitution to prevent one
republic from gaining sway over the others, but it has resulted in
an ineffective government by compromise.
   In Yugoslavia, the federal government is generally responsible
for economic policy while the collective presidency, which appoints
the premier, dictates defense and foreign policy.
   But the bulk of political influence in the country is
concentrated in the Communist Party, with power dispersed in eight
often fractious central committees reflecting the administrative
division of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
