<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Marcos     10-04 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Marcos,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Backs Ban on Marcos' Body; Alleged Plot Against Aquino Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet on Wednesday backed the
ban on burying Ferdinand Marcos in the Philippines after the
defense chief reportedly warned legislators of threats against the
government.
   Also Wednesday, a government agency said it might help the
former president's widow, Imelda, with her legal problems if she
returns some assets acquired with money allegedly embezzled by
Marcos during his rule.
   Marcos, 72, died in Honolulu on Thursday. He had lived in exile
in Hawaii since he was ousted in a military-civilian uprising that
catapulted Corazon Aquino to power in February 1986.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow the body to be brought back
here for burial, citing possible civil unrest.
   Economic Planning Secretary Jesus Estanislao said Defense
Secretary Fidel Ramos told Cabinet members the country faced a
number of security risks if Marcos' body were returned.
   ``There are destabilization threats,'' Estanislao told The
Associated Press. ``He (Ramos) presented intelligence reports
including the possible assassination of the president.''
   Ramos refused to confirm or deny Estanislao's disclosure, saying
the briefing was ``highly classified.''
   Ramos said his department has been constantly receiving reports
about possible attempts against the government. He said the
20-year-old Communist insurgency remains the most serious threat.
   Marcos' followers have been linked to several of the six armed
attempts to topple Mrs. Aquino. But since Marcos' death,
demonstrations by his followers have been relatively small and
peaceful.
   On Tuesday, the Supreme Court agreed to consider a petition from
Marcos' supporters to allow Marcos to be buried in his homeland and
to allow his widow and three children to attend. They also are
barred from entering the Philippines.
   In a speech Wednesday, Mrs. Aquino repeated her concerns about
allowing the Marcos family in.
   ``I know the threat that this man poses to the country I am
sworn to protect, yet I know the loneliness of exile and the pain
of being struck by death without setting foot on one's native
soil,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   Imelda Marcos has been banned from leaving the United States
pending her trial in New York in March on charges of embezzling
Philippine government money and investing some of it in the United
States. The Marcoses were indicted last October, and Mrs. Marcos is
free on $5 million bail.
   Augusto Villarin, a deputy chief of the Presidential Commission
on Good Government, said if Mrs. Marcos surrendered a substantial
portion of the ``hidden wealth,'' the government might intercede
with U.S. authorities to drop the charges.
   ``My common sense tells me that if the victim, which is the
Philippine government, has been satisfied that the stolen wealth
has been returned, maybe we can request the U.S. government to be
lenient,'' Villarin said.
   The commission was appointed to recover the estimated $10
billion the Marcoses allegedly stole during his 20-year rule.
Marcos denied the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
