<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     10-04 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Leading Opposition Members Jail in Abortion Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two leading members of Burma's opposition
movement were ordered jailed for three years for allegedly
sheltering a man whose girlfriend had an illegal abortion, official
media reported Wednesday.
   The Working People's Daily said the opposition leaders, Win Tin
and Ngwe Hlaing, of the National League for Democracy, were accused
of sheltering 22-year-old Soe Thein.
   Soe, his girlfriend and two doctors who performed the abortion
have since been sentenced to 10 years in jail, the newspaper said.
   It said Soe and his girlfriend are members of the youth wing of
the National League for Democracy, the most popular opposition
group to emerge from a pro-democracy uprising last year.
   Win Tin was a member of the National League's nine-man central
executive committee, and Ngwe Hlaing was an organizer for the group
in Rangoon. They were arrested July 4.
   ``It is in keeping with the line that none are ever persecuted
for their political activities _ only for breaking the law in some
way _ that they have chosen to come down extremely savagely on an
alleged abortion,'' said a Rangoon-based Western diplomat in a
telephone interview from Bangkok. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Abortion is illegal in Burma, but prosecution has been rare.
   In July, the military government began a general clampdown on
the National League and other active opposition groups.
   On July 20, Aung San Suu Kyi, the general secretary of the
league, and its chairman, Tin Oo, were put under house arrest on
charges of subversion. Since then, Western diplomats say several
thousand other activists have been detained.
   The U.S. Embassy in Rangoon says that it has ``credible''
reports that many of those arrested have been tortured, some until
death.
   Gen. Saw Maung's government seized power in Sept. 1988 after a
series of bloody crackdowns on dissent.
</TEXT>
