<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Poland     10-04 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Poland,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Arrive, Some Wet From Swimming River Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 130 East Germans, some telling
desperate stories about swimming rivers and evading border police,
arrived at the West German embassy Wednesday seeking refuge and
passage to the West.
   The newcomers brought to about 400 the number of people waiting
in Poland for word on their bid to reach West Germany.
   A West German diplomat urged the refugees to be calm and not to
fear giving accurate information as they were registered, even
though some had crossed the border illegally.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said in a
radio interview that he expected Poland ``to keep its word not to
send any refugees back to the GDR (East Germany) against their
will.''
   An Interior Ministry spokesman said there were ``mass scale''
attempts by East Germans to enter Poland illegally and that border
guards had turned back some East Germans before they reached Poland.
   There have been no confirmed reports of East Germans being
handed back over to East Germany once they are on Polish soil.
   Many East Germans said they headed for Poland after learning the
border to Czechoslovakia had been closed. However, East Germans
need permits from their government to travel to Poland, and several
said these were now unavailable.
   Genscher said he expected a solution would be found for the
refugees in Poland, although none was announced when permission was
given Tuesday night for about 11,000 East Germans to leave Prague.
   When the two Germanys reached their first agreement about
refugees, about 800 left Poland for West Germany by train early
Sunday, following thousands of others from Prague.
   Among those waiting for a second solution to the crisis are some
who missed the weekend release by minutes.
   One father said that as his family drove up Sunday to learn they
were too late, ``We panicked. We didn't know what would be.''
   ``But we were sure we wouldn't go back,'' he said. ``And then it
turned out we were not alone.''
   Wednesday's arrivals huddled outside a kiosk near the West
German Embassy in a residential section of Warsaw, filling out
forms and waiting for buses to transport them to hotels 24 miles
from the capital.
   Some trembled in clothing wet from their overnight swim across
the Neisse and Oder rivers that form the border. An embassy
official brought a carload of blankets.
   Reports circulated of soldiers massing at the border, and some
refugees told of hiding from guards.
   Some said Polish border guards had chased refugees. Earlier
groups of East Germans had said Polish authorities appeared to make
little effort to stop the crossings.
   Col. Andrzej Sadlinski, the spokesman for the Interior Ministry,
confirmed that many East Germans had tried to cross the border
illegally. He said Poland was obligated to prevent such crossings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
