<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   10-04 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: future flight.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 28
   Statesman-Journal, Salem, Ore., on Dr. Elizabeth Morgan:
   It doesn't take a sharp legal mind to figure out that something
went wrong with our justice system when a mother who wouldn't tell
the court where her daughter is must spend more time in jail than
drug dealers and rapists.
   Dr. Elizabeth Morgan, (arguing that her ex-husband sexually
abused her 7-year old daughter), refused to produce Hilary for
court-ordered visits. Morgan (spent) 759 days in jail for contempt
of court.
   It took a public outcry and an act of Congress to free her. But
the case isn't finished, and she could be jailed again for
continuing to defy the court. ...
   The law that tries to force a person to obey legitimate legal
orders, especially when it involves a youngster, is sound. It's the
procedure and the judge's interpretation that are out of whack. ...
   Custodial interference cases of this sort demand a different
kind of justice and punishment. And now that Congress has seen the
injustice of sentencing Morgan to an indeterminate sentence ...
without a trial or a conviction, maybe it will change the laws on
contempt of court.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 1
   Santa Barbara (Calif.) News-Press on education vs. apathy:
   When President Bush invited the nation's governors and educators
to Charlottesville, Va., last week to establish broad educational
goals, they were there _ along with 900 newspaper and television
reporters. It was a happening.
   Two weeks ago, when the Santa Barbara Council on Alcoholism and
Drug Abuse invited 7,500 parents to attend a presentation intended
to help them keep their children in school and out of the clutches
of chemical dependency, organizers were justifiably stunned and
bewildered when only 30 people attended. For them it was a poignant
moment _ a stark realization that this essential ingredient in the
formula for educational success is often missing.
   In convening the nation's governors for only the third time in
U.S. history, President Bush, who has vowed to be the ``education
president,'' implored parents to become full partners in the
education of their children. ...
   For the United States to regain its standing in a rapidly
changing world as the best and brightest, it will not be a measure
of George Bush or the 50 governors. It will be a measure of
individual commitment to do better.
   If Johnny can't read or write, or add and subtract, the solution
ultimately lies in the living room and the classroom with each and
every parent, student and teacher _ interested, engaged and
determined.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 30
   Lawrence (Kan.) Journal-World on a national education curriculum:
   Gov. Mike Hayden (of Kansas) is on the right track with his
opposition to a national education curriculum. Some of the current
problems in the U.S. education system probably can be attributed to
an increasing lack of local control over schools.
   When teachers and administrators get too tied up with fulfilling
state mandates or measuring up to federal standards, they find it
harder and harder to provide the kind of education that may be
needed in their individual communities.
   To say that schools in inner-city Chicago should teach the same
classes that are taught in rural Baldwin (Kan.) is to ignore the
socio-economic and cultural differences that exist between those
two areas.
</TEXT>
