<FIRST>r i AM-India-Blast     10-04 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Blast,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Kills Four in Crowded Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A time bomb exploded in a crowded market
Wednesday and police said four people were killed, including three
members of a family involved in a land dispute.
   Police reported four other people wounded in the explosion in a
parking area at the Sadar Bazaar in northern New Delhi. Residents
of the area said 13 people were hurt.
   Those killed included the wife and two granddaughers, aged 4 and
8, of Abdul Razak, who operates the parking lot on the disputed
land. The fourth victim was a customer.
   At least four scooters in the lot were badly damaged and many
were spattered with blood.
   Razak, 65, his white T-shirt stained with blood, said the
bombing probably resulted from a land dispute with a neighboring
shopkeeper that has been in court more than 25 years.
   Police did not confirm the allegation, but a senior official
said they were ``investigating all angles.'' No arrests were
reported.
   Investigators searched the debris for clues and remnants of the
bomb, the police said.
   A senior officer at the site, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the bomb was put in a plastic jug wrapped in cloth
and hidden under a wooden platform where Razak's relatives were
sitting. A canvas thatch over the parking area was blown down when
the bomb went off just after 10 a.m.
   A member of the bomb disposal squad said: ``It was a crude bomb
but had a powerful blast.''
</TEXT>
