<DOCNO> AP891004-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Hugo 1stLd-Writethru a0490 10-04 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0490,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Lift Bridge Damaged in Storm</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with bridge repair under way. PICKS
UP 8th graf, `Criticism of....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army engineers raised a bridge dangling
at a 45-degree angle in the water today in an effort to restore the
link to two islands cut off from the South Carolina mainland by
Hurricane Hugo 13 days ago.
   High tide this morning helped lift the 500,000-ton bridge, and
workers used a crane to restore it to its stand.
   Officials said they hoped to have the ends of the Ben Sawyer
Bridge connected to the road later in the day so that it could be
inspected and reopened to traffic Thursday to hurricane-devastated
Sullivan's Island and the Isle of Palms.
   Without the bridge, building and cleaning supplies have had to
be flown or ferried over in boats.
   ``The people just wanted to get back in their homes and get
started digging out,'' said Melvin Anderegg, mayor of Sullivan's
Island. ``Everywhere you look over there, people are cleaning up
and moving things.''
   The Coast Guard had to turn away dozens of boaters who filled
the waterway to watch the bridge repair. Officials nevertheless
were eager for the public to know that life is returning to normal
in an area that boasts 60 miles of beaches and attracted 10 million
visitors last year.
   More than 1,000 truckloads of debris a day are being removed
from Charleston, the city where the Civil War began.
   ``We've bounced back from Hurricane Hugo and visitors should not
cancel their plans to come to Charleston but should come right
ahead,'' said Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr., who wore a T-shirt saying
``Charleston S.C. We're Going Strong.''
   The mayor said Tuesday that 90 percent of the city's hotels have
reopened, and a 9 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew should be lifted shortly.
   Criticism of federal relief efforts continued along with the
recovery.
   Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., called for the General Accounting
Office, Congress' watchdog agency, to investigate the
``incompetent'' work of the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   Hollings again complained that the agency has not opened enough
offices in the 22 South Carolina counties declared a federal
disaster area. There are about 10 offices opened in those areas.
   FEMA spokesman Bill McAda said he would welcome an
investigation, and said the agency was fulfilling its role of
aiding long-term recovery.
   ``I believe we're doing that and under the circumstances doing
it as fast as it can be expected to be done,'' he said.
   That view was seconded by Marilyn Quayle, the vice president's
wife, who helped at disaster and American Red Cross centers in
Charleston on Tuesday.
   ``From what I've been able to observe, FEMA, very frankly, got a
bum rap,'' she said.
   The agency has 350 workers in South Carolina to process
applications from people seeking low-interest loans and grants to
rebuild homes and businesses.
   Hurricane Hugo roared into the South Carolina coast Sept. 21,
leaving at least 18 dead, 50,000 homeless, 270,000 jobless, and a
swath of damage extending into North Carolina. In all, 29 people
were killed on the U.S. mainland.
   Damage in South Carolina alone has been estimated at at least $3
billion.
   In the community of Murrells Inlet about 10 miles south of
Myrtle Beach, author Mickey Spillane examined the wreckage of his
home and office, where he has written detective novels since 1963.
   One section of a wall was gone, and first editions of his books,
including ``I, The Jury,'' and ``My Gun is Quick,'' had
disappeared, as well as a manuscript in progress. But the author
wasn't too upset.
   ``Hey, not to worry,'' he said. ``I'll make (the manuscript) up
in two weeks, ... maybe three. That's how long it takes to write a
book.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
