<FIRST>u w PM-US-Angola 3rdLd-Writethru a0585 10-04 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Angola, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0585,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mobutu, Bush Meet to Bolster Truce Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 2 grafs after 6th graf pvs to update with Van
Dunem comments; Picks up 7th graf pvs: At a...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zaire's President Mobutu Sese Seko and
President Bush met today in efforts to bolster the faltering truce
accord between Angola's government and its U.S.-armed opposition.
   Mobutu, in New York to attend the United Nations General
Assembly, made a quick trip to Washington for the meeting as part
of intensive behind-the-scenes U.S. efforts to prevent the collapse
of the agreement reached through Zairean mediation in June.
   The two leaders met for nearly 45 minutes. Mobutu declined to
answer reporters' questions as he left the White House.
   Also in Washington today were Jonas Savimbi, the rebel who leads
the Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), and Pedro
van Dunem, the foreign minister of Angola's Soviet-backed
government.
   U.S. officials have ruled out a meeting among all three sides
but not a possible reconciliation meeting between Savimbi and
Mobutu. Savimbi is scheduled to meet Bush on Thursday.
   Mobutu, who has served as the major conduit of an estimated $40
million in U.S. arms and other supplies to UNITA annually, is
supporting the Angolan government's interpretation of the June
accords. President Eduardo dos Santos contends Savimbi agreed to
temporary exile and to integrating his forces into the Angolan
armed forces.
   At a news conference here Wednesday, Van Dunem accused Savimbi
of not being ``willing really to commit himself to a process of
peace.'' He told reporters the United States should support the
agreement reached last June, including Savimbi's exile and the
integration of his forces into the government military.
   Van Dunem said he had conveyed these thoughts to members of the
House of Representatives subcommittee on Africa and would tell
secretary of state James Baker the same thing when he meets him,
probably next week.
   On Tuesday, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. complained at a hearing of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee that Mobutu had cut the flow
of U.S. arms to Savimbi's forces, asking Herman J. Cohen, assistant
secretary of state for African affairs, why that had been done.
   Cohen said that while it was an ``open secret'' that the United
States has been aiding Savimbi in his struggle against Angola's
Marxist government, details of the operation are classified.
   Helms said his question was not based on classified material and
added: ``I can say publicly that the supply lines have been cut and
you and I know why and who did it.'' Helms asserted that ``Mobutu
got his hackles up because Savimbi wouldn't knuckle under'' to the
terms of the peace plan.
   This week, both sides are currying U.S. support in meetings with
administration officials, members of Congress and the media.
   Savimbi is arguing for continued U.S. aid _ he already gets one
of the largest sums of covert assistance _ and for support of free
elections that would allow UNITA to share power.
   Angola is asking primarily for U.S. recognition, arguing that it
has fulfilled Washington's main demand by agreeing to the
withdrawal of more than 50,000 Cuban troops by 1991. U.S. officials
say the Cuban pullout from Angola is proceeding as planned but that
diplomatic recognition will be withheld until the government agrees
to free elections.
   Angola is backed by a coalition of advocacy groups that has
organized media briefings and demonstrations against Savimbi this
week.
   Half-page ads this week in The Washington Post and The New York
Times, paid for by the Angolan government, said Savimbi was a
``dictator'' here to press for more covert aid.
   UNITA is represented by a prestigious array of lobbyists and
public relations experts.
   UNITA supporters on Tuesday released the content of a letter
written by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, asking Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh to investigate a major Angola supporter, the TransAfrica
lobbying organization.
   Hatch said TransAfrica may have violated the Foreign Agents
Registration Act by accepting more than $2,000 from the Angolan
mission to the United Nations.
   Randall Robinson, the director of TransAfrica who just returned
from a fact-finding trip to Angola, said the money went to buy
tickets for the organization's annual dinner in which some 50
African and Caribbean countries took part.
   A Justice Department spokesman said the Hatch request had been
forwarded to the Criminal Division.
</TEXT>
