<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Fire 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 10-04 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0556,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Burns Historic Hotel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with missing men found, fireman
hurt. Pickup 6th pvs, `The Langham...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire engulfed part of a historic hotel being
restored in central London today and one fireman was injured when a
section of roof collapsed, the Fire Brigade said.
   Firemen called off a search for two plumbers after they were
found outside the building, said a brigade spokesman, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   One hundred firefighters and more than 15 fire trucks with
aerial ladders tired to control the blaze at the old Langham Hotel.
The top four floors and roof of the 10-story building were ablaze,
and it took two hours to put out the fire, the spokesman said.
   One firemen was taken to University College Hospital with a
possible broken leg after part of the roof collapsed while he was
inside, the spokesman said.
   The Langham Hotel on Portland Place, built in 1864, was the
forerunner of London's grand hotels, constructed in the style of a
Florentine palace with plaster-relief ceilings and mosaic flooring
by Italian craftsmen.
   More than 2,000 people attended the gala opening including the
future King Edward VII. The hotel remained a favorite of the rich
and famous including the exiled French emperor Napoleon III,
Italian conductor Arturo Toscanini and American author Mark Twain.
   Between World War I and World War II, as the center of
fashionable London moved west and more luxury hotels were built,
the Langham declined in popularity but still retained many of its
aristocratic patrons.
   It suffered extensive damage in 1940 from a German land mine and
was forced to close. It is now being refurbished as a 400-bed hotel
and conference center.
</TEXT>
