<FIRST>u a PM-SchoolTakeover 1stLd-Writethru a0611 10-04 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Takeover, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0611,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Jersey Seizes Jersey City School System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to ADD background on Jersey City and other
takeover laws; PICKS UP 12th graf pvs, `This summer ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state seized control of Jersey City's
28,000-student school system today, making it the biggest urban
district in the nation to be taken over for failing to do its job.
   State officials charged that the school system in the gritty,
impoverished community across the Hudson River from New York City
is academically bankrupt and rife with corruption, mismanagement
and patronage.
   At least four other states have school takeover laws, and two _
New Mexico and Kentucky _ have seized districts deemed failures.
   The state Board of Education gave final approval to the takeover
and appointed Elena J. Scambio to a three-year term as
superintendent. Under New Jersey law, the state has five years to
make improvements.
   The move gives the state extraordinary power in Jersey City, the
state's second-largest district and the first to be taken over by
the state. Ms. Scambio can fire administrators, abolish the local
board of education and set policy.
   The Jersey City school system has a staff of 3,322 and a budget
for the current year of about $180 million.
   Enrollment is 44 percent black, 34 percent Hispanic and 13
percent white. Fifty-five percent of the students are involved in
compensatory, bilingual or special education programs.
   Today's decision was expected and ends a long process that was
strongly pushed by Gov. Thomas H. Kean, who has billed himself
``the education governor.''
   Ms. Scambio, who will give up her job as Essex County schools
superintendent, has vowed to make Jersey City a national model of
urban education. But her immediate plans were unclear.
   State board Vice President Robert A. Woodruff, reading a
resolution, said the district's problems were ``deep-rooted and
endemic. The Jersey City board of education totally failed to meet
its obligations.''
   There are ``severe long-standing, deep-rooted deficiencies
permeating all aspects of the school system,'' the resolution said.
   The state had cited political intrusion in hiring, poor test
scores, failure to provide a safe and clean environment, violations
of bidding laws, failure to provide for handicapped children and
unauthorized use of funds.
   ``The idea of takeover does not come easily to me,'' said
Education Commissioner Saul Cooperman. ``I've always believed the
role of the state department is to help others help themselves.''
   Cooperman said the state is initiating the takeover ``not
because we want to. It's because we have to. If not us, who? If not
now, when?''
   National education groups say they will closely monitor the
takeover.
   Jean McDonald, a researcher for the National Governors
Association, said Kentucky, South Carolina, Texas and New Mexico
have laws allowing state takeovers of failing districts.
   She said laws in Illinois and Arkansas let the state eliminate
deficient districts, an Ohio law allows the state to revoke a
troubled district's charter and Georgia may impose heavy financial
penalties on such districts.
   This summer, an administrative law judge agreed state officials
had the power to take over the district. He noted that some of the
district's textbooks are more than 30 years old.
   Jersey City officials bitterly fought the takeover, saying the
problems were caused by a prior administration and that the state
trumped up its case against the district.
   Opponents also question whether the state can improve conditions
in Jersey City, saying New Jersey's system of funding schools has
crippled urban districts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
