<FIRST>u i PM-PlaneCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0619 10-04 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Crash, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0619,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Tanker Crashes; Three Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Air Force confirming explosion,
no indication of trouble; PICKS UP 10th graf pvs, `The noise ...'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PERTH-ANDOVER, New Brunswick (AP) _ A U.S. Air Force tanker jet
exploded in the air just above the American border today, killing
at least three crewmen, authorities said. The fourth crewman was
missing and feared dead.
   ``I've never seen anything like it _ it was like fireworks,''
said Paul McNally, a resident who said he saw the explosion before
dawn.
   The KC-135 was returning to Loring Air Force Base in Limestone,
Maine, from a refueling mission when it went down around 6 a.m. and
set woods on fire near Perth-Andover, a community of about 1,900,
the Air Force said.
   Loring spokeswoman Capt. Kellie Rebscher said that the plane
exploded in the air and that a military-civilian panel would seek
to determine the cause.
   Rebscher said the crew had been in radio contact with the Loring
control tower minutes before the explosion but gave no indication
of trouble. She said the plane had no ``black box'' cockpit voice
recorder.
   Three crewmen were confirmed dead, and a search was on for the
fourth, said Air Force Sgt. Darlene Bailey. The Air Force said in a
tape-recorded statement that there was a ``low probability of any
survivors.''
   The KC-135 Stratotanker is a Boeing 707 reconfigured as a tanker
for refueling fighters and bombers in the air. It has no ejection
mechanism, but has emergency exits.
   Rebscher said she did not know how much fuel the plane was
carrying or its altitude at the time of the explosion.
   ``The noise! My whole house shook _ windows and everything,''
said Anita Davenport, who lives across from the crash site.
   Ray Gamblin, who owns the woods where the debris landed, said he
was on the scene in less than five minutes and saw no sign of
survivors or parachutes.
   He said chunks of twisted metal and other debris were scattered
over a half-mile radius around his farm.
   ``The flight pattern goes right over our house all the time,''
he said. ``If it had been a few seconds later, it would have been
right in our yard probably.''
   Sgt. Charlton Ritchie, a Loring spokesman, said the four crewmen
were experienced and were training to keep their skills sharp.
   An Alaska National Guard KC-135 exploded and burned Sept. 20 at
Eielson Air Force Base, killing two people. On Jan. 31, all 19
people aboard a KC-135 died when it crashed on takeoff from Dyess
Air Force Base in Texas. A KC-135 crash in 1988 killed six crewmen
at Wurtsmith Air Force Base in Michigan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
