<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Secretariat     10-04 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Secretariat,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Triple Crown Winner Secretariat is Destroyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretariat, who in 1973 became racing's first
Triple Crown winner in 25 years, was destroyed today at age 19
because of a painful hoof ailment.
   ``Of course, I'm terribly sorry to lose an old friend,'' said
owner Helen Chenery. ``As long as he was alive, his memories had
more immediacy. The dream is over.''
   Secretariat had an incurable inflammation known as laminitis. He
was put down at Claiborne Farm, where he had been put out to stud,
said Gus Koch, the farm's assistant manager.
   Koch said Secretariat's condition rapidly worsened on Tuesday
and put the chestnut stallion in extreme pain for the first time.
   Secretariat was to be buried at the farm today, close to
stablemate Riva Ridge, who won the 1972 Kentucky Derby and Belmont
Stakes.
   Secretariat became the ``people's horse'' when he won the Triple
Crown with a 31-length victory in the Belmont, setting records
there and at the Kentucky Derby. The other Triple Crown race is the
Preakness.
   Not since Citation in 1948 had a horse won all three races.
   ``Red,'' as farmhands referred to the horse, was something of a
disappointment in the breeding shed. He ranked No. 25 among leading
active sires.
   ``Everybody still wants him to duplicate himself, and I just
don't think that will happen,'' said John Sosby, manager of
Claiborne Farm.
</TEXT>
