<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Riot     10-04 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe-Riot,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Closed After Students, Police Clash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's only university was closed
Wednesday after thousands of students protesting the arrests of two
student leaders clashed with hundreds of riot police. Fifty
students were arrested.
   All 8,000 students were ordered to leave the University of
Zimbabwe campus by noon Thursday. Police sealed off entrances to
the campus as darkness fell. Riot squads barred students from
entering the campus.
   The violence began after the arrests of student council
officials Arthur Mutambara and Enock Chikweche. In a leaflet
distributed before the start of classes, student leaders called for
a meeting to discuss the arrests.
   The leaflet alleged police surrounded and stormed a campus
residence and that Mutambara was ``profusely bleeding'' after
jumping from a second-floor window in an effort to escape police.
   Student leaders said they believed Mutambara's arrest was
prompted by a statement he issued Oct. 2 criticizing the government
and university authorities.
   The University of Zimbabwe's vice chancellor, Walter Kamba,
announced the closing at a news conference after conferring with
President Robert Mugabe.
   Kamba called the move ``regrettable and sad'' and said it was a
university decision and not the government's.
   But student leaders, who requested anonymity, told The
Associated Press they believed Mugabe had personally ordered the
shutdown because of widespread student disillusionment with the
leadership over top-level corruption.
   About 4,000 students boycotted classes and many fought running
battles with baton-wielding riot squads through the day, a student
spokesman said. Rioters threw stones at police and smashed the
windows of a limousine used by Kamba.
   Sporadic clashes continued throughout the day and the
semi-official Zimbabwe Inter African News Agency said more than 50
protesters were arrested. They could face up to five years in
prison. Students said police injured several protesters.
   In the past year, college students have staged several
demonstrations in which they accused the government of stifling
free expression and curbing academic freedoms. They also have
protested official corruption.
   Education minister Fay Chung has called students ``hooligans and
drunkards'' who were being manipulated by political opponents to
attack the government.
</TEXT>
