<FIRST>u w PM-Panama-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0652 10-04 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Was Noriega in Custody? ^Eds: RECASTS lead to clarify attribution
and UPDATES with Fitzwater comments. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panamanian rebels who tried to oust Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega had him ``in their clutches'' for several
hours, according to some U.S. officials who said today they are
mystified as to why the insurgents let him go.
   The spokesman for President Bush said, ``We don't' really know
if that was the case,'' and an attorney who represents Noriega
disputed the account.
   The officials, asking not to be identified, said Noriega was in
the custody of the rebels for four to five hours after taking over
the Defense Force headquarters Tuesday.
   ``It's crazy, I don't understand it,'' one official said when
asked why the insurgents decided to free Noriega.
   The account was disputed by one of Noriega's Miami-based
lawyers, Raymond Takiff, who said the general was away from the
headquarters when the fighting began. Takiff said he spoke with
Defense Force spokesman Edgardo Lopez while Noriega stood at
Lopez's side.
   Shortly before the rebellion was put down Tuesday afternoon,
Jose Blandon, a former Noriega aide, told reporters in Washington
that he was informed by one of the leaders of the insurrection by
telephone that Noriega had been wounded while in rebel custody.
   But when Noriega made a brief public appearance after the
rebellion was defeated, there was no obvious indication of any
injury.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said today that the
rebels on Tuesday ``indicated they had Noriega'' in custody, but
``We don't' really know if that was the case.''
   He said these individuals, whom he described as low-level, also
``made it clear they weren't willing to give up Noriega,'' to face
drug trafficking charges in the United States, the spokesman added.
</TEXT>
