<FIRST>u a AM-FaxAngels Bjt   10-04 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fax Angels, Bjt,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rembrandt's Angel Flies via Fax</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Copies of a Rembrandt angel winged their way
around the world via fax Wednesday, lighting in Amsterdam,
Jerusalem and Tokyo to commemorate the 320th anniversary of the
artist's death.
   ``Rembrandt would have liked this,'' said Max Alexenberg, the
American artist responsible for the electronic event, saying the
master was himself something of a technology buff, using the latest
equipment and techniques then available.
   ``I feel like I'm painting on a global canvas,'' said
Alexenberg, a foThen, he enlarged the computer's stark rendition of the
drawing
into a 6 by 4 foot angel, divided into 24 sections to fit into a
fax machine.
   ``This `FaxArt' event reminds us that the electronic revolution
is the most far-reaching in human history,'' Alexenberg said in a
written statement defining his work. ``It is reshaping our
experience of space and time and redefining art.''
   While Americans now fax everything from restaurant orders to job
resumes, few probably realize that a crude telegraphic prototype of
what eventually became the fax machine was invented in 1842 by
Alexander Bain, a Scottish physicist and clockmaker, according to
AT&amp;T.
   The machine's popularity slowly increased over the past three
decades, then went wild in recent years.
   Laura Abbott, an AT&amp;T spokeswoman, said industry experts predict
the number of fax machines installed will triple worldwide, from 3
million in 1989 to 9 million in 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
