<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1606EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     10-04 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Six Months of Pittston Strike Costly to Union, Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers strike against
Pittston Coal Group is growing more divisive and expensive to both
sides as it turns 6 months old Thursday, but the costs are
remarkably even.
   Contract talks are on hold and the union leadership has raised
the stakes of the strike by using mass demonstrations to choke off
coal shipments.
   The UMW, with a $100 million national strike fund, has been
fined $25.4 million for illegal strike activities, mostly for
efforts to disrupt coal production by replacement workers.
   The union also has been paying each of Pittston's 1,695 union
employees from Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky $200 a week
from the fund since they went on strike April 5.
   In the first three months of the strike, the second financial
quarter, Pittston reported losses of $3.6 million compared with $9
million in profits the same quarter in 1988.
   UMW research director Mike Buckner said financial statements
from the next three months coming out in a few weeks will show the
company losing at least as much in potential revenue _ or $25.2
million over six months.
   Pittston also has a strike kitty _ a $100 million line of credit
the company received in late 1987, Buckner said.
   ``We have charged that that is a strike breaking fund,'' he said.
   A Russell County judge is expected to take away more UMW chips
by once again fining the union, this time for taking over
Pittston's main coal preparation plant for four days in late
September, the most dramatic act of civil disobedience of the
strike.
   UMW Vice President Cecil Roberts said similar unarmed invasions
and occupations to cut off coal shipments will be mounted soon,
regardless of the cost.
   ``This strike has been very expensive already,'' Roberts said.
He added, ``We're prepared to do whatever it takes to win.''
   The union has said all along that money has little to do with
this labor dispute. The main issues are not wages but job security
and health benefits for retired workers.
   ``If we have to spend money to win this strike then we're going
to spend it,'' Buckner said.
   Asked whether the union could afford the drain on the strike
fund, Buckner said, ``The question is, can we afford not to protest
Pittston's actions?''
   Pittston President Mike Odom declined to discuss specifics of
production or financial losses. But he said, ``The violence and
blatant violation of our rights under the law has cost the company
a substantial amount of money during the six months of the strike.''
   The union claims Pittston's production is about one-third of its
normal output. Tax records in the counties where Pittston has mines
show substantial decreases in the amount of coal coming out of the
ground.
   However, records at Virginia ports show little change in coal
shipments since the strike began. Shipments by all companies using
the ports has increased 20 percent through August, from about 25
million tons to about 30 millions tons, said John Randolph,
director of the Virginia Center for Coal and Energy Research.
   ``There is little data to show any dramatic effects on Pittston
operations or on Virginia production,'' he said.
   Buckner and coal industry analysts say that is because Pittston
is buying high-priced coal from other companies to fulfill its
contracts.
   ``That is indicative of the severity of the economic
difficulties the company is having with this strike,'' Buckner said.
   To block coal shipments the union contends were bound for
Pittston's preparation plants, UMW President Richard Trumka ordered
selective strikes that began early Monday at two mines in Kentucky
and five in West Virginia.
   About 350 UMW employees walked off their jobs Monday and a union
official said there was no way to tell how long that would last.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1612EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AgricultureNominee     10-04 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agriculture Nominee,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Criticize Bush Choice for Agriculture's Top Natural Resources
Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Agriculture Committee chairman on
Wednesday criticized President Bush's choice for a top natural
resources job as more concerned about pleasing special interests
than protecting the public trust.
   ``In government, the public interest has to come first,'' Sen.
Patrick Leahy told James Cason, the nominee for assistant secretary
of agriculture for natural resources and the environment during
confirmation hearings.
   Cason, 35, has been a high-ranking official in the Interior
Department since 1982 and is acting head of Land and Minerals
Management.
   Leahy said as a government official, Cason's one assignment has
been to protect the public interest.
   ``Time and time again, he has failed that assignment,'' said
Leahy, who grilled Cason during two days of hearings on decisions
he made at Interior.
   ``When it came to protecting the spotted owl, Mr. Cason chose
timber interests over the public welfare,'' the senator said in his
closing statement.
   ``When it came to getting tough on oil and gas companies who
were not paying their fair share of royalties, the decisions were
made behind closed doors. Key parties were excluded from meetings.''
   Leahy said Cason tried to stop the government from collecting
oil royalties, even where evidence of collusion or underpayment
among companies existed.
   During questioning, Leahy said Cason changed an audit system
when the oil industry reacted negatively to it, even though it was
designed to collect millions of dollars in underpaid royalties owed
the Indian tribes and the state and federal governments.
   Cason stopped audits of any leases negotiated before 1980, but
allowed oil companies to continue collecting overpayments from the
government for those leases, said Leahy.
   Cason said that by concentrating on audits of leases after 1980
and eliminating the ones that came earlier, the department was
merely making the best use of its audit staff.
   In addition, Cason said the government could make more money
through the post-1980 audits.
   Leahy chastised Cason for not consulting with the states or the
Indian tribes before eliminating the pre-1980 audits.
   ``It's like a judge in a divorce case locking the wife out of
the courtroom and dealing only with the husband,'' said Leahy.
   Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., questioned Cason's management
abilities, saying a General Accounting Office report showed that a
system under Cason's jurisdiction for finding mining law violators
has been defective for four years.
   Cason blamed the computer system and said the problems were
being worked out.
   Daschle said ``it says something about management'' when after
four years ``it didn't get better.''
   Cason assured Leahy that if confirmed, he would work with the
committee to set Agriculture Department policy.
   ``We have a plethora of statutes that require us to do some very
difficult things,'' he said. ``During the confirmation process I
have learned a lot. I have been exposed to new opinions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
