<FIRST>r w AM-Salinas 1stLd-Writethru a0624 10-04 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salinas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Pledges to Root Out Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE K. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
told a joint meeting of Congress on Wednesday his nation intends
``to eradicate drug trafficking at its very roots.''
   But Salinas, who is on a state visit to the United States,
warned that ``at the world level, we are losing.'' He said that was
unacceptable, and called for greater cooperation between
governments to turn the tide.
   While vowing an all-out effort to curb drug trafficking, Salinas
firmly ruled out joint U.S.-Mexican military operations to fight
the traffickers.
   ``The responsibility for the fight in our country is exclusively
ours,'' he said. ``There will be no joint military operations on
our soil.
   ``Mexico intends to eradicate drug trafficking at its very roots
in the sphere that falls under its responsibility,'' Salinas said,
speaking in Spanish while his audience of senators and House
members read from English translations.
   Drug smuggling and the alleged corruption of many Mexican law
enforcement authorities have led to complaints in Congress that
have at times been so strident they have been dubbed ``Mexico
bashing.''
   Salinas appeared to be appealing for an end to this, saying,
``The time has come to build a new relationship free of myths and
distrust, abuses and recriminations.''
   He said that the worldwide fight against drug trafficking also
is shared by Mexico but that mutual accusations about who is to
blame for the multibillion scourge waste time and effort.
   ``In Mexico, we now affirm that drug-trafficking is a threat to
national sovereignty ... because, as in other nations, it corrupts
whatever it touches,'' Salinas said.
   Later, in a speech at the National Press Club, Salinas said
Mexico will provide ``no haven and no sanctuary'' for narcotics
trafickers.
   ``We will hit them where it hurts, in the pocket and in their
personal liberty,'' he said.
   The Mexican president also used his speech to Congress to renew
his appeal for greater Mexican access to U.S. markets, saying that
while Mexico has eliminated most non-tarrif barriers to U.S.
products, ``we continue confronting them in the United States.''
   Salinas described this as an ``inequitable paradox'' and said
Mexico must have ``greater and more secure access to the world's
greatest market, the United States'' to obtain the economic growth
that is needed to improve the lot of its people.
   U.S. officials disagree with Salinas' portrayal of the United
States as a protectionist nation. They say two-thirds of Mexico's
exports come to the United States and that Mexico had a $2.7
billion surplus in its U.S. trade last year on total two-way trade
of about $44 billion.
</TEXT>
