<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Paxton     10-04 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Paxton,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record-Setting Trans-Atlantic Aviator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH MIAMI, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederick Paxton, a Royal Air Force
aviator who broke the trans-Atlantic speed record in 1945, died of
a heart attack. He was 74.
   He died Tuesday at North Miami Medical Center.
   Paxton was born in New Brunswick, Canada, with a hip disability
and spent his first 12 years bedridden in a body cast. He was left
with a limp.
   ``The war came along and it gave him the opportunity to excel
and be involved,'' said son John Paxton. ``He overcame all his
handicaps by flying.''
   Paxton and Capt. J.G. Naz shaved a minute off the previous
record in May 1945 by flying a twin-engine Mosquito bomber the
2,184 miles from Gander, Newfoundland, to Prestwick, Scotland, in 5
hours, 37 minutes.
   They were delivering the newly built bomber to the front in
World War II. The record would soon fall with the introduction of
jets.
   ``But it was still pretty good,'' said Fred Hotson of the
Canadian Aviation Historical Society. ``The Mosquito bomber was the
fastest thing around the first 2{ years after it was flown for the
first time.''
   Paxton retired to Miami in 1958.
   Survivors include his wife, Vera Viola, and sons John and David
of Hialeah. Private services were planned.
</TEXT>
