<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1929EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     10-04 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Sets Oct. 12 Space Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Engineers replaced a faulty rocket
computer Wednesday, and NASA officially set Oct. 12 for the launch
of space shuttle Atlantis with a nuclear-powered planetary probe.
   Shuttle managers had expected to select that date on Tuesday but
delayed the decision because of a problem in one of two computers
on a rocket intended to boost the Galileo spacecraft toward Jupiter
after it is released in orbit by Atlantis' astronauts.
   The bad computer was replaced by a spare, and NASA reported
initial tests showed it was working fine and that there was no need
to delay the launch. Oct. 12 had been the unofficial date for
several months.
   Liftoff was set for 1:29 p.m.
   Officials said the two computers were supposed to ``talk the
same language'' but they did not because one had a software problem.
   Because Galileo will be powered by two generators fueled by
radioactive plutonium-238 dioxide, three anti-nuclear groups last
week sued in U.S. District Court in Washington, D.C., in an attempt
to stop the launch.
   The organizations filed briefs with the court Wednesday. The
National Aeronautics and Space Administration is scheduled to file
its reply on Friday. Judge Oliver Gasch has set an Oct. 10 hearing.
   The opponents contend that a launch accident could spread
poisonous plutonium over heavily populated east-central Florida.
   NASA says that in tests the plutonium containers have been blown
up, shot at and burned to determine how they would survive
accidents. They have withstood pressures far greater than those
generated in the 1986 explosion of Challenger, the agency said.
   Even if there were a release, NASA said, it ``would have no
appreciable adverse health effects on the population.''
   If they lose the lawsuit, the anti-nuclear activists said they
will try to physically halt the liftoff by trying to infiltrate the
Kennedy Space Center on launch day.
</TEXT>
