<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bedford Springs,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Runs Out For Historic Hotel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD SPRINGS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the historic Bedford
Springs Hotel said Wednesday he had been notified that a bank will
take control of his debt-ridden, 185-year-old resort.
   Asher Sky, president of Sky Group International Inc., told the
Bedford Gazette that Union National Bank of Pittsburgh told him
Monday that it would take the hotel's title in lieu of foreclosure.
   Donald Malecki, attorney for the bank, declined to comment.
   Sky was unable to meet the Sept. 30 deadline for paying back
$4.8 million to the bank. The money was spent out of a $7.5 million
loan in 1987 for renovations never completed because of a dispute
between owners that ended up in federal bankruptcy court.
   The resort's clubhouse, 244-room hotel and golf course closed
Friday.
   The hotel and 2,300 acres of mountain land were put on the
auction block Sept. 21, but Sky rejected the high bid of $5.3
million as not enough.
   The hotel is a stately stretch of three- and four-story
buildings in the Allegheny Mountains. In its glory days, it
attracted notables including six presidents.
