<FIRST>r w AM-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru a0637 10-04 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Continues Search for Nominee to Fill Civil Rights Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 15th graf pvs bgng: ``It's a...'' with
comments from civil rights attorney, picks up 16th graf pvs bgng: ``The
department''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two months after his first choice was rejected
by lawmakers, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is still looking for
someone to be the Justice Department's civil rights chief, a
spokesman said Wednesday.
   ``We don't have a short list of candidates,'' said David Runkel,
press secretary for the attorney general. ``It's a difficult
position to fill.''
   The delay in finding a candidate raises the possibility that
President Bush would not have a new nominee for the position before
Congress adjourns later this fall.
   ``The last guy who was nominated for that position took a few
knocks, there are not a lot of people volunteering,'' Runkel said
of the Senate Judiciary Committee's refusal to approve William
Lucas to be assistant attorney general for civil rights.
   About a half-dozen people have been interviewed for the job
since the panel voted Aug. 1 to kill the nomination on a pair of
7-7 votes, Runkel said.
   After those votes, Thornburgh said Lucas was a victim of ``raw
politics'' and accused the Senate Judiciary Committee of
establishing a ``litmus test'' that anyone nominated for the job
must oppose recent Supreme Court decisions on job discrimination.
   But critics contended that Lucas was professionally unqualified
for the job, having never tried a court case and lacking lengthy
experience as a lawyer.
   During his confirmation hearing in July, Lucas stumbled several
times when discussing civil rights cases, confessing at one point
that he was ``new to the law.''
   Several Democratic senators also expressed dismay that Lucas
would not criticize the high court rulings, which civil rights
lawyers say will make it harder to win discrimination cases.
   Lucas stuck close to the Bush administration's policy, saying he
would monitor the impact on those decisions to determine if
legislation were needed to overturn them.
   Justice Department aides argued that Lucas was a victim of
timing as much as anything because he was forced to defend Supreme
Court decisions that were handed down shortly before his
confirmation hearing.
   They argued it was absurd to expect Bush to nominate someone who
didn't agree with his civil rights policies.
   Thornburgh quickly appointed Lucas to head the Justice
Department's Office of Liaison Services _ a post that did not
require Senate confirmation. Lucas' duties include dealing with the
very same civil rights groups that opposed his confirmation.
   On Wednesday, Runkel argued that the rough treatment Lucas
received during his confirmation hearing has hampered efforts to
recruit a new nominee.
   ``It's not an easy position to fill and part of the reason was
the way Bill Lucas was treated,'' Runkel said.
   ``I couldn't accept the notion that Lucas' demise in the
committee makes it difficult to fill the job,'' said Washington
civil rights attorney William Taylor, who lobbied against the
nomination.
   ``There are hundreds of lawyers with civil rights experience in
the country who would not have any difficulty passing muster with
the committee,'' Taylor said.
   The department, which conducts interviews and makes
recommendations to the White House, has not asked the FBI to
conduct background checks on anyone who has been interviewed,
Runkel said.
   The FBI conducts such background checks, which routinely take
several weeks, before a nomination is approved by the White House.
   Once the nomination is made, the Senate Judiciary Committee's
own investigation can delay a vote by the panel and the full Senate
for several weeks, perhaps months.
   The spokesman declined to say whether the difficulty in finding
a candidate means that Bush wouldn't have a nominee ready for
Senate consideration before Congress adjourns this fall.
   The civil rights division, which initiates criminal and civil
cases to enforce anti-discrimination laws, is being run by Acting
Assistant Attorney General James Turner, who took over after the
departure of William Bradford Reynolds, who headed the division
during the Reagan administration.
</TEXT>
