<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1849EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MysteryWoman     10-04 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mystery Woman,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans to Stay in Tennessee, for Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By URSULA THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amnesiac was reunited Wednesday with
her Ohio family after a 10-month disappearance but said that for
now she prefers to stay in Nashville rather than return home.
   ``I have a family now. They are very warm people, but I still
have no memory of them,'' said Ruth Ellish, who took the name
``Kitty Jordan'' from a slip of paper she found in her coat pocket.
   Ms. Ellish, of Akron, who still prefers to be called Kitty, met
with her mother and sister at the women's shelter where she has
stayed since arriving mysteriously in Nashville in December.
   She was identified as the 50-year-old divorced mother of three
after relatives saw national news stories about her.
   She plans to return to Nashville after a brief trip to Akron in
two weeks.
   ``I have a family here,'' she said in a news conference at the
Family Life Center, where she has worked as a cooking supervisor.
``They're very supportive. Otherwise, I wouldn't have been able to
make it. I've been living here, just trying to find a life and a
Social Security number.''
   Ms. Ellish disappeared from Akron on Dec. 8. Two days later,
Kitty awoke in a Nashville motel with a headache and bruises on one
eye, her arms and legs. She did not know how she got to the motel
and could not account for a 24- to 48-hour period.
   Her mother, Irene Christ and sister, Elise White, flew to
Nashville on Wednesday after police matched a missing-person report
from Ohio and the relatives heard her voice on the telephone
earlier this week.
   ``I feel better than I have in the last 10 months,'' Ms. Christ
said after the three spent some time by themselves, looking at
family photographs. ``I never broke down.''
   ``Time will take care of everything,'' Ms. White said. ``We want
her to come home, but we want what's best for her.''
   Ms. Ellish said she did not recognize Ms. Christ and Ms. White
but did not doubt they were her relatives.
   ``I can't put this into focus. It doesn't all register,'' she
said. There's still that feeling of `Why don't I remember?'''
   At the time of her disappearance Ms. Ellish, a telephone company
computer analyst, was having personal problems with her 18-year-old
daughter and was being treated for migraine headaches and stress,
her sister said. She also has two sons, ages 20 and 29.
   Ms. Ellish said doctors told her the memory loss was caused by a
traumatic event and that her memory may return, either gradually or
in a flash.
</TEXT>
