<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-CapitalGains     10-04 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Capital Gains,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Repeats Support For Cutting Capital Gains Tax</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Taxes-Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush renewed on Wednesday his push
for a lower capital gains tax, saying it is not ``a tax cut for a
few'' but a way to help ``millions'' of Americans find jobs.
   Bush made the pitch at a Small Business Administration ceremony
honoring minority entrepreneurs.
   He urged the Senate to follow the lead of the House and ``cut
the capital gains tax now.''
   It is not ``a tax cut for a few but ... a tax cut for all, a way
to channel investment back into new growth and new jobs,'' said the
president.
   The major beneficiaries will not be the rich but people
``looking for their first job or perhaps their second job,'' said
Bush. ``It is a job-oriented tax cut.''
   The House last week voted to cut the capital gains tax, now 28
percent to 33 percent, to 19.6 percent for two years and then
provide inflation indexing for new assets subject to the levy.
   Congressional tax experts have said 80 percent of the benefits
would go to people with incomes over $100,000 a year. It would
boost federal revenues in the next three years by $9 billion, but
lose $21 billion over 10 years, according to the Joint Committee on
Taxation.
   But Bush disputes those estimates, arguing that by freeing money
for investments, a lower capital gains tax would spur economic
growth and generate more tax revenues.
   Bush said the measure will ``raise employment and raise millions
of our fellow Americans to a new threshold of opportunity.''
   ``The business of America is not businss; the true business is
opportunity,'' he told 150 people at the gathering in the Old
Executive Office Building. No government program ``can match the
opportunity created for all Americans by those special people that
we call entrepreneurs.''
   Bush drew loud applause by promising ``to restore and
reinvigorate the vision behind the Office of Minority Business
Enterprise.''
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher and SBA Administrator Susan
Engeleiter joined Bush in presenting awards to:
   _Ronald Thompson, head of General Railroad Equipment and
Services, Inc., of East St. Louis, Mo., as Minority Entrepreneur of
the Year. His company has grouwn fivefold in seven years and now
employs 300 people.
   _Teresa McBride of Albuquerque, N.M., as SBA Minority Small
Business Person of the Year. Her retail consumer electronics
business, McBride Micro Source, has sales of $8.6 million a year.
   _Roy and Rudolph Terry of Terry Manufacturing of Roanoke, Ala.,
as the Graduate of the Year from the SBA's 8a program to help
minority-owned firms get off the ground. Terry, one of three
national uniform suppliers for McDonald's, employs nearly 300
people and has sales exceeding $12 million.
</TEXT>
