<FIRST>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     10-04 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corn-Soviets,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buying More Soybean Meal, Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought 100,000 metric
tons of soybean meal and an additional 200,000 tons of corn for
delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the
Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   The meal and corn were on top of an order for 2 million tons of
corn announced Tuesday. The seventh year of the long-term agreement
between the two countries began Oct. 1.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89, the sixth year of the
agreement, were a record of more than 21.7 million tons, including
more than 16.3 million tons of corn and nearly 5.4 million tons of
wheat.
   In addition, the 1988-89 sales included 442,500 tons of
soybeans, 1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons
of grain sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 200,000 tons of
corn would be about 7.88 million bushels.
   The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting
companies, which are required to report large sales to the
department. No selling prices or further details were released.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.22 per bushel at the
farm, according to USDA's five-day average, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of around $17.5 million.
   Soybean meal has been selling at wholesale in Illinois at an
equivalent of around $220 per metric ton. That would make the
latest Soviet purchase worth around $22 million at the U.S. plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1657EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Angola     10-04 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges Mobutu to Settle Difference with Angola's Rebel Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Wednesday urged Zaire's
President Mobutu Sese Seko to settle his differences with Angolan
rebel leader Jonas Savimbi amid reports that Mobutu has disrupted
the flow of U.S. arms to Savimbi's guerrillas.
   Mobutu was summoned to the White House from New York to discuss
the deterioration in his relations with Savimbi and the faltering
June cease-fire which Zaire mediated between the rebels and
Angola's Soviet-backed government, who have been fighting for 14
years.
   Mobutu, Savimbi and Angola's foreign minister, Pedro van Dunem,
were all in Washington on Wednesday, but none of them met.
   Mobutu returned to New York where he addressed the U.N. General
Assembly on Wednesday afternoon. During Mobutu's speech at the
United Nations, U.N. guards hustled six people out of the visitors'
gallery after they shouted ``Murderer'' at him.
   Savimbi, who leads the Union for the Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA), is to meet with Bush on Thursday.
   During Bush's 30-minute meeting with Mobutu, ``The president
reiterated the strong U.S. support for UNITA and our appreciation
of President Mobutu's efforts to try to help bring about national
reconciliation in Angola,'' said White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   ``The president urged President Mobutu to work out any
differences which he might have with UNITA so that the goal of
national reconciliation can be met,'' he said. Bush will also
``urge him (Savimbi) to work with Mobutu and all the parties
involved.''
   The problem is that UNITA and the Angolan government have
differing views of what reconciliation means. The sides have
refused to sit in the same room. Instead, they have used Mobutu,
other African leaders and the United States as go-betweens.
   Van Dunem, who came to Washington for one day Wednesday to
counter Savimbi's visit, told reporters his government wants
Savimbi to step down and to integrate his forces into the Angolan
armed forces. Once that happens and the civil war ends, multiparty
elections can be discussed, he said.
   ``A multiparty system now is unthinkable,'' he said.
   Van Dunem contended that Savimbi agreed to go into temporary
exile during a closed-door meeting in June with Angolan President
Eduardo dos Santos held in Gbadolite, Zaire, the same place where
they openly agreed to a cease-fire.
   However, Savimbi denied the claim during a news conference,
saying, ``If there was a secret agreement, it was a secret to me
too.''
   He said the first step for Angola must be free elections that
would give UNITA a role in running the country.
   Van Dunem accused Savimbi of reneging on the Gbadolite
agreements, saying Savimbi had come to the United States to ask for
more weapons to augment an estimated $40 million in arms he already
gets annually.
   He said Mobutu, the main channel for American arms supplies to
Savimbi, told the Angolan government he had stopped shipping U.S.
weapons to UNITA before the June accords.
   On Tuesday, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C. complained at a hearing of
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee that Mobutu had cut the flow
of U.S. arms to Savimbi's forces, but neither Fitzwater nor Savimbi
would discuss the matter. Mobutu did not talk to the news media
during his brief visit to Washington.
   During his previous visit to Washington in June, Mobutu told
administration officials that U.S. aid to UNITA and Soviet aid to
the Angolan government should both stop to give the Gbadolite
agreements a chance to work.
   But the truce agreement collapsed soon after it was signed, and
Mobutu has been siding with the Angolan government which demanded
that Savimbi step down.
   Mobutu has promised to ask Savimbi to sign a commitment of
temporary exile before an upcoming summit of African leaders in
Gabon, van Dunem said.
   He urged the Bush administration to support the Gbadolite
accords as interpreted by Angola, Mobutu and other African leaders
_ that Savimbi go into exile _ saying he planned to press his case
with Secretary of State James Baker III. Baker has agreed to meet
with van Dunem although the United States and Angola have no
diplomatic relations.
   Van Dunem also accused the administration of reneging on a
promise by former Secretary of State George Shultz that the United
States would establish diplomatic links with the Angolan government
once Angola agreed to the withdrawal of the 50,000 Cuban troops
stationed there.
   The Cuban pullout was agreed to in a U.S.-sponsored agreement
signed last December and about half have left thus far.
   The State Department has denied such a promise was made, saying
the United States would withhold official recognition of Angola
until national reconciliation with UNITA is achieved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
