<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2001EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-APME-FOIAward     10-04 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-APME-FOI Award,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit News Wins APME Freedom of Information Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit News won the top award
Wednesday in the 1989 Freedom of Information competition of the
Associated Press Managing Editors association.
   The News was selected for its successful efforts to document a
city redevelopment project that cost taxpayers $40 million.
   The 19th annual award was presented Wednesday at the APME
convention here by David Hawpe, editor of The Courier-Journal of
Louisville, Ky., and chairman of the APME FOI committee.
   Five citations also were awarded for extraordinary effort toward
a better-informed citizenry. They were signed by Hawpe and APME
president Paul Janensch of The Journal-News, Rockland County, N.Y.,
and presented to:
   The Daily Southtown Economist of Chicago, for successful efforts
to force release of presentencing letters and reports that a judge
said influenced him in sentencing the Willow Springs, Ill., police
chief.
   The Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch, for successful efforts to
open juvenile records in the case of the late Rakie Cloyd.
   The San Jose (Calif.) Mercury News, for efforts to open
legislators' driving records and for revealing secret meetings of
the state Legislature.
   The Spokesman-Review and Spokane Chronicle of Spokane, Wash.,
for efforts to obtain records illustrating the problem of sexual
abuse of students by teachers.
   The Washington Post, for an examination of the way in which
corporations and institutions use court secrecy to prevent
disclosure of critical information relating to health and safety
issues.
</TEXT>
