<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1718EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     10-04 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldiers Kill Two Masked Palestinians, Wound Others in Gaza</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fired on masked Palestinians
in the Gaza Strip on Wednesday, killing two and wounding others,
the army said.
   Arab reporters said some soldiers were disguised as laborers and
drove a private car. The army spokesman's office said the soldiers
were in uniform.
   Also Wednesday, three Palestinians suspected of collaborating
with Israel were reported killed by fellow Arabs. The army
confirmed two of the deaths, one in an Israeli prison camp, and
said it was checking further.
   Sixteen Palestinians in all were reported wounded by Israeli
gunfire in the occupied territories Wednesday.
   Arab reporters in the Gaza Strip said soldiers, operating under
cover, came upon a gang of masked Palestinian youths in Bureij
refugee camp and fired.
   Residents of Bureij identified the dead as Mahmoud Abu Shamala,
22, and Maher Mohammed Al-Makadma, 18, raising to 583 the number of
Palestinians killed by Israelis since the uprising began in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip 21 months ago. Forty Israelis
also have died. In addition, 126 Palestinians were killed by fellow
Arabs.
   New army firing orders allow soldiers to fire live ammunition at
masked Palestinians after shouting a warning and firing in the air.
If warnings go unheeded, soldiers can fire at suspects' legs.
Earlier, troops could fire at masked men only if the men were armed.
   In politics, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said he expected Prime
Minster Yitzhak Shamir and Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak to hold
a long-awaited first summit. He said no date was set.
   His comment preceded a crucial government meeting on Middle East
peace prospects. The two divided parties in the coalition Cabinet
met separately to outline their strategies for a session of the
inner Cabinet Thursday on Mubarak's offer to arrange an
Israeli-Palestinian meeting in Cairo.
   U.S. officials urge acceptance of Mubarak's efforts as a way to
further Israel's own plan for Middle East peace, including
elections in the occupied territories taken from Jordan and Egypt
in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Israel's left-leaning Labor Party accepts Mubarak's proposal.
   But after senior ministers in Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc met
Wednesday, officials said Likud stood by its rejection of Mubarak's
main ideas.
   Likud rejects Mubarak's call for Israel to accept the
U.S.-backed formula of trading occupied land for peace. Labor,
which arranged to meet Wednesday night in Tel Aviv, supports
land-for-peace and talking to Palestinians outside the occupied
territories.
   Industry Minister Ariel Sharon urged Wednesday that at least 300
more Jewish families move into the Moslem quarter of Jerusalem's
Old City, Israel radio reported.
   Sharon, who owns a house in the quarter, made the comment at a
ceremony opening a ``security center'' for self-protection by the
30 Jewish families living there. Sharon's house is under 24-hour
police guard.
   The Old City is part of the territory Israel captured from
Jordan in 1967.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2041EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Drug-SquadSlaying 1stLd-Writethru a0711 10-04 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug-Squad Slaying, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Officers Indicted in Dealer's Beating Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six members of Miami's street narcotics unit were
indicted Wednesday on charges they allegedly chased down a drug
dealer and beat him to death after an anonymous tip indicated he
had a murder contract on one of them.
   The federal indictment charged the officers with civil rights
violations resulting in the Dec. 16 death of Leonardo Mercado. Two
of the officers also were accused of beating Mercado about six
weeks before the fatal attack. And all six were charged with
attacking Mercado's stepson, Jose Soto, on the night of the killing.
   State Attorney Janet Reno would not respond when asked if her
department was pursuing state charges.
   A federal magistrate ordered the six officers, who were relieved
of duty after Mercado's death, to post $200,000 personal surety
bond and appear for arraignment Oct. 16.
   The six entered court manacled to each other amid applause from
relatives and friends outside. If convicted, each faces life
imprisonment and a $750,000 fine.
   ``It's a sad day when a federal grand jury must indict six
police officers for intentional use of unreasonable force,'' said
U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
   ``This case reminds us that everyone _ president, police
officers, the average citizen _ is subject to the law and will be
prosecuted for deliberate violations of the law,'' he said.
   Miami police cooperated with the federal investigation and
expected the indictment.
   ``We're saddened by the experience, but we must go out and
perform our duties in a professional manner and continue to serve
the community,'' said Police Chief Perry Anderson.
   The indictment alleges that about six weeks before the fatal
attack, officers Pablo Camacho and Andy Watson beat Mercado, 35, at
a game room near his apartment. It then alleges that all six
officers were on their way to a drug sting on Dec. 16 when they
allegedly detoured to Mercado's apartment and attacked him and his
stepson. Mercado died hours later.
   Reports had been circulating around the department for a few
days that an anonymous tip indicated Mercado had targeted Camacho
for murder.
   All six officers were charged with conspiracy to threaten and
intimidate Mercado by use of unreasonable force under color of law
and civil rights violations in the death of Mercado and the attack
on Soto. Camacho and Watson were charged with a civil rights
violation in the November beating of Mercado.
   The officers charged and their experience with the department
are: Camacho, 42, 13 years; Charlie Haynes, 30, 10 years; Ronald
Sinclair, 46, seven years; Thomas Trujillo, 31, nine years;
Nathaniel Veal Jr., 31, eight years; and Watson, 32, nine years.
   The indictment of the six officers is the second scandal within
the Miami Police department in five years. A band of 15 officers
was charged with running a drug-ripoff ring that was blamed for the
drownings of three drug boat guards in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
