<DOCNO> AP891004-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2000EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo     10-04 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Linking Islands and Mainland Lifted Out of Water</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bridge that is the only land link
between the mainland and homes on two barrier islands on Wednesday
was hoisted out of the Intracoastal Waterway, where it was dumped
by Hurricane Hugo.
   Officials of hard-hit Charleston put out the word that they want
tourists to start coming back to the historic city.
   Officials hoped to open the Ben Sawyer Bridge to traffic by
Thursday, giving residents of the Isle of Palms and Sullivan's
Island land access to their homes for the first time since the
killer storm struck on Sept. 21.
   Hugo's 135-mph wind wrenched the 500,000-ton swing bridge,
leaving it tipped at a 45-degree angle, leaning on its center
support pier with one end submerged in the water.
   The bridge was lifted out of the water by a crane mounted on a
barge.
   Highway officials said they would inspect the bridge before
declaring it safe for traffic. Since the storm, the only access to
the islands has been by boat or helicopter.
   Dozens of spectators watched the bridge operation in small boats
stopped in the waterway.
   Others watched from the shoreline at the Toler's Cover marina
and condominium complex, where the storm ripped the roofs off some
units and tossed boats around the parking lot.
   Among them was Melvin Anderegg, mayor of Sullivan's Island.
   Residents were again living on the island and power and water
has been restored, although the water has not yet been approved for
drinking, he said.
   ``The people want to get back to their homes and get started
digging out,'' Anderegg said. ``Everywhere you look over there are
people cleaning up and moving things.''
   The mayor estimated that between 100 and 150 of the
approximately 850 houses on the island are not habitable. Many of
them are rental and vacation homes.
   The South Carolina Electric &amp; Gas Co. said about two-thirds of
the utility's 158,000 customers in the metropolitan Charleston area
had power restored by late Tuesday. Power was restored by Wednesday
to almost all customers in other areas of the state, power company
officials said.
   Hurricane Hugo slammed into the South Carolina coast Sept. 21,
killing at least 18 and damaging and destroying homes, businesses,
schools and municipal buildings as far inland as Sumter and north
to North Carolina. In all, 29 people were killed on the U.S.
mainland.
   Damage in South Carolina has been estimated at $3 billion or
more.
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency opened two additional
disaster assistance centers Wednesday in South Carolina, making a
total of 16 centers where people can apply for emergency grants and
loans. In addition, it is now operating a telephone hotline and
applications may be submitted over the phone, said Paul Hall,
FEMA's coordinating officer for the hurricane recovery.
   The Red Cross announced Wednesday that only seven storm
evacuation shelters housing 454 people remain open around the
state, down from 10 shelters Tuesday. Since the storm approached,
453 shelters have housed 87,230 people.
   Even while the cleanup continued, officials urged visitors to
return to historic Charleston.
   ``We plan to go to every city in America that sent aid to
Charleston and go on their media and thank them and tell them
Charleston is open for business,'' said Tom Blazer, chairman of the
Charleston Trident Chamber of Commerce.
   Ninety percent of the area's hotels and restaurants should be
open by mid-October.
   The tourism industry is worth $4.9 billion to the local economy,
Blazer said.
   Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. also urged visitors to return.
   ``We've bounced back from Hurricane Hugo and visitors should not
cancel their plans to come to Charleston but should come right
ahead,'' the mayor said. A 9 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew should be lifted
soon.
   Meanwhile, a coalition of Charleston area groups announced plans
to begin replacing millions of acres of trees devastated by Hugo.
The effort, dubbed Lowcountry Releaf, will collect funds to buy
seedlings and distribute trees between Thanksgiving and Arbor Day,
Dec. 1.
</TEXT>
