<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-McGee     10-04 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-McGee,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Old-Time Cajun Fiddler Dead at 96</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUNICE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis McGee, a master fiddler who played on
some of the earliest recordings of Cajun music, has died of natural
causes. He was 96.
   McGee performed on the radio show ``Prairie Home Companion'' and
often played at festivals and on college campuses around the
country well into his 90s.
   The Eunice resident died Tuesday in Savoy Medical Center in
Mamou. Funeral services were scheduled for Thursday at Emanuel
Baptist Church in Eunice.
   McGee played with such Cajun artists as Amede Ardoin, Joe Falcon
and Amede Breaux when the music was first being recorded in the
late 1920s.
   ``He was very well-known and very much respected in lots of
different circles around the country and none of that affected
him,'' said Barry Ancelet, a chronicler of the Cajun culture and
history.
   ``Dennis McGee was around when what we now call Cajun music was
invented, or was developing,'' Ancelet said. ``Because of how he
learned and who he learned from, he was one of the last living
links to our musical past.''
</TEXT>
