<FIRST>u w AM-Panama-US-Military     10-04 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US-Military,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Troops Are In Panama To Protect the Canal and US Civilians</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The principal tasks of the nearly 13,000 U.S.
military forces in Panama are to protect both the Panama Canal and
the estimated 40,000 American civilians living in that country.
   These forces are precluded from involvement in Panamanian
internal affairs but Panamanian officials have said U.S. troops
frequently have been used in maneuvers designed to intimidate the
government.
   Under the Panama Canal treaties, U.S. forces are allowed to
patrol only their own bases and areas under joint U.S.-Panamanian
jurisdiction.
   There were about 10,800 U.S. military personnel in Panama early
this year but President Bush augmented that number by 2,000 after a
post-election outbreak of violence in Panama.
   The U.S. Southern Command, responsible for all U.S. military
activities in Central and South America, is headquartered at Quarry
Heights, one of 10 major military installations in Panama.
</TEXT>
