<FIRST>r i AM-LeakingTanker     10-04 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leaking Tanker,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Spills Oil Off Southern Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cypriot oil tanker leaked
about 350 barrels of oil into the Indian Ocean that on Wednesday
had formed a slick 14 miles long off southern Africa, news agencies
reported.
   The independent South African Press Association quoted Capt.
P.H. Kroon of the Transport Department's marine division as saying
a strong southerly current would keep the slick away from the coast.
   It quoted R.C. van der Krol, port captain of East London, as
saying the tanker Pacificos spilled the oil about 25 miles south of
East London and that he did not know the ship's port of origin or
its destination.
   Government television said the oil was leaking from a 50-foot
gash just above the water line in the midsection of the 26,800-ton
tanker, but did not say how or when the damage occurred.
   It said the captain notified authorities Wednesday afternoon and
a coast guard plane flew over the slick, which the television said
was three miles wide at some points.
   SAPA quoted a spokesman for Pentow Marine, a Cape Town salvage
company, as saying a coast guard anti-pollution vessel was in the
vicinity and another was on its way. The spokesman, not identified,
said the tanker was carrying 10,000 tons of oil and that a salvage
tug was to reach it by Thursday afternoon.
</TEXT>
