<DOCNO> AP891004-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BloodBank-AIDS     10-04 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blood Bank-AIDS,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Blood Bank To Begin Reporting AIDS Carriers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS-Blood, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blood bank plans to start reporting the
names of AIDS carriers to health authorities who in turn will try
to trace the patient's sexual contacts, officials said.
   ``We don't want people with AIDS or people at high risk for AIDS
donating blood,'' said Ken Wiebeck, spokesman for the Southwest
Florida Blood Bank. ``It's not right, it's not safe. The safety of
the public is of primary importance.''
   Also, the blood bank wants to discourage people from using
donations as a way to get a free, confidential AIDS test.
   ``One of our fears is that people may be donating blood to get a
confidential test for AIDS,'' said Dr. Paul Schmidt, director of
the blood bank and a recent past president of the American
Association of Blood Banks.
   A spokesman for AIDS patients advised caution in reporting names.
   ``Passing along names would scare people,'' said Chuck Kuehn,
executive director of the Tampa AIDS Network. ``They would have
achieved their purpose but I don't agree with their tactics.''
   The Tampa blood bank is considered among the most aggressive in
the country in trying to prevent AIDS carriers from donating blood.
In March 1988, the bank became one of two in the United States to
start interviewing donors to identify high-risk applicants. A San
Bernardino, Calif., blood bank was the other.
   Donors will be told of the policy and asked to sign a form
acknowledging they were so advised. If tests show young donors, 17
or 18, carry the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, which causes
acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the blood bank will notify
their parents or guardian.
   Dr. Don Kwalick, director of the Hillsborough County Health
Department, said his employees intend to follow the same procedures
they use in tracing contacts of patients with other sexually
transmitted diseases. Names from the blood bank would be used as
one source of information in tracing contacts.
   He said recently passed laws let the department include AIDS
patients in the tracing, but that state Health and Rehabilitative
Services officials have to give their permission.
   The Health Department offers anonymous and confidential AIDS
testing.
   The blood bank has been identifying between one and two donors
that test positive for the AIDS virus for every 10,000 units of
blood donated. That is about what would be expected nationally,
Wiebeck said.
   In the interview process, potential donors are asked a series of
questions instead of simply being asked to complete a form saying
they do not fall into high-risk categories.
   The Tampa data showed 62 donors out of the approximately 36,000
seen since the questioning began were ``deferred'' because they
gave a positive response to a question.
   The questions include:
   Have you had sexual contact with prostitutes in the past six
months?
   Have you had clinical or laboratory evidence of AIDS infection
or had sexual contact with someone who has?
   Have you engaged in male homosexual activity or had sexual
contact with someone who had?
   Two additional questions ask about intravenous drug use and
whether the donor has immigrated from Haiti or west or central
Africa since 1977 or had sexual contact with an immigrant from
those regions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1854EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SchoolTakeover     10-04 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Takeover,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>State School Board Approves Jersey City Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MARTELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMESBURG, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state superintendent took control of
Jersey City's faltering public schools Wednesday, completing a
five-year legal struggle that ended in the nation's largest state
takeover of an urban school district.
   Jersey City students have been subjected to ``educational child
abuse,'' said Gov. Thomas H. Kean. ``Now the community can put
politics and patronage aside, and get on with the business of
learning.''
   The state had cited political intrusion in hiring practices,
poor test scores, failure to provide a safe, clean environment for
students, violations of bidding laws, failure to provide for
handicapped children and unauthorized use of state funds as some of
the reasons for the takeover.
   On Wednesday, the state Board of Education in Jamesburg gave
final approval to the takeover and formally appointed Elena J.
Scambio to a three-year term as superintendent of the school
district.
   Ms. Scambio's first act was to abolish the jobs of seven top
administrators in the district, including that of school
Superintendent Franklin Williams. The state board's action also
officially disbanded the Jersey City Board of Education.
   A new board is expected to be appointed by state Education
Commissioner Saul Cooperman by December.
   Ms. Scambio, a former Essex County school superintendent who has
been preparing for the transition since August, promised to
``unravel the quagmire that exists in Jersey City'' and make the
city a national model of urban education.
   Under New Jersey's takeover law, the state has five years to
make improvements. National education groups say they will closely
monitor the progress of the takeover.
   The move gives the state extraordinary powers in Jersey City,
the state's second largest district with 28,000 students.
   Ms. Scambio said other immediate changes may include trimming
from 100 to 150 staff positions, streamlined management, physical
improvements to schools and better community relations.
   The Jersey City school system has a staff of 3,322 and a budget
for the current year of about $180 million. Enrollment is 44
percent black, 34 percent Hispanic and 13 percent white.
   The board's decision was expected and ends a bitter legal battle
by the state to take over the schools, a process strongly pushed by
Kean, who has billed himself as ``the education governor.''
   State board Vice President Robert A. Woodruff, reading a
resolution, said ``the district's problems were deep-rooted and
endemic. The Jersey City board of education totally failed to meet
its obligations.''
   This summer, Administrative Law Judge Kenneth Springer agreed
with the argument of state officials in his decision to grant the
state power to take over the district.
   Springer noted that some textbooks used in Jersey City
classrooms are more than 30 years old.
   Jersey City officials bitterly fought the takeover effort,
saying the problems were caused by a prior administration and that
the state trumped up its case against the district.
   Williams, who was relieved as school superintendent but can
still teach in the district, released a statement Wednesday
criticizing the takeover effort.
   ``In a society that offers little enough to bolster the
self-confidence of urban children, the campaign to take over the
Jersey City schools has only further lowered the self-image of our
students,'' Williams said.
   Williams said test scores have climbed in recent years, and one
of the district's high schools was one of only five in the state
with a 100 percent passing rate on the high school proficiency test.
   Local officials had at first sought to rally public opinion
against the intervention but found little political support. Former
Mayor Anthony Cuccio, who opposed the takeover, lost his seat in
May to Gerald McCann, who said he would not oppose the move.
   ``It should have happened much sooner, I think,'' said Samir
Skular, 31, a 31-year-old city resident with two daughters in the
public schools. ``It was just politicians trying to protect their
jobs and not thinking about kids.''
   Jean McDonald, a researcher for the National Governors'
Association, said Kentucky, South Carolina, Texas and New Mexico
have laws allowing state takeovers of failing school districts.
   In Kentucky, the state school board has taken limited control of
three county districts under an ``academic bankruptcy'' law enacted
by the General Assembly in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
