<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0688 10-04 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0688,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Lawmakers Discuss New Division of Power; Iran, Warlords
Critical</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with Iranian warning, warlords' negative
reaction, other. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heckled by Iran, Lebanese legislators
met on Wednesday and debated scrapping a 46-year-old pact that
divides government jobs along sectarian lines.
   They agreed earlier to revamp Parliament with an equal number of
Moslems and Christians in an effort to end the 14-year-old civil
war.
   Any agreement, however, must win the support of powerful
warlords who have controlled much of Lebanon since fighting began
in 1975. Moslem militia leaders Nabih Berri and Walid Jumblatt
reportedly gave negative assessments of the Taif efforts on
Wednesday.
   Militia leaders have been kept away from the meeting.
   The conflict is a battleground for conflicting Arab interests as
well as for Lebanese factions. The war has killed at least 150,000
people and turned much of the capital, Beirut, into rubble.
   Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani warned the legislators
Wednesday not to surrender to domination by Maronite Catholics.
   ``If they give in, they have done a great treason to the
Lebanese people, and should be seriously confronted,'' the Islamic
Republic News Agency quoted Rafsanjani as saying.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati earlier Wednesday
rejected decisions taken by the legislators on grounds they failed
to hand over the bulk of political power to Moslems.
   In Beirut, two foreign passenger jets _ an Aeroflot flight from
Moscow and a French airliner _ landed at the airport Wednesday, the
first since the airport reopened nearly two weeks ago after a
cease-fire that ended six months of shelling duels between Moslem
and Christian militias.
   Thirty-three Christian and 30 Moslem legislators, representing
all but 10 of the body's surviving 73 members, met for a fifth day
to discuss reforms aimed at ending the war.
   They agreed Tuesday to expand the 99-seat Parliament and to
ensure an equal distribution between Christians and Moslems.
   The last official census conducted in 1932 showed Christians
made up a majority of the population, but later estimates say
Moslems make up 55 percent of Lebanon's 4 million people.
   On Wednesday, the deputies talked of using a merit system to
fill government jobs.
   Sources at the meeting, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said all deputies opposed continuing the present sectarian system
but differed on how and when to change it.
   Some Christian speakers made reform conditional on a withdrawal
of Syrian forces from Lebanon, the sources said.
   Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud al-Faisal and other mediators
met Christian deputies, apparently to try to persuade them to drop
this condition.
   Deputies also discussed possible expansion of the premier's
powers at the expense of the president.
   Under an unwritten 1943 national covenant, power was shared by a
Maronite Catholic president, a Sunni Moslem premier and a Shiite
Moslem Parliament speaker, with top government, army and public
administration posts going to the Maronites.
   One Parliament member, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
abolishing political factionalism ``is an issue too explosive for
the parliamentarians to handle without the prior consent of the
warlords who control the Lebanese arena.''
   Iran's state-run news agency IRNA said Rafsanjani's statement
came after he met in Tehran with four Lebanese Moslem leaders:
Berri, leader of the Shiite Amal movement; Jumblatt, the Druse
chieftain; Sheik Subhi Tufaili, a leader of the Shiite Hezbollah,
or Party of God; and Sheik Saeed Shaaban, head of a Syrian- and
Libyan-backed Sunni fundamentalist faction.
   Velayati told a news conference in Tehran ``we can place no hope
in the Taif meeting,'' Iranian TV reported.
   ``Since the majority of the Lebanese people are Moslems, it is
natural that the principal rule in Lebanon must be in the hands of
Moslems,'' he said.
   ``If any decision is made at Taif or elsewhere that contradicts
this basic principle ... it will not be accepted by the Moslem and
nationalist forces, and it will be rejected by Iran and Syria,''
Velayati said.
   The broadcast and IRNA dispatch were monitored in Cyprus.
   Jumblatt and Berri say Syrian troops are needed to guarantee a
settlement.
   Iranian TV said Amal issued a statement saying the Taif meeting
will not reach a just solution to Lebanon's crisis.
   In Beirut, the Christian-run Voice of Lebanon quoted Jumblatt as
saying a cease-fire that began late last month was just an
``intermission'' in the war.
   Iran is a major backer of Shiites in Lebanon, who are estimated
to be the largest sect there.
   Supporters of Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun, a Maronite,
demand a timetable for a pullout of Syria's 40,000 troops from
Lebanon before considering political reforms.
   If agreement is reached on reforms, the Lebanese parliament
would convene in Beirut to ratify them formally, with a tentative
date set at Oct. 21.
</TEXT>
