<FIRST>u i AM-IRA-Shooting     10-04 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRA-Shooting,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Shot Wrong Man, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Irish Republican
Army on Wednesday shot and killed a Roman Catholic after mistaking
him for a Protestant gunman, police said.
   The victim, 52-year-old James Henry Babbington, was shot
point-blank by two men outside a primary school, the Royal Ulster
Constabulary said.
   In a statement to local news media, the predominantly Catholic
IRA claimed it killed a gunman who was involved in several attacks
against IRA members. The IRA statement gave a name of the purported
victim, but it was not Babbington.
   ``The victim was an entirely innocent man who was on his way to
work,'' the Constabulary said in a statement late Wednesday.
   ``The fact that the shooting appears to have been carried out
before the horrified gaze of young children speaks volumes for the
sick mentality of the murderers,'' said Alban McGuinness, chairman
of the Social Democratic and Labor Party. It is the largest
predominantly Catholic party in the province.
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, said the man
identified by the IRA was taken into protective custody. A
Constabulary press officer declined to comment on that report.
   The outlawed Ulster Volunteer Force, an extremist Protestant
group, claimed responsibility for another shooting Wednesday in
north Belfast. The victim, who suffered shoulder and leg injuries,
was related to a prominent member of Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal
political wing, police said.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the 60 percent Protestant province with the 95 percent
Catholic Irish Republic.
   Twenty years of violence have claimed 2,758 lives in Northern
Ireland, 47 of them this year.
</TEXT>
