<FIRST>u p AM-ElectionRdp     10-04 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Election Rdp,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson `Ready to Roll' in Atlanta; Phoenix Mayor Ponders Mixed Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta Mayor-elect Maynard Jackson prepared to trade places for
a second time with Mayor Andrew Young, while Phoenix Mayor Terry
Goddard pondered the mixed message contained in his landslide
re-election.
   ``We're ready to roll,'' Jackson said after his own overwhelming
victory Tuesday, which made him the city's first three-term black
mayor. ``I'm eager to get to it.''
   Goddard said he would try to figure out why voters rejected his
plans for a downtown baseball stadium even as they returned him to
office for a third term.
   Atlanta's city charter prohibited Young, the former United
Nations ambassador, from seeking a third consecutive term as mayor,
just as it prohibited Jackson from seeking a third straight term
eight years ago.
   Young plans to run for governor next year, while Jackson will
resume leadership at City Hall. He was in Chicago on Wednesday, but
campaign officials said he would announce the members of his
transition staff on Thursday.
   Jackson won Tuesday by a nearly 5-1 margin over civil rights
activist Hosea Williams. In final, unofficial returns, Jackson had
54,897 votes, or 79 percent, to 11,1116, or 16.5 percent, for
Williams. Four other candidates shared 4.5 percent of the vote.
   Goddard beat his nearest rival in Phoenix, state Republican
Party Chairman Burton Kruglick, by nearly a 2-to-1 margin, while
voters spurned the proposed baseball stadium by a 3-to-2 margin. It
was the latest in a series of rejections for large public works
projects that Goddard has supported.
   Goddard conceded that he was responsible for selling his
projects to the public. ``Obviously, we haven't done that,'' he
said.
   The Phoenix and Atlanta elections were among several Tuesday.
Among the others:
   _ In Mississippi, a Democratic state senator and a Republican
political aide are gearing up for an Oct. 17 runoff in their race
to fill the seat left vacant by the late Rep. Larkin Smith, who
died in a plane crash.
   Democrat Gene Taylor claimed 42 percent of the vote Tuesday and
Republican Tom Anderson received 37 percent to win spots in the
runoff. State Attorney General Mike Moore trailed with 21 percent.
   _ Albuquerque, N.M., Mayor Ken Schultz was turned out of office,
prompting one of the candidates who beat him, Louis Saavedra, to
say that voters ``are fed up with all the politics that go on at
City Hall.''
   Schultz received just 10 percent of the vote in his defeat at
the hands of Saavedra and Pat Baca, who will face each other in a
runoff that must be held within 30 days. No mayor has been elected
to back-to-back terms since Albuquerque enacted a mayor-council
form of government in 1974.
   _ Cleveland voters will elect the city's second black mayor on
Nov. 7 after City Council President George Forbes and his youthful
former protege, state Sen. Mike White, defeated three rivals to
advance to a runoff.
   _ In Escondido, Calif., pro-choice advocate Tricia Hunter won a
vacant state Assembly seat by defeating a Democratic opponent and
turning back a strong write-in campaign by an anti-abortion
advocate she beat in the Republican primary.
</TEXT>
