<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-04 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain in the Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More than an inch of rain fell in Texas on Wednesday and showers
and thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold front drenched other
parts of the Southwest.
   A thunderstorm produced 1.18 inches of rain at Victoria, Texas,
and more than 1{ inches at Thomaston.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from southern Arizona into
Colorado. Nearly an inch of rain fell in Childs, Ariz.
   More than a dozen cities reported record low temperatures for
the date, including St. Cloud, Minn., which was the cold spot in
the nation Wednesday morning with 19 degrees.
   High temperatures were in the 80s across much of the area from
Texas to Florida and southern Georgia, with lower 90s reported in
southern Texas and southern Florida.
   Readings were only in the 40s across eastern Montana, much of
North Dakota, northern New England and upstate New York.
   Tropical Storm Raymond, centered about 500 miles south of San
Diego. was moving north northeast about 15 mph. Very moist air was
streaming into Arizona, and showers and thunderstorms were expected
throughout the week.
   Skies were sunny over much of the nation west of the Rockies and
much of the area from the upper Great Lakes to the Carolinas and
the central Gulf Coast states.
</TEXT>
