<SECOND>AM-Family Slayings,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dead Woman's Husband Said She Threatened Child Poisonings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who fatally stabbed her two young
daughters, then forced her 8-year-old son to kill her with the same
knife had threatened last month to poison all four of her children,
a social services lawyer said Wednesday.
   The allegation came to light in a Juvenile Court custody hearing
the day after Marie King killed her 3- and 4-year-old daughters
with a 10-inch kitchen knife and ordered her son to stab her,
investigators said.
   The woman's husband, Christopher King, called the state
Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services last month, saying
she had threatened to poison all four children, said Pablo Perez, a
department lawyer.
   Mrs. King, 32, denied the threat when confronted by social
workers, Perez said.
   Christopher King then refused state services, saying he needed
his wife at home to take care of the children while he worked, said
Ruben Betancourt, a spokesman for the department.
   The department's investigation remained open, and Betancourt
said agency procedures were followed.
   ``We started an investigation at the father's request on the
accusation that the mother was threatening the children. We went
and talked to the mother, talked to the father, talked to the
children, who were happy, well-fed,'' Betancourt said.
   Neighbors said Mrs. King rarely left the two-bedroom house since
the family moved in a few months ago. Her husband attended two
neighborhood Crime Watch meetings, and the children frequently were
seen playing outside.
   Judge Seymour Gelber said the agency's handling of the matter
was appropriate. ``It appears HRS did what it should have done,''
he said. ``So this was not a case where HRS failed to follow up.''
   The state agency went to court Wednesday for custody of the
8-year-old and his 6-year-old brother after the father refused to
allow medical and psychological evaluations of the boys, Perez said.
   The judge granted the agency custody, and the boys were placed
in a temporary state shelter, Betancourt said.
