<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Rebels 1stLd-Writethru a0691 10-04 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Rebels, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rebels Held Noriega Hostage for Hours, Aide Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with aide confirming Noriega was held. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers trying to depose Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega held him hostage for up to five hours, but let him
go after loyal forces told his captors they would ``face the
consequences'' if any harm came to the general, a Noriega aide said
Wednesday.
   Lt. Col. Arnulfo Castrejon, director for the Panamanian Defense
Forces Security and Defense Committee, told journalists that during
the coup attempt on Tuesday, Noriega ``had tried to calm his
captors during the time he was held, trying to avoid a bloodshed.''
   Lower-ranking officers attempting the coup were defeated after
loyal forces surrounded Defense Forces headquarters and
counterattacked.
   ``The surrender came when the loyal officers took command of the
combat units and gave the rebels a last chance to release the
commander and members of his staff or face the consequences,''
Castrejon said. ``The general was a hostage for four hours.''
   Later Castrejon said Noriega was held for five hours. It was not
clear if Noriega was released before or after the final violent
assault on the headquarters that led to the rebel forces' surrender.
   ``He was confident that elite forces and the special forces and
rest of the officers and soldiers of the Defense Forces were going
to solve the problem immediately, as it happened,'' Castrejon added.
   Castrejon spoke briefly to reporters in front of Defense Forces
headquarters Wednesday and did not say who coordinated the rescue
and counterattack operation.
   U.S. officials, speaking on condition of anonymity in
Washington, said they were mystified by the decision to let Noriega
go.
   ``Noriega was in their clutches,'' said one U.S. official
Wednesday.
   The United States has been trying to oust Noriega since February
1988, when he was indicted on drug trafficking and money laundering
charges in Florida.
   If things had gone right for the rebels, ``Noriega would have
been at night court in Miami listening to a judge telling him he
was being detained without bail,'' one U.S. official said wistfully.
   However, U.S. Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney said U.S.
officials didn't know how long Noriega had been held and told
reporters, ``Clearly they (his captors) were not of a mind to turn
him over to us.''
   In Panama City, neighbors said they saw Noriega enter Defense
Forces headquarters with members of his staff Tuesday morning, and
that the shooting began about 10 minutes later. They spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   During the fighting Castrejon made a television announcement
saying Noriega was in an undisclosed location and was in radio
contact with his troops.
   Later, Maj. Edgardo Lopez, a Defense Forces spokesman, said
Noriega had personally taken the rebels' surrender, meaning he was
on the spot when the fighting ended.
   The headquarters building is a four-story structure that
occupies an entire city block. The Urraca company, whose soldiers
were involved in the coup attempt, is located in barracks across a
small patio in the same Defense Forces compound that extends for
several hundred yards along Panama Bay.
   Jose Blandon, a Panamanian defector once close to Noriega, said
in Washington he had been told by a coup leader over the telephone
during the uprising that the general had been wounded, but when
Noriega appeared before television cameras later there was no sign
of an injury.
   Asked why the rebels would decide to free Noriega, one U.S.
official said, ``It's crazy. I don't understand it.''
   The U.S. officials said they are concerned that the rebels face
a bleak future in detention. The sources said some of the
insurgents involved in the March 1988 uprising are still being
tortured.
   U.S. officials have refused to comment on reports that some of
the rebels took refuge at U.S. Southern Command headquarters in
Quarry Heights, a few hundred yards from the fighting.
   Asked if anything positive occurred during Tuesday's events, the
officials said Noriega had tried hard through purges to ensure the
loyalty of the Defense Forces but was still unable to head off an
uprising.
   Tuesday's coup attempt also was much closer to succeeding than
the 1988 insurrection, the officials said, adding that Noriega's
own behavior Tuesday evening indicated how close he had come to
being deposed.
   Noriega was ebullient after riding out the earlier coup and was
far more subdued this time, they said.
   By Wednesday, however, Noriega leaned out a window to wave to a
cheering crowd of supporters outside his bullet-pocked headquarters.
</TEXT>
