<HEAD>Coppola Beginning `Godfather 3' Movie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third act of ``The Godfather'' films
begins next month in Italy with Francis Ford Coppola directing Al
Pacino as the powerful underworld don Michael Corleone.
   Paramount's ``The Godfather _ The Continuing Story'' starts
filming in Rome on Nov. 15 from a script written by Coppola and
Mario Puzo, who first chronicled the Corleone saga in the
best-selling novel ``The Godfather.''
   In addition to Pacino, nominated twice for Academy Awards in the
previous two films, Diane Keaton will return as the ex-wife of
Pacino's Corleone and Talia Shire, Coppola's sister, reprises her
role as sister Connie Corleone.
   New faces in the trilogy will be Andy Garcia, who portrays an
illegitimate Corleone son, and Eli Wallach as a friend of the late
Don Corleone.
   ``We hope to do something in the tradition of the others,''
Coppola told Daily Variety in Wednesday's editions. ``If all three
were put together, we would like to feel they're all part of one
`Godfather' project.
   ``This is very much a third act.''
   The original ``Godfather'' movie was released in 1972; the
sequel two years later garnered 16 Oscar nominations. Each won the
coveted best picture Academy Award.
   The two ``Godfather'' movies have grossed more than $700 million
worldwide.
