<FIRST>u w AM-JuvenileExtradition 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Juvenile Extradition, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0727,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Refuses To Block Extradition of Alabama Juvenile</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITS a0777 to note earlier story in keyword line.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia Court of Appeals
refused Wednesday to block the extradition of a juvenile facing a
possible death sentence in Alabama in connection with a 1988
firebombing that killed a 14-month-old boy.
   A three-judge panel of the court ruled that the district must
honor an interstate agreement governing the extradition of
juveniles, despite the district's own ban against capital
punishment.
   ``If our city, through its courts, does not respect its
obligations to other jurisdictions, then they will not respect
theirs to us,'' Associate Judge Frank E. Schwelb wrote in a
concurring opinion.``Under the compact, the district's word is its
bond.''
   The youth, identified only by the initials O.M., has been held
by district authorities since last December, when he was arrested
in connection with a warrant issued by Gadsden, Ala., authorities,
charging him with arson and murder in the death of Tamel Jackson.
   The infant was killed when a firebomb was hurled into a Gadsden
apartment. Alabama authorities also have charged two uncles of O.M.
with arson and murder in the case. One of the uncles, another
juvenile identified by the initials S.T., was arrested by district
authorities in August and is fighting extradition.
   The appeals court ruling dissolves an order that had been
blocking O.M.'s extradition. One of the boy's lawyers, James Klein
of the district's public defender's office, declined to comment on
whether new legal challenges will be filed.
   Detective Lt. Jeff Wright of the Gadsden Police Department said
he will make travel plans to pick up O.M. and return him to Alabama
as soon as the department is notified officially of the ruling.
   The case has attracted widespread attention because of
contentions by O.M.'s lawyers that he cannot get a fair trial from
the predominantly white judicial system in Etowah County, Ala.,
where both his father and another relative died while in police
custody.
</TEXT>
