<HEAD>Panama's President: Coup Bid Was Work of Small, U.S.-Backed Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD quotes on rebels as unrepresentative of
military; charge U.S. wants to abrogate treaties; TRIMS pvs; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's provisional president on
Wednesday blamed the aborted coup against Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega on a small group of disgruntled soldiers backed by the
United States.
   In remarks to reporters, Provisional President Francisco
Rodriguez asserted Tuesday's attempted coup ``was fostered and
supported by the government of the United States'' but that it
``found no resonance of any kind within the ranks of the defense
forces or citizens.''
   He asserted there was no widespread dissatisfaction in the
Panamanian military. Noriega, the Defense Forces chief, uses his
official position to maintain de facto control of the government.
   In Tuesday's coup attempt, rebel forces attacked and seized the
Defense Forces headquarters in Panama City and claimed to have
ousted Noriega. But forces loyal to Noriega counterattacked and
took back the compound several hours later.
   The Panamanian military said about 65 rebel soldiers were
detained.
   In his comments, Rodriguez claimed videotapes show U.S. tanks
and ``U.S. contingents in combat readiness blocking roads in our
country in order to prevent contingents of the Defense Forces from
having access to the headquarters.'' He said film and photographs
would also be release as proof.
   President Bush has denied the United States engineered the
attempt to overthrow Noriega, but White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said U.S. officials had advance knowledge of it.
   U.S. officials said American forces moved into positions near
the fighting for security reasons.
   Rodriguez was asked why a superpower like the United States
would not be able to topple Noriega if it really wanted to support
a coup.
   ``It is clear that overt aggression backed by actual troops of
the U.S. Army would make everything too clear, and they really
wanted to cover up their ambitions in this area. But there is clear
evidence, photographs and so on, that there was support from the
U.S. Army stationed in our country,'' said Rodriguez.
   He said his provisional government will ``evaluate'' whether to
hold national elections some time after March but that Panama
cannot hold free and fair elections until the United States ends
its ``military and economic aggression.''
   The U.S. government has been trying to force out Noriega since
two federal grand juries in Florida indicted him on
drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges last year.
   U.S. efforts have included diplomatic pressure and trade and
economic sanctions against Panama.
   But the steps have not budged Noriega, whose government annulled
May 7 presidential elections. International observers said
opposition candidate Guillermo Endara won the presidency by a
landslide.
   Rodriguez, a longstanding associate of Noriega, was installed as
a provisional president after the election was nullified.
</TEXT>
