<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Norway-Nobel     10-04 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Nobel,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Europeans High Among Peace Prize Contenders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights activists and the leaders of
democratic forces in communist Eastern Europe were high on the list
of 90 candidates for the Nobel Peace Prize, to be announced
Thursday.
   The Peace Prize is given by a five-member committee chosen by
the Norwegian parliament and the other Nobels are awarded by the
prize committee in Stockholm, Sweden.
   Candidates included Abbe Pierre, a French Roman Catholic priest
nominated for humanitarian work; Bruno Hussar, who set up an
Israeli-Palestinian peace village in Israel, Nelson Mandela, the
imprisoned black South African leader, and the International Scout
Movement, celebrating its 100th year.
   Sources who have been reliable in the past said the Dalai Lama,
exiled god-king of Tibetan Buddhists, had a chance of being chosen,
but the ferment in eastern Europe caused speculation that the prize
would go a democratic leader in the region.
   Often in recent years, the Peace Prize has been used to
encourage trends considered worthy and to build international
support for peace efforts.
   The 1987 award to President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica was
considered a major boost to his Central American peace plan, which
was adopted by the five presidents involved. Last year, the prize
went to the U.N. peacekeeping forces.
   Dagbladet, an Oslo newspaper, put two Czechoslovak dissidents,
writer Vaclav Havel and Jiri Hajek, foreign minister in the
reformist government of Alexander Dubcek at the time of the 1968
Soviet-led invasion, among the leading candidates for 1989. They
were signers of the Charter 77 human rights manifesto in communist
Czechoslovakia.
   Members of Sweden's parliament collectively nominated the Baltic
republics of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, which were independent
when the Soviet Union absorbed them in 1940.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet Union and former
President Ronald Reagan were early nominees for their 1987
agreement to eliminate medium-range nuclear missiles. Nominations
close on Feb. 1 and the accord came too late for last year's prize.
   The first Peace Prize was awarded in 1901, but in 19 years none
was given. Nobel prizes this year are worth three million Swedish
kronor _ $469,000 at the current exchange rate.
   Prizes for peace, chemistry, literature, medicine and physics
were established by the estate of Alfred Nobel, who invented
dynamite and made a fortune. A sixth prize, in economics, was added
later and financed Sweden's central bank.
   Members of the Norwegian committee are Egil Aarvik, a retired
journalist and Cabinet minister; former Prime Minister Odvar
Nordli; history professor Francis Sejersted, the Rev. Gunnar J.
Staalsett, a Lutheran minister, and author Gidske Anderson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Soviets     10-04 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Soviets,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Propose Expanded ``Hot Line'' As Part of Peace Initiative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow on Wednesday suggested turning its
``hot line'' with Washington into a worldwide party line.
   Saying hot line expansion would reduce the risk of war, the
Soviets proposed linking the line between the Soviet and U.S.
capitals also with Beijing, London, Paris, the U.N. headquarters
and nations belonging to the non-aligned movement.
   Vladimir Petrovsky, the Soviet deputy foreign minister, said
that idea and other ways of averting wars in the making were
submitted to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on Wednesday.
   Petrovsky, who leads the Soviet U.N. delegation during the
General Assembly, said previously that Moscow hopes this year to
begin implementing practical aspects of its sweeping proposals to
improve world security.
   The Soviet Union has discussed its ideas with many nations, he
said, including the United States, where Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze broached the subject with Secretary of State James A.
Baker III.
   He said the U.N. Secretariat ``could establish a military risk
reduction center as a link between the U.N. headquarters and the
Security Council members' capital cities and the chairman of the
non-aligned movement.''
   The 102-member non-aligned movement is made up of nations
without formal military alliances with East or West.
</TEXT>
