<FIRST>u i AM-Belgium-Slaying 1stLd-Writethru a0661 10-04 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Slaying, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Leader Slaying Viewed as Terrorist Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE justice minister calls it terrorist
act. Pickup 6th graf, Prime Minister ... with minor editing to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Joseph Wybran, the leader of
Belgium's Jewish community, was shot to death in a hospital parking
lot in what the justice minister on Wednesday called an act of
terrorism.
   Police said Wybran, 49, was shot once in the head from close
range at about 6 p.m. Tuesday as he approached his car outside
Brussels University Hospital, where he headed the immunology
department. He underwent emergency surgery but died early Wednesday.
   No one claimed responsibility.
   Wybran, head of a coalition of Jewish groups, was a moderate in
the Israeli-Arab conflict. He campaigned for removal of a Roman
Catholic convent from the site of the Auschwitz concentration camp
in Poland.
   Justice Minister Melchior Wathelet told a radio station
Wednesday, ``This cold-blooded murder committed with such
efficiency points to a terrorist act, probably linked to the role
Dr. Wybran played at the head of the Jewish community _ even worse,
because of his moderation.''
   There were no witnesses. Police made a nationwide appeal for
information.
   Police were investigating whether the killing was anti-Semitic
or political.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel said Wybran would ``go
down in history as an example of a Jew who fought for the sake of
his people.''
   A statement from the Israeli Embassy said Wybran had no personal
enemies, and ``it is therefore evident'' that he ``was assassinated
in cold blood because he was a Jew.''
   Michel Peytier, a spokesman for the Brussels prosecutor's
office, said, ``Given the nature of his activities, it cannot be
excluded that this was a political attack.''
   He added that ``at first sight it is very unlikely, not to say
beyond probability'' that Wybran was killed for private reasons.
   Prime Minister Wilfried Martens issued a statement expressing
``indignation at violence and intolerance.''
   Wybran headed the Coordinating Committee of Jewish Organizations
in Belgium, which represents about 30,000 Jews in this
overwhelmingly Catholic country of 9.9 million.
   He also served as chairman of the Belgian chapter of the
Auschwitz Committee, which has pressed for removal of an order of
Carmelite nuns from the site of the former Nazi death camp.
   On a recent visit to Poland, Wybran urged authorities to
publicly oppose anti-Semitism and other forms of racism.
   Jewish leaders say the convent and its religious symbols are
offensive at place where 2.5 million Jews were killed.
   The church has said it will move the convent to an interfaith
center to be built nearby.
   Israeli Ambassador Avi Primor told Israeli army radio Wednesday
that neo-Nazis might have been behind Wybran's murder because of
his involvement in the Auschwitz matter.
   In 1980, one youngster was killed in a grenade attack in
Brussels on 50 Jewish teen-agers bound for summer camp. Three
people were killed the next year when an explosives-laden van blew
up outside an Antwerp synagogue and, in 1982, attackers sprayed a
Brussels synagogue with automatic weapons fire, wounding four
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
