<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     10-04 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Union To Continue Suspension of Arms Shipments to Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will keep withholding
arms shipments to Nicaragua to encourage the United States to take
similar steps in Central America, officials announced Wednesday.
   The announcement was made in a Nicaraguan government statement
at the end of a 24-hour visit by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze. The Soviet official told reporters it amounted to a
joint statement.
   The communique said the suspension ``is a contribution Nicaragua
and the Soviet Union are making toward a total solution to the
conflict in the region and a decided support of the Central
American presidential agreements.''
   President Daniel Ortega and the presidents of four other Central
American countries signed an agreement Aug. 7 calling for
demobilizing the U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels based in border
camps in Honduras.
   In exchange, the leftist Sandinista government agreed to make
democratic reforms, including allowing free campaigning by the
opposition for elections advanced to February 1990.
   The temporary halt to weapons shipments ``opens great
opportunities,'' Shevardnadze said. He said a total and permanent
suspension in weapons shipments would have to be ``reciprocated''
by the United States.
   However, he said the region also needs a way of setting limits
on combat forces in the Central American countries.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told President Bush in May
that the Soviet Union had suspended weapons shipments to Nicaragua
at the end of 1988.
   Soviet aid totaled $11.2 billion from 1980 to 1988, half of it
in military assistance. Though it says it has cut off supplies of
weapons, the Soviet Union has still sent Ortega's government $500
million in various forms of military aid this year.
   The United States has supported the Nicaraguan Contra rebels,
who have fought to overthrow the Sandinistas. However, it halted
weapons shipments to them in February 1988 while continuing such
aid as uniforms, food, vehicles and other supplies.
   However, the Sandinistas want the United States to cut off all
aid to the rebels.
   Washington also provides military and economic aid to the
Salvadoran government in its 10-year-old war against a leftist
insurgency.
   On the battlefront, Contra rebels attacked a military patrol in
western Nicaragua on Wednesday, killing six soldiers and wounding
six, the Defense Ministry said.
   In a news release, the ministry said the attack occurred near
the village of Puerto de Paris, 110 miles west of Managua. It gave
no details of the fighting.
   The government radio, the Voice of Nicaragua, called the attack
``cowardly and treacherous,'' noting that the government has called
a unilateral cease-fire in an effort to end the war.
   Also Wednesday, the Interior Ministry said two election
officials were kidnapped by Contras near the town of San Nicolas,
about 80 miles north of Managua. Its news release gave no details.
</TEXT>
