<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     10-04 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Guerrillas Kidnap TV Executive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen thought to be leftist guerrillas
kidnapped prominent TV executive Hector Delgado Parker on Wednesday
after shooting up his armored-plated car, killing his driver and
badly wounding his bodyguard, police said.
   Police said pamphlets from the pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru
Revolutionary Movement were found at the site. Witnesses said some
of those involved in the abduction were disguised as police
directing traffic.
   Delgado, the senior news executive of the major Channel 5
television station, served as an adviser to President Alan Garcia
before resigning two years ago in disagreement with Garcia's
efforts to nationalize Peru's banks. His family has controlling
interest in the station.
   Delgado may have been wounded in the shooting, witnesses said.
He was seized six blocks from Channel 5 in the middle-class suburb
of Lince.
   Witnesses told police another automobile cut off Delgado's car
at a street corner and that three men jumped from a second car that
was following the executive's vehicle and opened fire with
submachine guns.
   Delgado's car was hit at least 30 times, its windows shot out,
its tires punctured and deflated, police said.
   His driver was hit at least 12 times and died on the way to a
hospital. his bodyguard returned fire, but was struck by at least
seven bullets, police said.
   Witnesses said that up to eight kidnappers took part, including
three dressed as police who steered traffic away after Delgado's
car was intercepted.
</TEXT>
