<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Gypsies     10-04 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Gypsies,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Order Gypsies Ejected From Former Nazi Death Camp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hamburg officials ejected a group
of Gypsies occupying a former Nazi death camp site near this
northern port city, police spokesman Peter Michael Wenig said
Wednesday.
   Police moved in on Monday after city cultural officials, who own
and oversee the former Neuengamme concentration camp, filed a
trespassing complaint, Wenig told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview.
   He said police ordered 60 Gypsies occupying a building at the
camp to leave, adding, ``They decided to leave peaceably, we didn't
have to drag anyone or push anyone out. There was no force used.''
   The Gypsies have accused Hamburg police of using force to eject
them. Gypsy spokesman Yaron Matras told reporters in Hamburg on
Tuesday the police action ``makes a farce of claims that everyone
can live freely in West Germany.''
   The Gypsies and set up house trailers and built campfires there
Sunday to protest rejection of some of their applications for
asylum in West Germany.
   They demand that all be allowed to stay in West Germany and none
be forced to return to their Yugoslav homeland. A decision on
possible deportation is pending.
   The Gypsies now are staying at a Protestant church community
center.
   About 500,000 Gypsies were exterminated during the the Nazi era.
</TEXT>
