<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-AfghanKiteFights Adv11   10-04 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan Kite Fights, Adv 11,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday AMs, Oct. 11, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Afgans Engage in Another Kind of Combat _ Kite Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another kind of combat _ kite fighting
_ draws hundreds of Afghans to the fields on the edge of Kabul on
Friday afternoons.
   They call it ``the game'' and some bet the equivalent of $10 _
the monthly wage of a starting government employee _ on the outcome.
   Kites fly over Kabul all the time, especially in the strong
winds that follow a rainstorm. They are the favorite of most
children because other toys are too expensive and kites are cheap.
All it takes to make a kite are some bright paper, bamboo sticks
and string, usually costing a dollar or two. Those who can't afford
the favored paper from Germany make do with plastic bags.
   ``School children invented kites,'' said Mohammid Nabi Delaghah,
43, one of the kite sellers around the Shor Bazaar who promote the
idea that Afghan children were the first to make kites.
   Told that other accounts have it that kites originated in China
around the time the Great Wall was being built, he concedes that
maybe Afghans only invented fighting with them.
   ``Two people with kites had a war 90 years ago,'' said Delaghah.
``A guy named Osman Bijo got a medal after he won the fight.''
   The rules for ``the game'' call for the competing kites to be
the same size with string from the same country _ supposedly to
assure that both will be of the same strength. But the specialists
say the real strength comes in the amount of crushed glass that is
glued onto the string: too much makes it inflexible; not enough
makes it weak.
   ``It's my specialty, but I won't show anybody how to make good
line,'' said Khan Shareen, a recognized expert on the string.
   When the kites get 900 to 1,200 feet up, the battle starts with
a nod or a shout between the duelers _ men usually in their 30s and
40s.
   A cry goes up from the spectators: ``They're fighting! They're
fighting!''
   A fight takes about 15 minutes.
   Qari Gholam Samih, 35, said he has not lost a kite in two years
of fighting. He said he spent five years just getting ready.
   The trick, he said, is ``to be brave, to have no fear.''
   The real war occasionally intercedes. Last winter a helicopter
came roaring over the field and took down about 50 kites.
   Kites are even part of Afghan literature. A famous short story,
``Word of Honor'' by Akram Osman, made into a movie, centers around
a kite maker from the Shor Bazaar who wants to marry his cousin.
   ``It would've been wonderful if the kites had eyes like yours,''
the kite maker says in the opening scene.
   The cousin's father, however, opposes the union, keeping his
daughter at home and even changing houses when the kite maker
successfully lands a kite that says ``Happy Holidays'' into their
courtyard.
   Then the story takes a certain Afghan twist _ the kite maker
takes up body building and beats the woman's brother at wrestling.
Only then is he allowed to marry the cousin.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Oct. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-KnightsofMalta Adv12   10-04 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Knights of Malta, Adv 12,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Oct. 12, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Knights of Malta Returning to Island They Once Ruled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: The knights return Oct. 17-22.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>By TERRY LEONARD</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALLETTA, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly two centuries after Napoleon's
forces routed them, the Knights of Malta are returning to the
island they got from an emperor in exchange for a falcon and ruled
for 268 years.
   The ``monks in armor'' will be here Oct. 17-22 for a gathering
their leadership hopes will help bolster Malta's economy.
   Officially named the Sovereign Military Order of the Hospital of
St. John of Jerusalem, of Rhodes and of Malta, the knights are the
oldest order of chivalry and the fourth oldest religious order in
the Roman Catholic Church.
   They ruled this rocky and almost barren Mediterranean
archipelago from 1530, when Emperor Charles V gave it to them for
the price of one trained falcon a year, until 1798 when Napoleon
sent them packing without the treasures they acquired during
centuries of plundering the Ottoman Empire.
   Fra Andrew Bertie, the 78th grand master of the 900-year-old
order, has summoned the knights back and has urged them to help
Malta improve its economy.
   For centuries, membership in the knights required proof of
generations of nobility. Although some ranks today are open to
those without noble ancestry, the rolls are still crowded with the
wealthy and influential.
   The New York financier J. Peter Grace is a member, as are former
U.S. Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig, Premier Giulio Andreotti
and President Francesco Cossiga of Italy and Giovanni Agnelli,
chairman of the Italian automobile company Fiat. Edward Bennett
Williams, the Washington attorney and owner of the Baltimore
Orioles major league baseball team who died in August 1988, also
was a member.
   Such men are one reason the order's Maltese association asked
Bertie to call the knights back to Malta, which in 25 years of
independence from Britain has found the economic road as rocky as
its coastline.
   Bertie, a long-time former resident of Malta, encourged knights
worldwide to attend the first world gathering of the order and
openly solicited their help.
   ``I also urge those of you who are directly or indirectly
interested in facilitating contacts with the development of the
economic life of the island to do so,'' Bertie told the knights
earlier this year in New York.
   Roger de Giorgio, president of the Maltese association of the
ancient order now based in Rome, said about 500 of the 10,000
members are expected to travel to Malta.
   ``We want knights from around the world to exchange ideas about
our hospital work and to rediscover Malta,'' said de Giorgio.
``During the 268 years the knights were here, they introduced new
thinking in architecture, law, medicine and merchant shipping.''
   The knights made Malta a thriving center of Christianity and
trade. De Giorgio said the knights also gave Malta the legal codes
that are the basis for much of its modern law. In 1575, they built
and then operated what then was one of the largest hospitals in
Europe. They gave Malta an architectural heritage of massive
fortifications and magnificent palaces and churches.
   The knights today operate about 200 hospitals and first aid
centers in 90 countries, especially in the Third World and war
zones.
   The order was founded in the late 11th century with the opening
of a hospice for pilgrims in Jerusalem. Its centuries-old
dedication to hospital work began when it treated the sick and
wounded after the army of the First Crusade captured Jerusalem in
1099.
   It first took up arms in the 12th century to defend the pilgrim
routes to the Holy Land.
   In the late 13th century, after the Holy Land fell to the
Moslems, the knights moved first to Cyrpus and then to Rhodes where
they built a navy to fight the Moslem Ottoman Empire.
   Sultan Suleiman the Magnificent defeated the knights and forced
them to leave Rhodes on Jan. 1, 1523, although with huge losses to
his troops.
   Seven years later, the knights resumed the fight from Malta.
Once again Suleiman attacked. This time 600 knights, 1,230 mostly
Spanish soldiers and about 6,000 Maltese militia defeated an
Ottoman army of 40,000. That victory in 1565 marked the beginning
of the end for Ottoman seapower and earned the knights the
gratitude of a threatened Europe.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, Oct. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
