<FIRST>a i AM-ReligionToday Adv06   10-04 0834</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 06,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Oct. 6, and thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>After 200 Years, Jesuits Return To Fight for Indians' Rights ^By
PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN IGNACIO DE MOXOS, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two centuries
after their expulsion by the Spanish crown, Jesuit priests are back
in this tropical outpost to champion the rights of Indians and a
shrinking wilderness.
   ``I always try to think in terms of how the Jesuits of 200 years
ago would have handled a problem,'' said the Rev. Enrique Jordan
Arias, a leader in the local Indians' battle with timber companies
exploiting the mahogany forests.
   ``We try to follow that Jesuit heritage in our fight with the
woodcutters,'' he told a visiting Associated Press reporter. ``San
Ignacio is where the Jesuit tradition is best preserved, and where
it is replanted in terms of modern problems.''
   San Ignacio de Moxos, on the vast eastern Bolivian savannah
called the Beni, was founded by Jesuits in 1689 as part of the
religious order's missionary penetration of South America's
heartland during Spain's colonial period.
   At the mission the Jesuits brought 14 Indian communities
together in a communal society and taught them weaving, carpentry,
cermanics, music and agriculture. They introduced cattle ranching
and coffee and peanut farming.
   One Jesuit priest, Francisco Eder, described the Indians' life
in an 18th century book as one of ``peace and tranquility, with an
abundance of food and clothing.''
   In 1768, the missionaries were forced to abandon San Ignacio de
Moxos, expelled with all members of their order across South
America by a Spanish crown that considered their motives and
technique subversive.
   The outpost survived but even now, with 6,000 inhabitants, it
remains remote. A dirt road winds northeastward for 270 miles to
the capital city of La Paz high in the Andes mountains. It is
impassable in the rainy season and always treacherous.
   ``This town has become a crossroads for lumbermen, merchants,
cocaine traffickers and ranchers,'' Jordan Arias, 50, said.
   His order returned to San Ignacio de Moxos in 1982 with three
priests. They function from a whitewashed church with elaborately
carved altars and furniture painted red, yellow and purple, all
dating back to the Jesuits' original stay.
   They also observe some of the founding traditions, including the
annual procession in which a statue of San Ignacio, the town's
patron saint, is carried around the square by the priests, town
officials, prominent citizens and Indians of the local Moxo tribe.
   Some Indians wear feather headdresses, wooden masks or other
colorful costumes and march to the accompaniment of long bamboo
woodwinds, playing a music taught to their ancestors by the
original Jesuits.
   When the ceremony ends, the European-descended townspeople and
the Indian descendants go their separate ways. This unofficial but
deeply entrenched racial discrimination is as abominable to the
Jesuits now as it was in the 1600s, when they were sharply critical
of the Spaniards' treatment of Indians.
   ``There are two worlds in this town,'' Jordan Arias said. ``They
go to school together, but then the whites go to their social club
and the Indians go to their social and spiritual center.
   ``One notices a great deal of discrimination and hostility
between the white and Indian communities,'' he said. Many Indians
are used as poorly paid laborers by white landowners and merchants.
   The church has published books and pamphlets detailing the rich
cultural heritage of the Moxo Indians and recently helped organize
a national conference on tropical forests and Indian rights that
attracted hundreds of delegates here.
   ``The legacy of the Jesuits is a better civilization and for
people to care for each other as brothers,'' said Antonio Coseruna,
the 36-year-old president of the Moxo Indian Council.
   ``The Jesuits are now teaching us how to defend our rights, and
to demand better pay,'' he said. ``The white men don't like the
Jesuits because ... before it was easy for the white men to cheat
us.''
   The government has given seven timber companies rights to the
vast forests around San Ignacio. But in response to a
Jesuit-sponsored public campaign, it now is considering a law that
would declare part of the wilderness an Indian reservation and
regulate the harvest of mahogany and other valuable hardwoods.
   For years, standard practice has been to remove worthwhile
timber then let settlers burn off the rest of the forest for
farming, which quickly exhausted the thin layer of topsoil. Left
behind are huge tracts of worthless, barren land.
   ``In 10 years, there will be no forests and animals left,''
Coseruna said.
   Not all whites resent the return of the Jesuits. They get high
praise from Ana Maria Ruiz de Antelo, 30, president of the town
council and member of a prominent cattle-ranching family, who has
worked to revive the Indian tradition in handicrafts that
languished after the Jesuits were ousted.
   ``The Jesuits,'' she said, ``have returned to awaken and defend
indigenous people because they have nobody else to protect them.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Oct. 6</NOTE>
