<DOCNO> AP891004-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IBM     10-04 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Supercomputing Software Based on AT&amp;T Advance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
announced software for supercomputers based on a patented
breakthrough by a mathematician at AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories.
   AT&amp;T introduced its own package of hardware and software based
on the so-called Karmarkar algorithm last year and it appears that
IBM's entry Tuesday puts the two technology giants in direct
competition.
   An IBM press release made no mention of AT&amp;T and simply said
that part of its software's power ``stems from a new programming
method which drew worldwide attention when it was introduced a few
years ago.''
   IBM spokesman Denis Arvay, who mentioned the AT&amp;T connection,
said IBM was entitled to use the AT&amp;T patent through a
cross-licensing agreement between the companies.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Bob Ford said he could not find anyone at AT&amp;T
who knew of the IBM product and thus the company had no comment on
it.
   The Karmarkar algorithm, invented in 1984 by AT&amp;T's Narendra
Karmarkar, is a programming method for solving resource-allocation
problems that involve huge numbers of variables, such as scheduling
daily crew assignments for a major airline.
   IBM said its software was able to obtain the best solution to an
airline scheduling problem in less time than a Cray 2 supercomputer
from Cray Research Inc. reportedly took to solve a problem
one-tenth the size.
   IBM's software, known as the Optimization Subroutine Library,
runs on big 3090 mainframe computers that have add-on equipment to
make them work as supercomputers. But IBM said versions of it can
run on smaller IBM computers, even its personal computers.
   The chief creators of IBM's software were John Tomlin of IBM's
Almaden Research Center in San Jose, Calif., and John Forrest of
the Thomas J. Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y.
   AT&amp;T's hardware-software product, Korbx, was introduced in
August 1988 at a price of $8.9 million. So far there are two
customers willing to have their names publicized, the Military
Airlift Command and Delta Air Lines Inc.
</TEXT>
