<FIRST>r f PM-TopCities     10-04 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Top Cities,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fortune Rates Dallas, Atlanta, Kansas City Top Business Metro Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dallas, Atlanta and Kansas City, Mo., are the
best metropolitan areas in America for U.S. businesses, according
to rankings in a Fortune magazine survey.
   The business biweekly said Tuesday it ranked the top 10 of the
nation's largest metro areas based on such factors as labor force,
cost of doing business, economic base, infrastructure and quality
of life.
   Dallas-Fort Worth emerged on top based on its 28 percent
commercial real estate vacancy rate, large pool of ``talented
workers,'' surging population and active night life.
   ``The so-called Metroplex, embracing the suburbs and the area
between the cities, is today's dream location for business, largely
because of surplus office and factory space in the wake of the oil
bust,'' Fortune said.
   The survey results appear in the Oct. 23 issue of the magazine,
which hits newsstands on Wednesday.
   The ratings were based on the magazine's opinions and a
statistical profile compiled by the corporate location consultants
Moran Stahl &amp; Boyer, Fortune said. It also factored in the opinions
of chief executives of big companies as compiled by business real
estate firm Cushman &amp; Wakefield.
   Among the statistical factors were labor supply growth since
1983, rate of growth in taxes, government bond ratings and local
government debt per capita.
   Fortune said No. 2 Atlanta rated highly because of its
appearance, low salaries and other business costs, and because it
has available land for expansion. Drawbacks included a high cost of
living and high crime rate.
   Kansas City scored for its fountains, museums, Frank Lloyd
Wright houses and midtown Country Club Plaza shopping area, as well
as good center city housing and an ample supply of technical and
professional labor.
   The rest of Fortune's top 10, in order: Los Angeles, Baltimore,
New York, California's Bay Area, Pittsburgh, Portland, Ore., and
Minneapolis-St. Paul.
</TEXT>
