<DOCNO> AP891004-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0105EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TimberInvestment Bjt   10-04 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Timber Investment, Bjt,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Timberland Investments Touted as Hedge Against Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GORDON FAIRCLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timberland is drawing increased
attention from investors who are rediscovering its value as a
relatively low-risk investment that provides a good hedge against
inflation, experts say.
   ``There is a growing interest by non-traditional investors in
timberlands _ pension funds and individuals _ who are looking at
timber as another asset to diversify their portfolios,'' said Clark
S. Binkley, a professor at Yale University's forestry and business
schools.
   ``The conventional wisdom (has been) that timber stands are
risky investments because of forest fires, insect infestations and
a volatile demand linked to fluctuations in the housing market,''
Binkley said. ``But the reality is that you can store timber on the
stump until demand goes up and only a miniscule percentage will be
lost to fires and disease.''
   Because timberland does not tend to fall prey to the same market
forces as stocks and bonds, Binkley said, it can be a useful tool
in building a diversified portfolio. Investments in timber also can
offer comparable rates of return to stocks and bonds with
considerably less risk, he said.
   Southern pine timberland, for example, has had an annual return
of about 10 percent since 1955.
   Investors are being drawn to timberland because of ``the
diversification and low risk coupled with what we consider very
good returns,'' said Robert Chambers, the Atlanta-based vice
president and manager of timberland for First Wachovia Investment
Management, a division of the First Wachovia Bank.
   Chambers said that pension funds have invested $600 million to
$700 million in timberland.
   While some pension funds, like USX Corp.'s, own thousands acres
on their own, most of these non-traditional investors join with
other investors in timberland investment funds.
   The largest fund is run by John Hancock, the Boston-based
insurance and financial services company. Other insurance
companies, including Mutual of New York, also manage timber funds,
as does First Wachovia Bank, which is based in Winston-Salem, N.C.
   First Wachovia runs the country's only open-ended fund, which
allows investors to increase or decrease the size of their
investments and allows new investors to join each quarter.
   Other funds are closed-ended, with participants investing a
fixed amount and remaining committed to the fund until a pre-set
maturation date.
   First Wachovia's fund has seven investors and owns about 33,000
acres of forest in Georgia, Florida and Mississippi, Chambers said.
   He said he expects ``substantial growth'' over the next three to
five years for timberland funds as they become more accepted by
pension fund managers.
   Binkley, a forestry professor who also has an appointment at
Yale's School of Organization and Management, has been working to
quantify the risks involved in timber investments.
   ``We need to be able to explain timberland to potential
investors in exactly the same terms as stocks, bonds and other
investments,'' he said in a recent interview.
   Binkley said his research shows that Maine timberland presents
the least risk to investors, while Southern woodland is slightly
more risky and timberland in the Pacific Northwest is the most
risky.
   Investments in Pacific Northwest timberland seem to be the most
volatile because of the federal government's controls on the sale
of timber there. Congress sets sales levels for timber in the
region every year, so lumber prices are not simply a function of
market forces, Binkley said.
   Binkley said, however, that as risk increases, so does the
potential for investment return.
   ``I'm not saying that every individual or pension fund manager
should rush to invest in timber. I am trying to provide the tools
they can use to assess whether the investment is right for them,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0106EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern     10-04 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Releases $75 Million to Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troubled Eastern Airlines, striving to rebuild
as a smaller carrier, has received permission to dip into $75
million held in escrow and to sell a $30 million note that it owns.
   At a hearing Tuesday, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland
granted Eastern's request to use the $75 million, which came from
asset sales, to help run its operations through the end of the year.
   Miami-based Eastern, which was struck by its unions and filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in early March, is selling
about $1.8 billion in jets, routes and other assets.
   In a separate action Tuesday, the Senate voted to cut off debate
on long-stalled legislation that would require creation of a
commission to investigate and recommend solutions to the Eastern
strike, which has entered its eighth month.
   David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed bankruptcy examiner for
Eastern, told Lifland he supported Eastern's request for the funds
on the grounds that it needed the cash to keep operating.
   After the $75 million is withdrawn, Eastern will have about $300
million left in escrow from which to repay its creditors or cover
operating expenses.
   The $75 million is necessary for and will be sufficient to
support Eastern's fourth-quarter operations, said Bruce Zirinsky,
an attorney for the airline. He reiterated the company's assertion
that it is exceeding the financial projections made in an operating
plan it released in April.
   In July, Eastern asked for $100 million from the escrow account
for running operations in the third quarter. Lifland agreed to the
release of $75 million at that time.
   Lifland also ruled Tuesday that Eastern could sell an unsecured
$30 million note that it acquired in 1986 from sister carrier
Continental Airlines. The note was originally issued by now-defunct
People Express Airlines, a no-frills carrier that was absorbed by
Continental.
   The judge also postponed until Dec. 15 a hearing on the unions'
request for a special trustee to be appointed to run Eastern in
place of current management. Consideration of the request by the
Eastern pilots, Machinists union members and flight attendants has
been put off several times by the judge.
   Shapiro requested that the trustee issue be postponed until he
can finish an in-depth financial investigation of Eastern,
Continental and their parent Texas Air Corp. Shapiro said he and
more than 20 associates are interviewing current and former
officers of the companies, union leaders and others.
   The examiner told the judge he expected to complete the
investigation by early December, and said his schedule has been
delayed several times by lawyers for the parties involved.
   Bruce Simon, an attorney for the pilots union, which supports
appointment of a trustee, said there was ``informal talk'' that the
investigation could take until next spring.
   Joel Zweibel, a lawyer representing the committee of Eastern's
major creditors, said that group did not believe a trustee should
be named at this time.
   Also Tuesday, Moody's Investors Service Inc. said it had lowered
its credit ratings on securities issued by Texas Air and
Continental, reflecting the ``high leverage, weak debt protection
and decreasing financial flexibility of the parent and its
subsidiaries.''
   The credit-rating agency said Texas Air's ability to support
Continental has been diminished by the bankruptcy of Eastern, its
other main subsidiary.
</TEXT>
