<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   10-04 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automakers Expect Tighter Market in 1990</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the 1990 model year debuts, automakers are
predicting a smaller U.S. car and truck market, more players in it
and the likelihood of more buyer incentives.
   Nearly 80 million vehicles have been sold during the last five
model years in the United States, or nearly one new car or truck
for every three people in the country. There has been some concern
that the market has been saturated.
   But demand that flagged during the 1989 model year, which
officially ended Saturday, may get a boost in the 1990 model year
as the vehicles on the road get older and closer to trade-in time.
   ``A lot of pessimists love to make the statement that we seem to
be selling cars at a pretty brisk clip for eight years now and who
needs a new car?'' said analyst Charles Brady of the New York
investment firm Oppenheimer &amp; Co. Inc.
   ``If we replace just one of three of the cars 10 years or older,
we'd sell 10 million vehicles,'' he said.
   Final sales figures, due out today, probably will show that just
under 15 million cars and trucks were sold during the 1989 model
year. Experts predict that figure won't be reached this model year.
   Bob Thomas, vice president and general manager of the Nissan
Division of Nissan Motor Corp. in U.S.A., this week predicted 14
million vehicles will be sold this year. General Motors Corp. is on
the high side of 1990 predictions at about 15 million, a slight
change from the 1989 model year.
   Chrysler Corp. expects about 14.2 million vehicles will be sold
in the 1990 model year, while Ford Motor Co. has said the figure
will be lower than the 14.8 million it believed were driven off
dealership lots in the 1989 model year. Ford has declined to make a
formal prediction for 1990 sales.
   During the past year, about two cars were sold for every truck,
and analysts predict that ratio will remain about the same, or
perhaps lean a little heavier toward trucks.
   Like Nissan, analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New
York is forecasting 14 million cars and trucks will be sold in the
1990 model year if incentives remain constant.
   He said that without the rebates that stretched through much of
1989, automakers would have sold 1 million fewer vehicles.
   ``That would have been an 11 percent drop instead of a 5 percent
drop,'' he said, referring to the 15.8 million vehicles sold during
the 1988 model year, the third best year in auto history.
   As the size of the market shrinks, the number of models offered
continues to grow.
   In the popular minivan segment, GM is introducing a trio of
models _ its first minivans with front wheel drive _ that Chrysler
admits will dent its dominance of that market. Chrysler is striking
back in part with an upscale version of its vans.
   On the luxury end of the car market, Japanese companies are
introducing two new lines to the United States this model year.
   Nissan's Infiniti and Toyota's Lexus are marketing two cars
each, ranging in price from just over $20,000 to nearly $40,000.
Jaguar of Britain also is introducing a new car to the U.S. market,
priced lower than its others at $39,700.
   On the less-expensive end of the market, GM's Chevrolet Division
is heavily promoting its Geo line of three cars and a sport-utility
vehicle made either entirely or partly by Japanese companies.
   Chrysler's dated Omni-Horizon models will continue, but with
less marketing emphasis, while Ford will introduce its new
generation of Escort-Tracer cars in mid-1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TobaccoSettlement     10-04 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tobacco Settlement,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Accepts Tobacco Firm's Settlement on False Advertising Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. has settled a
federal false advertising claim by agreeing ``not to misrepresent
in future advertisements'' the results of a study that linked
smoking and heart disease.
   The Federal Trade Commission was divided 3-1 over accepting the
settlement, which was termed ``conspicuously weak'' by the
dissenter, Commissioner Mary L. Azcuenaga.
   She said the acceptance ``demonstrates a modicum of interest, at
most, in important issues related to smoking and health'' and
indicates a double standard for deceptive advertising and lenient
treatment for Reynolds.
   Commissioner Andrew J. Strenio Jr. defended the agreement,
calling it ``both justified and commensurately strong.'' He said it
provides ``appropriate disincentives'' against recurrence of the
allegedly unfair and deceptive claims.
   In a statement, the tobacco firm said Tuesday it remains
convinced its advertising message ``constituted an exercise of free
speech'' but that it felt there was no purpose in continuing its
fight with the FTC.
   ``We have decided therefore to accept a settlement that puts the
matter behind the company,'' R.J. Reynolds said.
   The FTC complained that a Reynolds advertisement made false and
misleading claims about a long-term study funded by the National
Institutes of Health.
   ``Reynolds' advertisement falsely claimed that (the study)
provided scientific evidence that smoking is not as hazardous as
the public has been led to believe,'' the FTC complaint said. Also,
said the FTC, the ad falsely maintained that the study ``tends to
refute the theory that smoking causes heart disease.''
   The consent agreement is not an admission that the law was
violated and it can become final, after more commission debate,
after a 60-day comment period by the public.
   Commission chairman Janet D. Steiger did not vote on the order.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EngineeringAward     10-04 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Engineering Award,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Pair Win Top Engineering Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Texans credited with revolutionizing
electronics with their co-invention of the semiconductor microchip
were named the first winners of the Charles Stark Draper Prize, the
world's largest award given exclusively for engineering achievement.
   Jack S. Kilby, chief technical officer of the Houston Area
Research Center, and Robert N. Noyce, president of Sematech in
Austin, will share a $350,000 cash award and each will receive a
gold medal, officials announced Tuesday.
   The Draper prize, awarded for the first time this year, is
directed by the National Academy of Engineering, a private
organization affiliated with the National Academy of Sciences. The
prize will be awarded every two years.
   ``We believe that the Draper prize will focus world attention on
the important contributions of engineers in the same way that the
Nobel Prize now focuses attention on the accomplishemnts of
scientists,'' said Robert M. White, president of the National
Academy of Engineering.
   White said Kilby and Noyce are credited with the independent,
co-invention of the single crystal microchip. The microchip has led
to a revolution in electronics and has become a vital component in
machines used in communications, manufacturing, transportation and
computing.
   ``Very few things have changed the world as dramatically as the
integrated circuit,'' White said. ``Like the invention of the
telephone, the light bulb, or the automobile, the creation and
widespread practical application of the integrated circuit has
fundamentally changed our lives.''
   The microchip is used in electronic circuits that are at the
heart of such equipment as calculators, digital watches,
telephones, automatic cameras, personal computers, compact discs
and in the electronics of satellites, airplanes and military
weapons.
   Before the microchip was invented in the 1950s, electronic
circuits depended on transistors, resistors and capacitors that had
to be soldered and wired together to create a desired function.
Microchips, however, are made from a single silicon crystal and the
functions of thousands of electronic components can be built into a
chip about the size of a matchhead.
   Noyce, 62, is president and chief executive officer of Sematech,
a consortium conducting fundamental research in electronics and
computers.
   Kilby, 66, joined Texas Instruments in 1958 where he conducted
the research that led to his co-invention of the microchip. He is
now an independent consultant in Dallas and chief technical officer
for the Houston Area Research Center, a technology development
concern.
   Charles Stark Draper, for whom the engineering prize is named,
was the inventor of inertial navigation, a guidance system that
helped Apollo astronauts navigate to the moon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GenericDrugs     10-04 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Generic Drugs,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Says Generic Drug Review Results in One Recall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration says its
ongoing review of the 30 top-selling generic drugs has resulted so
far in the recall of one drug.
   Pharmaceutical Basics Inc. of Denver recalled its antifungal
nystatin tablets because they were found to be below potency, the
FDA said Tuesday.
   Five other companies have recalled drugs since the FDA began
investigating allegations of fraud and corruption within its
generic drug division and among some generic drug makers. None of
the recalled has posed a major safety problem, the FDA said.
   The FDA said the Sept. 27 recall by Pharmaceutical Basics was
``the first recall'' stemming from the testing. It did not say
whether further recalls would be required.
   The FDA said it has analyzed 1,827 samples of the 30 leading
generics for potency, dissolution, composition and other
specifications, and nearly all were found to be within acceptable
specifications. About 1.6 percent of the samples were found to be
deficient in potency or dissolution, which the FDA said is about
the rate it usually finds under normal industry conditions.
   The agency said it has more testing to do, and its findings are
to be released at the end of the month.
</TEXT>
