<DOCNO> AP891004-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 0122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Contel-McCaw Bjt   10-04 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contel-McCaw, Bjt,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Buying Half-Interest In NYC Cellular, Selling Southern Properties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After pounding for three months on LIN
Broadcasting Corp.'s front door, McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
is trying a side entrance in its takeover attempt.
   McCaw said Tuesday it would acquire a half-interest in a New
York City cellular franchise whose other half is owned by LIN
Broadcasting.
   At the same time, McCaw said it would sell its interests in 13
mobile-telephone franchises in Alabama, Kentucky and Tennessee to
Contel Cellular Inc.
   McCaw, the nation's largest cellular telephone company, said in
a statement that the New York deal involves an agreement to pay
$1.9 billion in cash for Metromedia Co.'s one-half interest in
Metro One, one of two New York cellular franchises. LIN, which owns
the other half, would have a 45-day right of first refusal to the
deal.
   The Metromedia deal would give McCaw a 50 percent voting
interest and 45.67 percent equity interest in the New York
franchise.
   LIN holds a 50 percent voting interest and 45 percent equity
interest in the franchise, which would be controlled entirely by
McCaw if its proposed acquisition of LIN goes through.
   ``It's a pretty savvy move by McCaw,'' said John Reddan, a stock
analyst for Moran &amp; Associates in New York. ``McCaw is basically
challenging LIN to either put up or shut up in New York.''
   The most immediate question for LIN officials would be whether
they wanted to borrow $1.9 billion to buy out Metro One. Taking on
the additional debt could make LIN less attractive in its own
efforts to merge with BellSouth Corp. in a 50-50 partnership,
analysts said.
   In June, McCaw offered to buy LIN for $5.85 billion. LIN
rejected that offer, but McCaw persisted, and dropped its offer
from $127 per share to $110 per share after a court decision in
July against LIN, which had claimed it owned key cellular franchise
rights in Philadelphia and New York Ciy.
   The $110-a-share offer for approximately 53 million LIN shares
has been extended to Oct. 13 despite LIN's September announcement
that it intended to merge with BellSouth.
   McCaw, LIN's largest shareholder with a 10 percent stake, has
been tendered more than 8 million LIN shares, said Tom Campo at
Adams &amp; Rinehart Inc., a New York public relations agency
representing McCaw.
   The Contel agreement would provide McCaw about $1.3 billion in
cash, or about $205 a ``pop,'' an industry yardstick obtained by
multiplying a market area population by the percentage ownership of
cellular systems serving the market.
   Each market is allowed two cellular franchises, one for the
local telephone company and one for an independent operation like
McCaw.
   The Contel agreement, which is subject to closing price
adjustments, would make the Contel Corp. subsidiary the nation's
seventh-largest cellular phone company, gaining controlling
cellular interests in 13 Southeastern markets, including Louisville
and Lexington, Ky.; Nashville, Memphis, Knoxville, Johnson City,
Chattanooga and Clarksville, Tenn.; and Birmingham, Tuscaloosa,
Florence, Anniston and Gadsden, Ala.
   The Metromedia deal covers about 6.8 million pops, and works out
to about $275 a pop. The Contel deal is about 6.1 million pops.
Atlanta-based Contel currently has about 14.4 million pops.
   These are ``two more steps toward achieving our longstanding
strategic objective of creating a national cellular network that
will give American consumers an independent alternative to
traditional providers of telephone service,'' McCaw Chairman Craig
O. McCaw said.
   He described Contel as ``a fellow independent with whom we have
had a long and mutually beneficial relationship.''
   McCaw, based in this Seattle suburb, operates in 127 areas with
a total of 50 million pops in 26 states, including major regional
systems along the West Coast and in the Rocky Mountains, Northeast,
Florida and Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
