<FIRST>r f PM-Harley-Davidson     10-04 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Harley-Davidson,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harley Vows to Stay Independent Despite Possible Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harley-Davidson Inc., the only remaining U.S.
motorcycle manufacturer, says it plans to stay independent despite
a possible takeover bid from an investor group holding a 6.24
percent stake in the company.
   Richard F. Teerlink, Harley's chief executive officer, said the
group headed by businessman Malcolm I. Glazer has had no contact
with the company.
   ``I don't know him or his intent,'' Teerlink said of Glazer in a
statement.
   However, Teerlink said Harley management, which repurchased the
company from AMF Inc. in 1981 and later took it public, wanted to
remain independent. Harley is the last remaining U.S. manufacturer
of motorcycles.
   In a filing Monday with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Glazer said he had purchased 488,200 shares, or 5.7 percent of
Harley's common stock. The filing said Glazer's six children each
controlled 8,500 shares of Harley for a family total of 6.24
percent.
   Glazer, of Rochester, N.Y., is chairman of First Allied Corp.,
which he said has interests in more than 30 companies in 12 states
with assets of more than $200 million.
   ``We invest in companies which we feel are significantly
undervalued, are leaders in their field, have strong brand name
recognition and exhibit tremendous future growth potential,''
Glazer said, adding that Harley had those qualifications.
   Teerlink confirmed that management controls a 10 percent stake
in the company, and he said Harley's anti-takeover measures include
a ``poison pill'' shareholder rights plan.
   When asked if the company would do anything differently to
increase the value of its stock, he replied, ``We think the way we
run the business enhances shareholder value well with a longterm
view.''
   Teerlink said he spoke Tuesday to Harris Associates of Chicago,
Harley's largest stockholder with a 12.9 percent interest, but he
declined to comment on what was discussed.
   Harley stock rose $3.62{ to $42.75 in New York Stock Exchange
composite trading Tuesday.
   Harley is best known for its heavyweight motorcycles built for
highway travel and favored by many law enforcement agencies.
</TEXT>
