<HEAD>London Shares Lower At Midday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: will be led after closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices slipped at midday Wednesday as an
initial surge was turned back by nervousness over the pound.
   At 12:15 p.m. local time, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was down 3.8 points at 2,314.9, off its early surge
of 2,331.1.
   Midday volume totaled 316.5 million shares, compared with 338.1
million the same time Tuesday.
   Dealers said shares were buoyed early by Wall Street's strength
on Tuesday, but jitters over the outlook for sterling got the upper
hand.
   Sterling fell against the West German mark, raising concerns
that the government would push up interest rates to support the
pound.
   The market is awaiting the outcome of Thursday's meeting of the
Deutsche Bundesbank central bank council.
   Many traders are expecting a half-point hike in key West German
interest rates to come out of the meeting, although some analysts
said such a move already was fully discounted by the market.
