<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1126EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Braniff     10-04 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Braniff,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Executive Predicts Braniff Will Survive as Smaller Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deregulation has hurt smaller, independent
airlines while favoring larger carriers, a top executive of Braniff
Inc. told aviation executives as his cash-starved airline tries to
rebuild as a smaller carrier.
   Tom Volz, Braniff's senior vice president for marketing, blamed
the carrier's troubles on the government's 1978 deregulation of the
nation's airline industry. Braniff, based in Orlando, filed last
week for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization and protection from
creditors _ its second such filing in seven years.
   Frequent-flier tickets are a particular source of unfair
competition, Volz told about 300 aviation executives attending the
Transport Aircraft Marketing Symposium in Orlando Tuesday.
   Although he said he doesn't favor a return to tight regulation
of the industry, Volz suggested that the government should consider
ordering an end to frequent-flier programs, which he said allow
unfair competition.
   Because of its smaller size, Braniff's frequent-flier program
was not started until after those of the larger airlines, Volz
said, and wasn't able to catch up.
   Volz said small airlines such as Braniff also were damaged by
travel agents he described as being ``locked in'' by the suppliers
of their computerized reservation systems. Those systems, he noted,
either are owned outright _ or jointly _ by the big airlines.
   Between 1978 and 1988, he said, the number of U.S. airlines
dropped from 36 to 28, while the carriers' combined profit fell to
$600 million from $1 billion, and 200 airlines filed for bankruptcy
or halted operations.
   Although Braniff has run out of cash, it hopes to remain aloft
as a smaller airline with hubs in Orlando and Kansas City, Mo., and
reduced service to ``spoke'' cities, Volz said.
   Kansas City will remain the airline's primary hub because of its
central location, Volz said, and Orlando will continue as a hub
because it is one of the fastest-growing areas in the nation.
   Passengers from feeder, or spoke, cities will be flown to the
hubs to catch connecting flights.
   A new Braniff marketing program will start within two weeks,
emphasizing ``a smaller, independent airline with a lower price
range,'' Volz said. ``We'll have to be a boutique airline, offering
more for less.''
   Braniff resumed service this past weekend after halting nearly
all flights last Wednesday, the day before its bankruptcy filing.
The airline announced Tuesday that it operated all 46 scheduled
departures in 11 cities nationwide.
   Braniff also said it will continue to offer $99 one-way bargain
fares to all destinations through Oct. 31. The airline was
``booking up heavily under this deep discount offer,'' Volz said.
   About 2,000 employees out of Braniff's pre-strike workforce of
4,800 were on duty Tuesday. The company's Orlando workforce dropped
from 1,000 to 275.
   In 1982, Braniff filed for bankruptcy reorganization in Dallas,
where it was based at the time. The airline emerged from Chapter 11
protection in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
