<SECOND>BC-USAir,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir Reaches Agreement with Pilots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc. said it reached a
transitional agreement with the Air Line Pilots Association that
specifies flying hours, scheduling and job bidding rights for the
airline's 5,800 pilots.
   The agreement covers pilots who joined USAir in its August
merger with Piedmont Aviation as well as those who flew for USAir
previously.
   ``It will allow us to have much more flexibility in using
airplanes and crews, and take better advantage of the benefits of
our merger,'' USAir spokesman John Bronson said Tuesday.
   The agreement also puts USAir and Piedmont pilots on one
seniority list, said Chris Beebe, a spokesman for the pilots
union's Pittsburgh chapter.
   The agreement takes effect Jan. 1 and will remain in place until
a comprehensive contract is settled, Bronson said.
