<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-StockFraud     10-04 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Stock Fraud,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>RW Technology Settles Stock Fraud Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESHIRE, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RW Technology Inc. has agreed to repay
more than 600 investors the Securities and Exchange Commission
claims were defrauded when the company sold stock at inflated
prices.
   The SEC said the rubber and plastic manufacturer firm sold $5.1
million in unregistered common stock starting in 1987, telling
investors that the price of $2 to $9.75 per share was discounted,
the SEC said Tuesday.
   In fact, the stock could have been purchased over the counter
for 50 cents to $2 per share, the filing said.
   The filing also charged that company officers misled investors
about the company's growth potential, product development and
number of customers.
   In settling the case, RW neither admitted nor denied the
allegations and agreed to account for all funds received from
investors, offer detailed plans for making restitution and not
further violate securities laws.
   The amount of planned restitution to investors was not disclosed.
   RW makes Typlax, a rubber and plastic compound made from
recycled tires.
</TEXT>
