<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Coffee     10-04 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Coffee,0182</SECOND>
<UNK>World Coffee Price Hits 14-Year Low</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee prices plunged to 14-year lows on Wednesday
after an official expressed pessimism about efforts to restore
export quotas.
   On the London market, coffee for January delivery fell by $81.60
from Tuesday's close to $1,062.40 a metric ton, recovering later to
finish the day at $1,088.
   The International Coffee Organization's latest indicator of the
average price of coffee traded throughout the world, released
Wednesday, was 64.31 cents a pound, a level last seen in 1975.
   After accounting for inflation, the price of coffee in real
terms is now at its most depressed level since the 1920s, analysts
said.
   The latest price fall started Tuesday when Jorio Duaster,
Brazil's chief coffee executive, said there was no chance of an
early return of the International Coffee Organization's export
quota system to keep excess world production off the market.
   His remarks while attending a London meeting of the organization
on the problem appeared to dash hopes of early international action
to lift and stabilize the market.
</TEXT>
