<DOCNO> AP891004-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1509EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Kerkorian-Vegas Bjt   10-04 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kerkorian-Vegas, Bjt,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>Billionaire Has Always Had Grand Ideas for Gaming Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been 40 years since Kirk Kerkorian
refurbished a small twin-engine airplane and began shuttling
passengers between a Los Angeles suburb and the fledgling gaming
resort of Las Vegas.
   In the years since then, the shy son of Armenian immigrants has
built a billion-dollar business empire while forging grand designs
in the desert.
   Now he's embarking on his grandest yet _ an entertainment theme
park and his third shot at building the world's largest hotel.
   Kerkorian's announcement Tuesday of plans to build the $700
million project on the Las Vegas Strip is a case of promises kept.
   ``I'll be back,'' Kerkot the eight largest hotels in the world _ three
of them with the Kerkorian imprint.
   Kerkorian said Tuesday his MGM Grand Inc., will build the hotel
on a prime Strip corner now occupied by the Marina Hotel and Casino
and the Tropicana Country Club.
   ``I used the word `bullish' many years ago in talking about Las
Vegas,'' Kerkorian said. ``I'm still bullish on the city.''
   The 115-acre theme park, still in its conceptual and design
stage, will be a family attraction aimed at drawing middle-class
tourists when it opens sometime in late 1992.
   MGM Grand chairman Fred Benninger said his company is confident
the park will cash in on the trend toward family tourism in a town
once dominated by high-rolling gamblers.
   ``I remember the days when Las Vegas lived almost entirely on
the high roller,'' Benninger said Tuesday. ``You can't do that
anymore.''
   Kerkorian's company built the International Hotel, now the Las
Vegas Hilton, and later built the MGM Grand Hotel, now Bally's.
   The International had 1,500 rooms when it opened in 1967 as the
biggest resort in Las Vegas and the MGM surpassed that with 2,100
rooms when it was built in 1973.
   The Las Vegas Hilton now has 3,174 rooms and is the world's
largest hotel. That mark will be broken when the 4,032-room
Excalibur opens next June, across the Strip from Kerkorian's new
site.
   The Hilton's sister property, the Flamingo Hilton, will have
3,600 rooms when an expansion is completed next year. Kerkorian
once owned the Flamingo as well. And he owned the land on which
Caesars Palace was built.
   Kerkorian is expected to spend about $250 million on the new
hotel and $450 million on the theme park, which will include
facilities for film making.
   Some have compared Kerkorian with Howard Hughes, the reclusive
billionaire who once owned nine Nevada hotel casinos and whose
Summa Corp. still has vast real estate holdings in the Las Vegas
Valley. Both men had a penchant for the movie industry, gaming,
flying, Nevada, airlines _ and privacy.
   Kerkorian, the son of poor Armenian fruit farmers in Fresno,
Calif., dropped out of high school to help support his parents and
three brothers. He once attributed his business acumen to growing
up during the Depression years.
   ``I didn't have any really big motivation in my life,'' he once
said. ``First it was simply trying to earn enough to get something
to eat, then enough to buy a car.''
   In the late 1940s he refurbished a small plane and began
carrying gamblers, sightseers and wedding couples from the
Hawthorne, Calif. airport to Las Vegas.
   In 1947 he formed his own airline, Los Angeles Air Service,
which he later changed to Trans International Airlines. He sold the
airline to TransAmerica Corp. in 1968 in a deal that netted him
$104 million.
   By then he was in the hotel business in Las Vegas, the city that
``has always been on the plus side for us.''
   Today, Kerkorian's MGM Grand Inc., a separate company from his
MGM-UA Communications Corp., owns an all-frills Los Angeles-New
York airline as well as the Desert Inn. It also retains rights to a
stylized version of the famous MGM lion logo.
   Kerkorian, 72, had sold and bought back pieces of MGM-UA
Communications for two decades, a period during which he also
traded Las Vegas hotels the way most people buy cars.
   Last month, Australia's Qintex Group agreed to purchase MGM-UA _
including the original lion logo _ for $1.5 billion.
   Kerkorian continues to shun the spotlight and is reluctant to
talk about his business success.
   ``I'm just a small town boy who got lucky,'' he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891004-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-TankTumult Adv08   10-04 1087</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tank Tumult, Adv 08,1133</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Oct. 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Small Service Stations Squeezed By EPA Rules On Storage Tanks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A spray-painted tin sign over Aldo Ranieri's idle pumps hangs as
an epitaph to a once-thriving business: ``NO GAS.''
   Ranieri is one of more than 20,000 independent service station
owners nationwide likely to go out of business because of new
environmental safety rules concerning underground storage tanks.
   The potential closures represent almost a fifth of all U.S.
gasoline retail outlets, threatening to significantly narrow
competition and raise prices, particularly in rural areas.
   Federal officials say the rules are aimed at protecting the
environment from underground leaks that could contaminate water
supplies.
   That's no consolation to people like Ranieri, who cannot afford
the enormous cost of replacing and insuring his tanks. ``Help,
that's what I need, help,'' Ranieri says.
   After 25 years of pumping gasoline at the same location in an
affluent Westchester County suburb of New York, Ranieri says state
officials forced him to stop selling gasoline four months ago when
he refused to have his tanks tested at a cost of several thousand
dollars.
   He has since laid off all but two employees, who continue to
repair cars in the garage.
   The federal regulations require service station owners to
replace or upgrade underground tanks by 1998. Before then they must
test their tanks, install leak detection devices and prove, through
pollution liability insurance or other means, that they can pay
damages if there's a leak.
   Oct. 26 is the deadline for owners of between 100 and 999 tanks
to have $1 million in insurance coverage to pay for possible leaks.
   Those who opt not to take the $1 million insurance generally
must be able to show they have a minimum net worth of $10 million
to cover the cost of cleaning a leak.
   With annual premiums more than doubling from an average of
$25,356 in 1986 to $66,064 in 1989, industry officials say many
station owners will not be able to comply by the deadline.
   ``Fifty-five percent of the people who should have insurance by
Oct. 26 won't and the situation is getting worse,'' says Phillip R.
Chisholm, executive vice president of the Petroleum Marketers
Association of America.
   A joint survey by three trade associations representing U.S.
gasoline marketers _ the petroleum marketers, the National
Association of Convenience Stores and the Society of Independent
Gasoline Marketers _ found that about 37,000 retailers with 100,000
tanks will likely miss the October deadline.
   Smaller owners like Ranieri, who own only a few tanks, have
until October 1990 to get coverage. But they face a December
deadline for testing tanks and installing leak detectors.
   Ranieri says he has asked Texaco Inc. for help, since he sells
the company's brand under a franchise, but has been turned down.
He's now seeking a buyer.
   Texaco concedes it has no program to help independent tank
owners.
   ``It's their responsibility,'' said Texaco spokesman Gary
Taylor. He said Texaco is considering assisting wholesalers with
insurance costs.
   The Petroleum Marketers Association estimates that at least
26,250 of the nation's 150,000 gasoline stations could close over
the next few years as a result of the Environmental Protection
Agency rules.
   Ranieri says his tanks are at least 30 years old and need
replacing. He estimates the cost could exceed $200,000 including
compliance with state regulations that require installation of
anti-vapor safety nozzles.
   ``I'm a little guy. For me to survive I have to replace the
tanks. I don't have the money,'' he says.
   Across the street at a Mobil station, business has picked up
since Ranieri's pumps closed. One recent weekday morning, a stream
of cars pulled in and out almost nonstop. The few unwary motorists
who drove into Ranieri's Texaco glimpsed the sign then wheeled over
to the Mobil pumps.
   ``They're busy all the time,'' Ranieri says. ``I'm too small to
fight. I can't fight the big guys.''
   Owners of 1,000 or more tanks such as Mobil Corp., which
operates the Mobil station, had to be in compliance by last
January. Most large oil companies already are self insured.
   Since the rules went into effect last December, all tank owners
are required to start testing the estimated 2 million underground
oil and gasoline tanks nationwide. Up to half are believed to
contain hazardous contaminants such as lead.
   ``Nobody is questioning the need for this,'' says Ron Brand,
director of EPA's underground storage tank program. ``The issue is
who pays, not whether we need it.''
   Older storage tanks are made of carbon steel, which corrodes,
and have typical design lives of 15-20 years. Products stored in
leaky or corroding tanks seep into water and underground wells.
   Tanks installed since 1985 had to be constructed of protected
steel, fiberglass or a sturdy composite, with non-corroding pipes.
   Jim McCormick, director of EPA's Policy and Standards Division
for underground storage tanks, says that leak damage often is
underestimated.
   ``They're not Love Canals, they're much smaller but there are
lots more of them,'' McCormick says.
   Up to 30 percent of the tanks could be leaking, although there
is no reliable estimate of the extent of environmental harm,
McCormick says.
   States such as California and Florida, which started testing
earlier than others, have found evidence of widespread leaks that
range in size from trickles to thousands of gallons.
   EPA officials say they are trying to ease the burden of the new
regulations by phasing in the rules and giving special
consideration to problem cases.
   One provision, for example, enables EPA Commissioner William K.
Reilly to suspend enforcement of the insurance deadline for six
months if coverage is not available, Brand says.
   But tank owners should not depend on the provision, Brand says,
because ``we don't have evidence that it's not available.''
   The petroleum marketers group has asked the EPA to suspend the
compliance date for one year, arguing that many insurance companies
remain reluctant to provide coverage before tanks are upgraded.
Other insurers require $100,000 deductibles, Chisholm says.
   Industry sources say that some banks also are reluctant to lend
money for tank upgrades because they consider it a high-risk loan,
so many tank owners are in a Catch 22 situation.
   While some states are coming to the rescue by establishing trust
funds to help owners upgrade tanks and cover the major portion of
spills, only a few have been approved by the EPA so far.
   ``The way I see it I'm out of business,'' says Ranieri.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Oct. 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
