<FIRST>u f BC-NWA     10-04 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-NWA,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Checchi Says He Won't Add Partner in NWA Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Alfred A. Checchi says he won't get
a new partner to make up the $225 million from KLM Royal Dutch
Airlines that the federal government ruled out as part of the
takeover of NWA Inc. by a Checchi-led group.
   The Transportation Department last week gave Checchi six months
to cut KLM's investment to $175 million from $400 million, which
had been the largest equity contribution to the deal to buy NWA,
the parent of Northwest Airlines.
   The department said it was worried that KLM could control the
airline even though it held only 5 percent of Northwest's shares.
   In an interview with the Los Angeles Times published Wednesday,
Checchi said, ``I'm not entertaining the thought of taking on
another partner. That wouldn't make sense.''
   Instead, the Los Angeles financier said, he plans to repay KLM
the $225 million from Northwest's cash flow, or by issuing
nonvoting preferred stock, or possibly by letting employees buy
into the company.
   NWA already has reduced its takeover-related debt from $3.35
billion to $3.1 billion, said Checchi.
   The group led by Checchi, including KLM and other investors,
bought NWA for $3.65 billion in June. Checchi replaced Steven
Rothmeier as NWA chairman last week.
</TEXT>
