<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1628EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Senate-Fed     10-04 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Fed,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Members Back Fed's Independence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee
and its senior Republican on Wednesday reassured the Federal
Reserve Board that they would oppose efforts to weaken the central
bank's independence.
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., the panel's chairman, noted
several proposals introduced in the House that would give the
administration more control of the Fed, which influences the
nation's economy by manipulating interest rates.
   The seven Fed members are appointed by the president. But the
chairman serves a four-year term and can't be removed by the
president. Other members are appointed to 14-year terms.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., chairman of the Joint Economics
Committee, has proposed legislation adding the treasury secretary
to the Fed board. Other House members are proposing other changes,
including adding representatives of farmers, builders, consumers
and small-business people to the board.
   Riegle, at a hearing reviewing the government's savings and loan
bailout, called Hamilton's proposal, ``probably not a sound one.''
   ``I would be reluctant to make any moves politicizing the Fed,''
he told Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   Riegle was backed by Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, the senior
Republican on the banking committee.
   ``Let the members of the House fiddle around with it all they
want. Let me suggest there aren't going to be any changes like that
on the Senate side,'' Garn said.
</TEXT>
