<FIRST>r f BC-AZT-Syrup     10-04 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AZT-Syrup,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burroughs Wellcome to Make AZT Available in Syrup Form</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RESEARCH TRIANGLE PARK, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burroughs Wellcome Co. has
introduced its anti-AIDS drug in a strawberry-flavored syrup to
help patients who have difficulty swallowing.
   The syrup form of Retrovir _ the brand name for AZT _ is
expected to be available in pharmacies within four to six weeks,
company officials say.
   ``This new formulation should provide more flexibility in making
dosage adjustments and be particularly useful to patients who have
difficulty swallowing capsules for a variety of reasons, including
lesions in the throat and mouth,'' said Kathryn H. Pattishall,
project leader for Retrovir at Burroughs Wellcome.
   Kathy Bartlett, a spokewoman for Burroughs Wellcome, said the
syrup would also help doctors adjust the dosage.
   AZT capsules were approved by the Food and Drug Administration
in March 1987, and the syrup received approval last month.
   AZT was rushed into production in 1986 after only nine months of
clinical tests, when preliminary results showed 8 percent of
patients died while taking the drug, compared with 40 percent in a
similar test group not given the drug.
   AZT is the only drug approved by the FDA that directly combats
the AIDS virus. Burroughs Wellcome last month cut its wholesale
price by 20 percent in response to complaints that the retail
price, $7,000 to $8,000 for a year's treatment, was too high.
</TEXT>
