<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1723EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DefenseElectronics     10-04 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Defense Electronics,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Electronics Should Prosper Despite Pentagon Cuts, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Within 10 years, Pentagon spending will
return to its level before the Reagan administration's defense
buildup, according to a study by leaders of the defense electronics
industry.
   But defense electronics will still get a healthy cut of defense
funds, said officials of the Electronics Industries Association,
meeting in Los Angeles.
   ``Defense electronics, despite a declining overall budget, is
holding its own as a quality enhancer for most weapon systems,''
said Geoffrey K. Bentley, chairman of an EIA subcommittee that
compiled the organization's annual 10-year forecast. ``In fact,
over the 10-year period, defense electronics will show real
growth.''
   Industry officials presented the study Tuesday at the
conference, which attracted more than 350 defense industry
executives and managers from across the country.
   The 90-page study, drawn from interviews with industry
executives, congressional sources, Pentagon officials, academics
and Wall Street analysts, says inflation will outpace the overall
defense budget.
   Although the budget is expected to reach as much as $375 billion
by the end of the 1990s, it will actually shrink 1.5 percent when
adjusted for inflation in 1990 dollars, Bentley said.
   ``We are looking at 12 straight years of real decline, which
will bring us back to the early Reagan years and fiscal 1981,'' he
said.
   Officials warned, however, that a loss of power by Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev and a return by the Soviet Union to
policies of the past could result in a change in the entire
equation.
   Barring such a change, cutbacks in big-ticket items such as
military personnel, missiles, tanks and aircraft appear inevitable,
association officials said. But military spending will remain
strong for defense electronics in areas such as space,
communications equipment, high-tech improvements in missiles and
aircraft and other weaponry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
