<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     10-04 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Sales Up, Spurred by GM Trucks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of North American-built cars and trucks by
the nation's Big Three automakers jumped 10 percent in late
September, due in large part to a 45.3 percent rise in General
Motors Corp. truck sales, the companies said Wednesday.
   For the entire model year, which ended Sept. 30, combined sales
of cars and trucks assembled in North America by GM, Ford Motor Co.
and Chrysler Corp. were up a more modest 0.1 percent compared with
the previous year, which proved to be the third-best model year on
record for automakers as a whole.
   The companies said they sold vehicles at an average daily rate
of 42,407 during the Sept. 21-30 period this year, compared with a
daily rate of 38,550 during the same time last year.
   Car sales rose 7.2 percent and truck sales, fueled by the big GM
increase, rose 14.8 percent.
   In September, GM was offering its dealers incentives to sell the
company's trucks, including pickups, sport-utility vehicles and
minivans. That helped push GM's light truck sales for the entire
month up 42.3 percent over September 1988. For the model year, GM
trucks sales were up 6.1 percent over last year.
   For the model year, which began Oct. 1, 1988, truck sales by the
Big Three were up 2.2 percent, offsetting a 1.1 percent decline in
car sales.
   GM also posted strong late-September car sales figures, rising
13.7 percent to an average daily sales rate of 14,660 during the
period this year from a rate of 12,892 last year.
   For the first nine months of the 1989 calendar year, GM's car
sales were down 5.6 percent and for the model year, car sales were
up 3.2 percent.
   While GM was gaining truck sales in late September, Ford was
losing. The nation's No. 2 automaker said its late-September light
truck sales were off 9 percent. For the calendar year, Ford's truck
sales were down 2.1 percent and for the model year, they were off
1.8 percent.
   Ford's car sales were up 6 percent in late September and 0.2
percent for the calendar year. For the 1989 model year, Ford's car
sales were up 3.2 percent.
   Chrysler, like GM, showed an increase in truck sales, but not
nearly as dramatic. Chrysler said its late-September light truck
sales were up 6 percent over the same time last year, and up 0.1
for the calendar year to date. For the model year, truck sales were
up 1.6 percent.
   Chrysler's car sales dropped 12.6 percent in late September,
and, through Sept. 30 of this calendar year, the company's car
sales were off 11.2 percent. For the just-ended model year,
Chrysler's car sales were down 7.5 percent compared with last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
