<HEAD>Gasoline Futures Sink; Crude Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline futures prices tumbled Wednesday after
the American Petroleum Institute said inventories had risen by 4.5
million barrels last week.
   The API report released late Tuesday showed total gasoline
stocks at 223.7 million barrels for the week ending last Friday.
Analysts said the bearish report drove prices downward.
   The November contract for unleaded gasoline on the New York
Mercantile Exchange lost 1.23 cents a gallon to 55.41 cents.
Subsequent months also lost ground, with the December contract
falling 0.91 cents a gallon to 54.17 cents.
   The increase in gasoline inventories was slightly above
expectations, said Andrew Lebow, energy futures analyst for E.D.&amp;F.
Man International Futures Inc.
   Home heating oil futures traded on the mercantile exchange also
fell. The November contract for heating oil was down 0.69 cents a
gallon to close at 58.99 cents. Subsequent months also fell, though
by less.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude oil, gained 2 cents to close at $20.15 per
42-gallon barrel on the mercantile exchange. Contracts for later
months fell slightly.
   Analysts said little influenced the price of crude as the weekly
API report showed an expected increase in stocks of 1.7 million
barrels to 333.3 million barrels.
