<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     10-04 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Sink To New 14-Year Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   World coffee prices sank to new 14-year lows Wednesday amid
deepening pessimism about the prospects for a return to the
price-support measures abandoned by the International Coffee
Organization in July.
   On other commodity markets, sugar futures climbed sharply,
precious metals were higher, energy futures mostly were lower and
grain and livestock futures were mixed.
   Coffee futures settled 2.5 cents to 3.7 cents lower on New
York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange with the contract for
delivery in December at 73.03 cents a pound, the lowest settlement
for a near-month coffee contract since late 1975.
   The International Coffee Organization's latest indicator of the
average price of coffee traded throughout the world, released
Wednesday, was 64.31 cents a pound, also a 14-year low.
   Market analysts called the sell-off a continuation of Tuesday's
steep slide, which was triggered when Jorio Dauster, Brazil's chief
coffee executive, said there was no chance of an early return to an
export quota system designed to keep excess world production off
the market.
   A new coffee agreement is impossible without support from
Brazil, the world's largest coffee producer.
   Coffee futures prices have plunged about 36 percent in the three
months since the ICO suspended the quotas because of
dissatisfaction among its largest consumer members, including the
United States.
   Dauster made his remarks at an ICO meeting in London that is
scheduled to end Friday. Key producer members of the 74-nation
group reportedly were drafting a resolution Wednesday on how to
proceed with negotiations on a new agreement but analysts said they
expected no movement in the near future.
   ``Unless it's radical surgery, it's difficult to see how
anything that comes out of the meeting in London is anything more
than window dressing,'' said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Many analysts predicted prices would drop further. But some said
roaster buying for the winter season, when coffee consumption
reaches its annual peak, should surface within the next two weeks
to slow or halt the slide.
   World sugar futures soared on the Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange
amid indications that India had made a major sugar purchase. Sugar
settled .31 cent to .75 cent higher with January at 13.85 cents a
pound.
   Gold and silver futures posted modest gains in quiet trading on
New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 20 cents higher with October at $367 a
troy ounce; silver was 2.8 cents to 3.1 cents higher with December
at $5.328 a troy ounce.
   Gasoline led most energy futures lower on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in reaction to Tuesday's weekly American
Petroleum Institute report showing increased U.S. supplies of
crude, gasoline and petroleum distillates.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents lower to 2
cents higher with November at $20.15 a barrel; heating oil was .10
cent to .69 cent lower with November at 58.99 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .40 cent to 1.23 cents lower with November at
55.41 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade as harvest-related selling offset buying linked to new export
sales of U.S. wheat and corn.
   Wheat futures settled { cent lower to 2 cents higher with
December at $4.09\ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to { cent
higher with December at $2.39 a bushel; oats were { cent to 1{
cents lower with December at $1.46\ a bushel; soybeans were 1}
cents lower to } cent higher with November at $5.76{ a bushel.
   Profit-taking pressured pork futures on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange while slack beef demand weighed on live cattle futures.
But strong cash markets boosted feeder cattle.
   Live cattle settled unchanged to .30 cent lower with October at
71.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .40 cent higher
with October at 83.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .63
cent lower with October at 44.77 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .33 cent to .88 cent lower with February at 48.17 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
