<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1753EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-04 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Mixed; Gold Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed against major currencies in
fairly quiet trading Wednesday with traders cautious ahead of the
meeting of West Germany's central bank.
   Some analysts expect the Bundesbank to raise its key lending
rates when it meets Thursday in an effort to push the dollar lower.
Its discount rate now stands at 5 percent and the Lombard rate is
at 7 percent.
   ``All eyes are watching the Bundesbank tomorrow,'' said Ronald
Holzer, chief currency broker for Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago.
   West Germany is one of seven industrial nations, including the
United States, that have joined in a concerted effort to weaken the
dollar.
   Analysts said that if intervention fails the backup plan is for
some countries to raise their interest rates.
   Higher West German interest rates would make mark-denominated
assets more attractive than dollar holdings and would tend to boost
the mark against the U.S. dollar.
   If the Bundesbank decides to raise interest rates other central
banks probably will follow, analysts said.
   ``If the Germans do it, it will be a matter of time before Japan
does it not only to show coordinated effort politically but also to
bolster the yen,'' said Jack Barbanel, currency analyst with First
Global Asset Management.
   Some analysts said the currency markets have already come to
expect a half-percentage-point rise so the Bundesbank will have to
kick rates higher to lower the dollar.
   ``If they raise it only a half-percentage-point it will take a
lot of the sparkle out of the Deutsche mark and other currencies
that it has appreciated against,'' Holzer said.
   Central banks began their intervention more than a week ago
after a meeting of the Group of Seven industrialized nations in
which they agreed that the dollar's recent rise was
``inconsistent'' with longer-run economic fundamentals. They are
the United States, Britain, Japan, France, West Germany, Italy and
Canada.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.05 yen to a closing 140.60 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 141.05 yen. In New York, the
dollar traded at 141.475, up from 141.20 late Tuesday.
   In London, the pound traded at $1.6055, unchanged from late
Tuesday. In New York trading the dollar strengthened as the pound
changed hands at $1.6020, down from $1.6045 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8815 West German marks, down from 1.8865; 1.6290
Swiss francs, down from 1.6350; 1.17475 Canadian dollars, down from
1.17495; 6.3825 French francs, down from 6.4000; and 1,376.75
Italian lire, down from 1,379.65.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Tuesday's prices,
included: 1.8770 West German marks, down from 1.8865; 1.6275 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6350; 6.3700 French francs, down from 6.4005;
2.1185 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1195; 1,373.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,380.50; and 1.1742 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1763.
   Gold traded in London late Wednesday at $366.25 per troy ounce,
up slightly from late Tuesday's $365.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $366, up from $365.25 late Tuesday.
Gold closed in Hong Kong unchanged at $366.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $367 an ounce, up from $366.30 on Tuesday.
Republic National bank of New York said gold was bid late in the
day at $366 an ounce, up from $365.50 on Tuesday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.24 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.22.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled
at $5.248 an ounce, up from Tuesday's close of $5.217.
</TEXT>
