<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1809EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-LiquorTax 1stLd-Writethru   10-04 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liquor Tax, 1st Ld-Writethru,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Repeal Little-Known Tax on Liquor Retailers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS percentage increase in 5th graf: ``Although the,''
from 463 percent to 363 percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill approved by the Senate Finance
Committee early Wednesday would give more than 100 years of amnesty
to fraternal groups, taverns and convenience stores for past-due
levies under a little-known tax on liquor retailers.
   Protests over the tax had grown after a Pennsylvania Elks lodge
got a $9,000 bill for 50 years of non-payment.
   The measure would prohibit the federal government from
collecting unpaid balances and penalties on the 123-year-old tax if
they accrued before Jan. 1, 1985, according to Sen. John Heinz,
R-Pa.
   Heinz, a member of the committee, argued successfully to get the
provision included in a sweeping budget bill. Both the provision
and the bill were approved on voice votes.
   Although the tax has been in the books since 1866, the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms says that up to 40 percent of
retailers never heard of it until the agency began a vigorous
collection effort last year. The crackdown began after Congress
raised the yearly tax 363 percent, from $54 to $250 for each
establishment.
   Heinz estimated his amendment would cost the government about $2
million per year in lost revenues through the 1994 fiscal year.
   According to bureau spokesman Jack Killorin, the list of
organizations liable for the tax includes some country clubs,
lodges, limousine operators and even bait and tackle shops _ any
organization that sells beer, wine and distilled spirits directly
to the public. In all, Killorin estimates that 600,000
organizations must pay the ``special occupational tax.''
   Responsibility for collections shifted to jthe Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms in 1986 from the Internal Revenue
Service. Killorin said in a recent interview that the bureau was
working with states to make certain retailers aware of their
obligations. He said the agency was willing to negotiate payment
plans so retailers can get their debt paid off.
   Opposition to the collection effort gained momentum in Congress
after Elks Lodge 109 in Wilkes-Barre, Pa., received a bill 11
months ago for $9,776.98 from the bureau, representing unpaid taxes
and penalties back to 1940 when the lodge got its liquor license.
   The Elks, who said they had never heard of the tax, complained
to Rep. Paul Kanjorski, D-Pa., who said in an interview Wednesday
that he has been fighting for a statute of limitations on the tax
because the establishments being dunned include ``the small tap
rooms, the private clubs _ people who can least afford to pay a tax
they knew nothing about for years and years.''
   Bureau spokeswoman Dot Koester said Wednesday that the agency
was taking no position on the Senate committee action. ``Whatever
Congress passes, we'll enforce. It won't be a problem for us,'' she
said.
   The Pennsylvania Elks lodge, which is celebrating its 100th
anniversary, recently settled with the bureau for $844.12, lodge
attorney Peter Paul Olszewski said Wednesday. The lodge argued that
it had not been open and functioning during part of the period for
which it was being taxed.
   But if the committee-passed provision becomes law, Olszewski
said the lodge might petition ATF for a refund.
   ``You can call this the `Elks Lodge Bill.' I think there would
be a tremendous amount of satisfaction to see Congress remedy an
administrative problem,'' Olszewski said
   Heinz's amendment was included in a sweeping bill designed to
make changes in the law to achieve the budget target set by
Congress at the beginning of the fiscal year. Heinz said in a
statement Wednesday that the provision ``provides reasonable relief
to many retailers, most of whom are small businesses and had no
intention of evading a tax.''
   The House Ways and Means Committee failed to include a provision
similar to Heinz's in its corresponding bill. Assuming passage by
the Senate, the matter would be resolved by a House-Senate
conference committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
