<DOCNO> AP891004-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 1813EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     10-04 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government bond prices finished slightly lower
Wednesday as trading slowed in advance of an important economic
report later this week on employment in September.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond lost 1-16 point, or about
63 cents for every $1,000 in face amount. Its yield held steady at
8.16 percent, unchanged from late Tuesday.
   Corporate issues also dipped, but tax-exempt municipals advanced.
   Market watchers said dealings were listless for most of the day
as traders were reluctant to make large commitments to either buy
or sell bonds in advance of Friday's scheduled release of the
September employment report.
   Some analysts were looking for payroll growth of about 275,000
compared with growth of about 110,000 in August.
   That would suggest continued vitality in the economy and some
analysts said they doubted that the Federal Reserve Board would
adjust its monetary policy as a result of that type of figure.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of
short-term, intermediate and long-term governments were all down by
between 1-16 point and 3-32 point, the Telerate Inc. financial
information service reported.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, lost 0.72 to 1,174.05.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities
of five years or longer, fell 0.08 to 329.70.
   But in the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40
actively traded municipal bonds rose 3-16 to 92[. The average yield
to maturity fell to 7.38 percent from 7.40 percent late Tuesday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 8.04 percent as the
discount gained 3 basis points to 7.78 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 8.30 percent as the discount advanced 4 basis points
to 7.87 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8.38 percent as
the discount rose 2 basis points to 7.79 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 8\ percent, down from 9 percent late Tuesday.
   But analysts said the relatively low funds rate was due to
technical conditions in the short-term market for bank borrowings
as Wednesday marked the end of a bank reserve reporting period.
</TEXT>
