<FIRST>r f BC-IntegratedResources     10-04 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Integrated Resources,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Selling Unit to Met Life for Undisclosed Price</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc., a financial services
company struggling because of heavy debts, said Wednesday it has
agreed to sell its United Resources subsidiary to the Metropolitan
Life Insurance Co. for an undisclosed amount.
   Announcement of the sale marked another step in Integrated's
plans to sell its businesses in order to raise cash for debt
obligations. In August, the company said it was selling four other
subsidiaries to the family-owned Whitehall Financial Group
partnership for about $310 million.
   United Resources provides retirement and financial programs to
more than 3,000 institutions and more than 70,000 individuals
employed in public school systems, colleges, nonprofit
organizations and the health care industry.
   In a statement about the sale, Met Life said that it also was
acquiring a segment of Integrated's flexible annuity operation,
with assets totaling $565 million, also for an undisclosed price.
   Integrated, a former high-flying real estate and insurance
concern, has faced increasing troubles repaying its debt, which
totals about $1.75 billion. In June the company defaulted on $955
million in short-term obligations and declared a moratorium on all
debt payments while it restructured.
   Met Life is one of the biggest U.S. insurance and financial
service concerns, with more than $125 billion of assets under
management.
