<FIRST>u f AM-NewspaperWar     10-04 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspaper War,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Times Herald Asks FCC to Revoke Belo Station's License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dallas Times Herald turned to federal
regulators Wednesday in its war with rival Dallas Morning News,
asking them to revoke the license of a television station owned by
the parent company of The Morning News.
   The Times Herald asked the Federal Communications Commission to
revoke WFAA-TV's license because of A.H. Belo Corp.'s ``naked and
unjustifiable'' actions in stripping the Times Herald of 26 popular
features it had been purchasing from Universal Press Syndicate.
   Belo General Counsel Michael McCarthy declined to comment on the
action, citing the Times Herald's pending lawsuit on some of the
same issues. ``We fully expect to be vindicated in trial,'' he said.
   As part of a joint venture between Belo and Universal Press, the
larger Morning News won exclusive right in the Dallas market to the
syndicate's features, which include Doonesbury, Erma Bombeck and
Dear Abby.
   The Times Herald has lost previous attempts in federal and state
court to block the action, and most of the features have begun
appearing in The Morning News. A trial on the Times Herald's
antitrust suit against Belo and Universal is pending in state
District Court.
   ``Belo has used its newspaper-television combination to engage
in conduct that severely undermines competition between the Dallas
Morning News and the Dallas Times Herald,'' says the petition to
the FCC.
   The FCC has outlawed joint newspaper-television ownership since
1975, but allowed such ownership to continue in Dallas and other
cities where it already was in place.
   WFAA is the leading television station in the Dallas-Fort Worth
market.
   Under the joint venture announced in August, Belo and Universal
agreed to explore television programming possibilities for some of
the syndicate's features, and Belo President James P. Sheehan
described the exclusivity clause as ``really secondary.''
   The Times Herald's FCC petition said the joint venture ``is
nothing more than a sham to cover Belo's real agenda, the
elimination of its only competitor in the Dallas newspaper market.''
   The petition says Belo's $1 million payment to Universal Press
for the features ``suggests that Belo is paying not for the right
to produce new video products, but rather for a monopoly of the
Dallas newspaper market.''
   Times Herald Publisher John Buzzetta said the petition was filed
reluctantly.
   ``We like competition, but we want to compete fairly and
honestly and insist that our competitor do the same,'' Buzzetta
said in a news release.
   The two papers have fought bitterly during the past few years,
even challenging each other's circulation figures in court.
   Edyth Wise, chief of the complaints and investigations branch in
the enforcement division of FCC, said ``we operate totally on a
complaint basis. Every action (on revocation) is on the basis of a
complaint, by listeners and frequently by competitors.''
   A complaint by a newspaper against a television station,
however, ``frankly that's unusual,'' she said, ``although they're
free to do it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
