<FIRST>r f AM-DanRiver     10-04 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dan River,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seasoned Textile Executive Buys Dan River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan River Inc., a textile company with
7,000 employees and four plants in the Danville area, is being sold
to an investment group headed by Joseph Lanier, officials announced
Wednesday.
   Lanier, a veteran textile executive from West Point, Ga.,
declined to name the price paid for Dan River. The company, more
than 100 years old, is saddled with an estimated $50 million debt
from an attempted hostile takeover in 1983 that forced the company
to purchase its own stock and become privately held.
   Lanier and Lester Hudson, president and chief executive of Dan
River, issued a statement saying an all-cash transaction was agreed
to by the company, the trustee of the employee stock ownership plan
and an acquisition company headed by Lanier.
   They plan to complete the sale of Dan River by the end of the
month.
   Hudson said the transaction ``will provide the company with the
capital necessary to further modernize and expand our Danville
facilities.'' Dan River began a $25 million home fashions
modernization at its nearby Schoolfield plant last year.
   Hudson said Lanier, 57, has a proven record of success with West
Point-Pepperell Inc. Lanier built West Point-Pepperell into the
owner of some of the textile and apparel industry's most famous
brand names before he was ousted as head of the company in February
during a hostile takeover by Farley Inc.
   Lanier, the fourth generation of his family to run what began in
1890 as West Point Manufacturing Co., said of Dan River: ``It is a
fine company with a good name and has a dedicated group of
employees. The future of Dan River is bright.''
   Both men said the company name will not be changed and that Dan
River will continue to be based in Danville.
</TEXT>
