<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-UAL-Machinists     10-04 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UAL-Machinists,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Shun United Buyout Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines' largest union, the
Machinists, on Wednesday formally rejected an offer to join the
proposed $6.75 billion pilot-management buyout of United's parent
company.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers had repeatedly expressed its opposition to the proposed
leveraged buyout of Chicago-based UAL Corp. by its employees and
management, saying it could endanger the nation's second-largest
airline. But it had not issued a formal answer until the
announcement from vice president John Peterpaul.
   ``After a thorough study of the proposed plan and after meeting
with company officials, the IAM will go forth with normal
negotiations as it would with any other carrier,'' Peterpaul said.
``We do not feel that IAM members' interest would be well served by
participating in the ESOP (employee stock ownership plan) program.''
   The Machinists union represents 25,000 of UAL's 70,000
employees. Its contract becomes amendable at the end of this month.
   United said in a statement that the Machinists' decision was
consistent with its ``previously announced and often repeated
position.''
   But the company said the IAM decision ``does not change the
benefits that flow to United's employees from ownership of their
company _ benefits we hope will be shared by all employees.''
   And the company indicated it would continue to woo Machinists
members, saying ``we would welcome the participation of our
employees represented by the IAM, and are prepared to continue to
explore ways to achieve that objective.''
   The $300-a-share plan calls for UAL workers to own 75 percent of
the company. A management group headed by UAL Chairman Stephen M.
Wolf would own 10 percent and the remaining 15 percent would be
held by British Airways PLC.
   The total cost of the buyout, including financing charges, could
reach $9.45 billion, according to documents filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission by pilots and management.
</TEXT>
