<FILEID>AP-NR-10-04-89 2318EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FarmersGroup-Goldsmith     10-04 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Farmers Group-Goldsmith,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Goldsmith Bid To Block Review of BAT Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Sir James Goldsmith lost another round
Wednesday in his attempt to block state regulators from reviewing
his $21.1 billion bid for BAT Industries PLC, the British parent of
Farmer's Group Insurance Inc. and several U.S. retailers.
   U.S. District Judge John A. Nordberg refused to block the
Illinois insurance director's review of the hostile takeover
attempt, said Farmers spokesman Jeffrey Beyer.
   Los Angeles-based Farmers, the 15th-largest insurance holding
company in the United States, operates in nine states. Insurance
regulators in those states are reviewing BAT's proposed takeover to
assure it is in the best interest of policyholders.
   Federal judges in California, Idaho, Kansas, Texas and
Washington have denied similar requests by Goldsmith's company,
Holyake Investments, for preliminary injunctions blocking review in
those states.
   Goldsmith contends state regulators have no constitutional right
to review a foreign takeover. His spokesmen have said he intends to
appeal the rulings.
   As part of Goldsmith's proposal, Farmers Group would be sold to
Ax Midi Assurance, a large French insurer, for $4.5 billion.
</TEXT>
